前言

Foreword

思考的终结

The End of Thinking

1.

1.

一家全球最大的医疗科技公司，一位高管坐在摆满白板的会议室里。投影仪屏幕上，幻灯片快速闪过。近十年来，这位执行副总裁所在的部门一直保持两位数的增速，并在糖尿病护理产品市场稳居领先地位。然而，今年，该部门却第三次未能达成销售目标。几个月前，他启动了一项广泛的市场调研，试图找出原因。营销人员对美国和欧洲各地数千名糖尿病患者进行了调查，衡量了数百个影响他们服药依从性的不同因素。他了解到，“43% 的 2 型糖尿病患者不服药，而 84% 的不服药患者表示健忘是他们不服药的主要原因。” 董事会对他破口大骂之前，公司只有很短的时间来扭转局面，这位执行副总裁怒不可遏。“我们已经知道，患者不服药是因为他们健忘。几十年来，我们一直都知道这一点。我们需要知道该如何帮助他们改变服药行为。”房间里一片寂静。经过数百万美元和数月的研究，房间里没有人知道人们为什么会这么做。

A senior executive at one of the world’s largest health care technology companies sits in a conference room filled with whiteboards. PowerPoint slides blink by on a projector screen. After growing in the double digits for almost a decade and securing a comfortable lead in the market for diabetes care products, the EVP’s department has missed its sales targets for the third time this year. A few months ago, he signed off on an extensive round of market research to understand why. The marketers conducted surveys with thousands of diabetes patients all over the United States and Europe, measuring hundreds of different factors that account for their compliance in taking their medication. He learned that “43 percent of Type 2 diabetes patients are noncompliant, and 84 percent of those noncompliant patients cite forgetfulness as the main reason for their noncompliance.” With only a short period of time to turn the company around before the board tears into him, the EVP is consumed with anger. “We already know that patients are noncompliant because they forget. We’ve known that for decades. We need to know what we can do to get them to change their behavior.” The room is silent. After millions of dollars and months of research, no one in the room has any idea why people do what they do.

2.

2.

一位战场州参议员候选人正在查看自己竞选的民调平均值。她的顾问告诉她，如果根据当前形势进行适当调整，这些平均值将确保她在11月胜选。顾问们将她的选区划分得越来越细，以便她能够相应地调整自己的竞选策略。他们说，这种情况我们以前就见过。今年11月将会像上次和再前一次一样。但到了春天，一件完全出乎意料的事情发生了。一位令人意外的新候选人加入了竞选。他没有使用竞选策略和细分选民，而是凭借其出色的演讲天赋，将看似截然不同的文化主题和模式编织成一个强有力的未来隐喻，从而抓住了选民的想象力。当这位领跑者观看他某次集会的视频时，她能看到选民们充满活力和兴奋之情。集会的气氛让她心中充满了一种深深的不祥预感。这么多的数据都表明她支持她的竞选活动，为什么她感觉这位候选人似乎比她更能与选民建立有意义的联系？在恐惧的时刻，她意识到尽管她做的每件事都正确，但她还是会输掉这次选举。

A candidate for Senate in a battleground state reviews the polling averages for her race. Her consultants tell her that the averages, when properly adjusted to reflect the current environment, assure her a win in November. They have sliced her electorate into ever-narrowing segments so she can shape her talking points accordingly. We’ve seen this before, they say. This November will be like the last election and the one before. But over the spring, something completely unexpected happens. A surprising new candidate puts his hat in the ring. Instead of talking points and segmentation, he captures the imagination of the electorate with an oratorical gift, weaving together seemingly disparate cultural themes and patterns into a powerful metaphor for the future. When the frontrunner watches a video of one of his rallies, she can see the swell of energy and excitement in the voters. The mood of the event fills her with a deep sense of foreboding. With all the numbers showing support for her campaign, why does it feel as though this man is making a more meaningful connection with the voters than she? In a moment of terror, it dawns on her that she is going to lose this election despite doing everything exactly right.

3.

3.

一家专注于太阳能解决方案的初创企业的创业者正在努力理解市场的变化。随着能源分配模式从由公用事业公司提供的集中式模式转变为从传统的依靠电网的模式，到日益分散、参与者众多的模式，企业家必须整合各种不同的数据流。她的团队以其工程专业知识——太阳能市场的尖端技术知识——而自豪，因此他们很少花时间处理企业可持续发展计划中出现的所有文化和政治动态。然而，尽管他们拥有丰富的行业知识，她的公司却在失去客户。就在今天，他们最大的企业客户之一——一家渴望在其营销平台中使用可持续发展计划的零售连锁店——宣布，他们正在与另一家太阳能公司签约，而这家公司销售的产品技术上比她提供的产品更差，价格也更昂贵。她必须立即找到合作伙伴来取代他们，否则一两个月内就发不出公司工资了。她想，为什么我们的市场份额会被技术知识远不如我们的竞争对手夺走？我们错过了什么？

An entrepreneur at a start-up specializing in solar power solutions struggles to make sense of changes in the market. As energy distribution moves from a centralized model—provided by utilities over the grid—to an increasingly distributed model with a constellation of players, the entrepreneur must synthesize a variety of different data streams. Her team prides itself on its engineering expertise—cutting-edge technical knowledge of the solar market—so they spend little time dealing with all of the cultural and political dynamics that occur within corporate sustainability initiatives. And yet, despite their industry knowledge, her company is losing clients. Just today, one of their biggest corporate clients, a retail chain eager to use sustainability initiatives in their marketing platforms, announced that they were signing on with another solar company selling products technically inferior and more expensive than the product she is offering. She must find partners to replace them immediately or she won’t make company payroll in a month or two. Why are we losing market share to competitors with far less technical knowledge? she thinks. What are we missing?

虽然副标题里有“算法”这个词，但这本书并非真正意义上的算法书，也不是关于计算机编程或机器学习未来的书。这是一本关于人的书。更具体地说，这是一本关于文化和我们时代钟摆式转变的书。如今，我们如此专注于基于STEM的知识——来自科学、技术、工程和数学的理论，以及“大数据”的抽象概念——以至于其他解释现实的框架几乎已经过时。这种钟摆式转变正在对我们的企业、政府和机构造成巨大的损害。正如这三种情况所表明的那样，社会以巨大的代价贬低了我们人类的推理和判断能力。我们对STEM的执着削弱了我们对非线性转变的敏感性，而非线性转变正是我们理解的钟摆式转变的体现。这种情况存在于所有人类行为中，削弱了我们从定性信息中提取意义的自然能力。我们不再将数字和模型视为世界的表征，而是开始将它们视为真理——唯一的真理。我们正面临着严重的危险，即彻底侵蚀我们对人类世界的感知，转而倾向于这些虚假的抽象概念。

Although the word algorithm is in the subtitle, this is not really a book about algorithms. Nor is this a book about computer programming or the future of machine learning. This is a book about people. More specifically, this is a book about culture and the pendulum shifts of our age. Today we are so focused on STEM-based knowledge—theories from science, technology, engineering and math, and the abstractions of “big data”—that alternative frameworks for explaining reality have been rendered close to obsolete. This pendulum shift is doing great damage to our businesses, governments, and institutions. As each of these three scenarios illustrates, society devalues our human inferences and judgments at a great cost. Our fixation with STEM erodes our sensitivity to the nonlinear shifts that occur in all human behavior and dulls our natural ability to extract meaning from qualitative information. We stop seeing numbers and models as a representation of the world and we start seeing them as the truth—the only truth. We are in grave danger of completely eroding our sense of the human world in favor of these false abstractions.

当然，硬科学是解释我们星球上很多事物的好方法，例如物质本质。它们在解释化学、工程学或物理学等方面非常有效。但它们并不擅长解释我们人类。正如著名物理学家尼尔·德格拉斯·泰森所说：“在科学中，当人类行为被纳入方程式时，事情就会变得非线性。这就是为什么物理学容易而社会学难。”

Of course, the hard sciences are a good way of explaining quite a lot on our planet, namely material nature. They are tremendously effective at explaining chemistry, engineering, or physics, for example. But they are not good at explaining us. As the famed physicist Neil deGrasse Tyson put it, “In science, when human behavior enters the equation, things go nonlinear. That’s why physics is easy and sociology is hard.”

因为，归根结底，无论我们掌握多少硬数据，无论我们在屏幕上监控了多少脑部扫描，无论我们用多少不同的方式细分市场，都毫无意义。如果我们缺乏对相关人类行为的洞察，我们的洞察力就毫无力量。当我们脱离了对每一次选举、每一次突破性创新以及每一项成功的企业举措背后的人类环境的理解时，我们真正理解世界的能力就会受到限制。

Because, at the end of the day, it doesn’t matter how much hard data we have in our hands, how many brain scans we’ve monitored on our screens, or how many different ways we have segmented our markets. If we don’t have a perspective on the human behavior involved, our insights have no power. When we lose touch with the human circumstances present inside every single election, behind every breakout innovation and each and every successful corporate initiative, we limit our ability to genuinely understand our world.

如果我们想真正理解我们所面临的挑战，就必须回归到一种在当今这个充斥着算法承诺的麻木世界中显得过时且过时的思维方式。这种思维方式在我们所有的组织以及公民话语的各个方面都极其缺乏。它被称为批判性思维。而且，作为一种思维方式，它从未如此具有革命性，也从未如此前沿。

If we want to truly make sense of our challenges, we must return to a process that feels old-fashioned and out of date in today’s anesthetizing world of algorithmic promise. It’s something that has been sorely lacking in all of our organizations and across all aspects of our civic discourse. It’s called critical thinking. And, as a process, it has never felt so revolutionary nor so cutting edge.

介绍

Introduction

人为因素

The Human Factor

人性的本质就是不追求完美。

The essence of being human is that one does not seek perfection.

——乔治·奥威尔，《就在你眼前：1945-1950》

—George Orwell, In Front of Your Nose: 1945–1950

最近，我们人类受到了一些负面报道。每天都有人说，与机器相比，我们是多么不理性、多么低效。与那些由硅驱动的、运转流畅的计算机相比，我们的大脑反应迟钝，而且饱受情绪的困扰。在职场上，人类就像个废物，拖慢了项目的进度，并且由于我们偏好模糊性和复杂性，把黑白分明的界限变成了灰色。我们需要通过经验来学习，而我们所学到的东西不像算法那样精确、严谨或一致。

We humans have been getting some bad press lately. Not a day goes by without hearing about how irrational or inefficient we are when compared with machines. Next to our sleek silicon-powered computer counterparts, our brains are sluggish and burdened by emotions. In the work world, humans are basket cases, slowing down projects and turning black and white lines into gray with our penchant for ambiguity and complexity. We need to learn through experience, and what we learn doesn’t have the same precision, rigor, or consistency as algorithms.

我们在世上的地位已跌至谷底，以至于我们发展出一套咒语来为自己的不足开脱。“我只是个凡人，”我们在休息室或欢乐时光小酌时对同事耸耸肩。这句俗语蕴含着我们文化对人性的理解：身为人，就注定充满缺陷。

Our standing in the world has fallen so far that we have developed a mantra to excuse ourselves from our inadequacies. “I’m only human,” we shrug to coworkers in the break room or at happy hour drinks. This idiom contains a singular truth about the way our culture conceives of our humanity: to be human is to be full of flaws.

在工程界，这被称为人为因素。人为因素——在航空、供应链管理和制药等诸多领域——换句话说就是：容错能力。甚至还有一个新兴的学术领域叫做人为因素研究，专注于如何优化和纠正人机交互（HCI）中的缺陷。人为因素研究探索的是当人类犯下常见错误时，机器如何才能最好地应对。例如，谷歌在其无人驾驶汽车尝试解读真实人类驾驶员的不一致性时，就运用了人为因素研究。人类行为异常是出了名的，这使得算法追求完美驾驶的努力受挫。

In engineering circles, this is referred to as the human factor. The human factor—in domains as varied as aeronautics, supply chain management, and pharmaceuticals—is another way of saying: the capacity for error. There is even a burgeoning area of scholarship called human factors research, focused on how to optimize and correct for our flaws in human-computer interaction, or HCI. Human factors research explores how machines can best cope when we humans make one of our typical mistakes. Google utilizes human factors research, for example, when one of their driverless cars attempts to interpret the inconsistencies of a real human driver. Humans are notorious for behaving irregularly, frustrating the efforts of algorithms to achieve driving perfection.

更糟糕的是，记者和未来学家告诉我们，人类很快就会把大部分工作交给机器人。工厂员工和客服人员是第一批被取代的，但很快我们的劳动力大军将全部被取代：餐厅员工、药剂师、医疗诊断师、律师、会计师，甚至老年人护理员。对于记者和学者来说，问题不在于这种情况是否会发生，而在于当它发生时，我们该如何应对。

To add to our list of woes, journalists and futurists are telling us that we humans will soon be turning over the majority of our jobs to robots. Factory and customer service employees have been the first to go, but it will soon be entire swaths of our labor force: restaurant workers, pharmacists, medical diagnosticians, lawyers, accountants—even caretakers for the elderly. For journalists and academics, the question is not if this will happen, but rather what we will do with ourselves when it happens.

解决人类问题的方法似乎很简单。如果我们想继续发挥作用，并且继续就业，就应该把地盘拱手让给周围的算法，甚至成为它们的奴隶。我们每天都会听到关于“点球成金”的新方案——聘请一位常春藤盟校毕业的经济学家，用清晰、基于事实的分析，而不是人类的直觉和经验，来打开一个行业。我们被亚马逊、谷歌以及无数其他应用程序和初创公司的大数据故事淹没了。求职网站Glassdoor根据职位空缺数量、薪资和晋升机会，将“数据科学家”评为2016年美国排名第一的职业。我们坚信，更多数据将带来更深入的洞察。如果我们通过查看一百个人的数据集合来学习X，那么在汇总数十万人、数亿人或数十亿人的数据集后，我们学习到的知识岂不是会成倍增加？Facebook首席执行官马克·扎克伯格最近告诉投资者，他希望Facebook的机器学习能够创建“世界上所有已知事物的最清晰模型”，这体现了我们对大数据的痴迷。

The solution to the human problem seems straightforward. If we want to remain useful—and employed—we should cede territory to the algorithms all around us—even become subservient to them. Not a day goes by without hearing about a new Moneyball fix—bringing an Ivy League–educated economist in to crack open an industry with clean, fact-based analysis rather than human intuition and experience. We are inundated with stories of big data scores from Amazon, Google, and countless other apps and start-ups. Employment website Glassdoor named “data scientist” as the number-one job in America for 2016 based on the number of job openings, salary, and advancement opportunities. We fervently believe that more data will lead to more insights. If we learn X from looking at a data set of one hundred people, wouldn’t we learn exponentially more after aggregating a data set of hundreds of thousands of people? Or hundreds of millions? Or billions? Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg captured our intoxication with big data when he recently told investors that he wanted machine learning at Facebook to create “the clearest model of everything there is to know in the world.”

我们的学生正在领悟这一道理。在美国最负盛名的大学里，英语和历史等文科专业曾经是最受欢迎的专业，但随着人们对工程学和自然科学的兴趣激增，许多人文科系却遭受重创。自20世纪60年代以来，授予人文学科的学位数量减少了一半。人文学科的研究经费也急剧下降。2011年，人文学科的经费还不到科学和工程研发经费的0.5%。在社会科学领域，社交网络分析和心理测量学等定量研究占据主导地位，而社会学和人类学等定性研究领域则被视为过时之作。在2015年的一次市政厅会议上，美国共和党总统候选人杰布·布什告诉听众，心理学等专业的学生将前往Chick-fil-A工作。同年，日本教育大臣下令日本大学关闭社会科学和人文学科，或将其转型，“以更好地服务于社会需求”。

Our students are getting the message. At the most prestigious universities in the United States, liberal arts fields like English and history used to be among the most popular majors, but a surge in interest in engineering and the natural sciences has decimated many humanities departments. Since the 1960s, the number of degrees awarded in the humanities has shrunk by half. Funding for humanities research has declined precipitously. In 2011, it amounted to less than half of a percent of the funds for science and engineering research and development. Within the social sciences, quantitative studies like social network analysis and psychometrics dominate, while qualitative fields like sociology and anthropology are seen as passé. At a 2015 town hall meeting, U.S. Republican presidential candidate Jeb Bush told the audience that students majoring in disciplines like psychology were headed for jobs at Chick-fil-A. That same year, the Japanese education minister ordered Japanese universities to shut down social science and humanities departments or convert them “to serve areas that better meet society’s needs.”

人文学科——探索文化的学科，例如文学、历史、哲学、艺术、心理学和人类学——不再满足“社会需求”。基于人文学科对不同人及其世界的理解如今已毫无意义。毕竟，与通过大数据获取的无穷无尽的信息相比，人类主导的文化探究有何价值？当算法可以“阅读”所有书籍并对其内容进行客观分析时，真正阅读几本好书还有什么价值？戏剧、绘画、历史研究、舞蹈、政治论文和陶艺，这些无法剥离其特殊性和背景并转化为海量信息的文化知识，还有什么价值？

The humanities—disciplines that explore culture, such as literature, history, philosophy, art, psychology, and anthropology—no longer meet “society’s needs.” A humanities-based understanding of different people and their worlds is now officially useless. After all, compared to the endless information accessible through big data, what value is there in human-led cultural inquiry? What value is there in actually reading a few great books when algorithms can “read” them all and give us an objective analysis of their content? What value is there in plays, paintings, historical studies, dances, political treatises, and pottery, in cultural knowledge that cannot be stripped of its specificity and context and transformed into vast sluices of information?

我写这本书是为了传达一个紧急的信息：它肯定是有价值的。

I write this book with one urgent message to impart: there most certainly is value.

我们忽视这些通过人文思维培养起来的文化知识，这将对我们的未来造成巨大的风险。当我们只关注硬数据和自然科学方法——当我们试图将人类行为量化为无数个夸克或小部件时——我们就会削弱对所有非还原论知识形式的敏感性。我们失去了与书籍、音乐、艺术和文化的联系，而这些让我们能够在复杂的社会语境中体验自我。

We dismiss this cultural knowledge—cultivated through humanities thinking—at great risk to our future. When we focus solely on hard data and natural science methods—when we attempt to quantify human behavior only as so many quarks or widgets—we erode our sensitivity to all the forms of knowledge that are not reductionist. We lose touch with the books, music, art, and culture that allow us to experience ourselves in a complex social context.

这并非一个只在象牙塔内讨论的深奥话题。事实上，我每天都在咨询工作中看到这种现象的后果。我看到大型企业高层缺乏有文化的领导力。我遇到的太多高层领导都局限在自己的世界观中。他们与客户和选民的人性脱节，结果误以为数字和模型就是现实生活。他们每天都在数据被分割成一个个小块，所以他们觉得没时间在纷乱的现实世界数据中徘徊。相反，他们直接进入解决问题的过程，并得出结论，而没有真正理解问题本身。

This is not an esoteric subject for debate solely inside the ivory tower. In fact, I see the consequences of this phenomenon playing out in my consulting work every day. I see the dearth of cultured leadership at the senior levels of major corporations. Too many of the top cadre of leadership I have met are isolated in their worldview. They have lost touch with the humanity of their customers and their constituents and, as a result, they mistake numerical representations and models for real life. Their days are sliced and diced into tiny segments, so they feel they don’t have time to wander around in the mess of real-world data. Instead, they jump into a problem-solving process and a conclusion without understanding the actual question.

正因如此，他们倾向于聘用工程学或MBA出身的初级管理人员，作为数据战线的步兵。他们对硬数据的执着往往掩盖了他们惊人的缺陷，而许多这样的基层管理人员在当今的商业世界中会遭遇玻璃天花板。他们是简化主义者，缺乏识别最令人兴奋、最本质模式的敏感性。这些经理人把每件事都做得“正确”：他们破解了系统，在所有考试中都取得了优异的成绩；他们就读于最好的学校，取得了所有优异的成绩；他们把整个教育经历都投入到训练自己的思维中，以便简化问题，然后解决问题。因此，如今他们根本不具备晋升至高层领导所需的智力水平。

As a result of all this, they tend to hire engineering-or MBA-trained junior executives to be their foot soldiers in the data trenches. Their fixation with hard data often masks stunning deficiencies, and many such lower-level managers will hit a glass ceiling in today’s business world. They are reductionists without the sensitivity to recognize the most exciting and essential patterns. These are managers who did everything “right”: they hacked the system and aced all the tests; they went to the best schools and got all the good grades; they spent their entire education training their minds to reduce the problems and then to solve them. And today, as a result, they simply don’t have the intellectual sophistication required to move into the upper echelons of leadership.

要用确凿的数据来证明这一点并不总是那么容易——人文和社会科学的培训对于成功的职业生涯来说与STEM同等重要，甚至更重要。但请允许我结合背景来解释这个数据问题。2008年，《华尔街日报》报道了研究公司PayScale Inc.对全球薪酬进行的一项大规模研究。该研究证实，拥有纯STEM背景的学生通常在大学毕业后就能找到薪水更高的工作。麻省理工学院（MIT）和加州理工学院的起薪中位数（7.2万美元）排名前两位，在职业中期薪资中位数方面也分别位列第三和第六。

It’s not always easy to prove this point—that training in the humanities and the social sciences is just as important, if not more important, than STEM to a successful career—with hard data. But allow me to put this data question in context. In 2008, the Wall Street Journal reported on a large-scale study of global compensation by the research firm PayScale Inc. The study confirms that students with a pure STEM background generally get better-paying jobs right after graduating from college. Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) and California Institute of Technology rank as the top two schools for starting median salary—at $72,000—and then at number 3 and 6, respectively, for the best mid-career median salaries.

但这项研究涵盖了所有大学毕业生在全美范围内，因此起薪和职业中期薪水的中位数测量都对 STEM 毕业生有利。这是因为文科毕业生最终会在全国范围内从事各种各样的工作和领域。如果你看看全国最成功的人——在职业生涯中期 90百分位及以后——故事就会开始改变。麻省理工学院直到第 11 名才出现，落后于十所具有强大文科理念的学院和大学。耶鲁大学和达特茅斯学院等地的收入中位数最高——超过 30 万美元。在所有其他以工程 STEM 为中心的大学中，只有卡内基梅隆大学甚至进入了职业生涯中期 90 百分位薪水的名单。

But this study includes everyone who graduated from college across the whole of the United States, so median measurements both for starting salaries and for mid-career salaries favor STEM graduates. This is because the liberal arts graduates end up working in an incredibly wide range of jobs and fields across the whole of the nation. If you look at the most successful earners in the entire country—in the 90th percentile mid-career and beyond—the story starts to change. MIT doesn’t show up until number 11, behind ten colleges and universities with strong liberal arts concepts. Places like Yale University and Dartmouth College show the strongest median earnings—above $300,000. Of all other engineering STEM-centered colleges, only Carnegie Mellon University even makes the list of mid-career 90th percentile salaries.

这项研究也揭示了同样的专业问题。通常来说，计算机工程和化学工程在薪资方面排名靠前，而人文学科在中期高收入人群的前20名专业榜单中却很难找到。但是，如果你看看全国收入最高的90%人群，你会发现政治学、哲学、戏剧和历史突然间就占据了显著位置，而且通常来自科尔盖特大学、巴克内尔大学和联合学院等纯文理学院。

The study reveals the same story about majors. Generally, computer engineering and chemical engineering are high-ranking majors when it comes to salary, while it is much harder to find the humanities on the top 20 majors list when it comes to higher earners mid-career. But, again, if you look at the most successful 90th percentile earners in the whole of the country, suddenly political science, philosophy, drama, and history are placed prominently, often from pure liberal arts schools like Colgate University, Bucknell University, and Union College.

从这些数据中我们可以得出的结论是，大多数 STEM 培训都能让学生在起步阶段获得不错的收入，并获得一份体面的职业。但那些高收入者——那些掌控全局、打破玻璃天花板、改变世界的人——往往拥有文科学位。如果你听听硅谷、政客，甚至许多领导人的普遍言论，你就会发现这个消息令人惊讶。在当今的教育领域。但是，如果你曾在一家跨国公司或全球最具影响力的机构工作过，你就会明白这一点。在为全球各地的顶级高管和管理人员提供咨询服务近二十年后，我可以告诉你，最成功的领导者都是好奇心强、受过广泛教育的人，他们既能读小说，也能看电子表格。

What we can take away from this data is that most STEM training will get students a good income at the starting gate and a decent career. But powerful earners—the people running the show, breaking through the glass ceilings, and changing the world—tend to have liberal arts degrees. This will come as surprising news if you listen to the general rhetoric coming out of Silicon Valley, politicians, and even amongst many leaders in education today. But, if you have spent any time in a global company or one of the world’s most powerful institutions, it makes sense. After nearly twenty years of counseling the very top executives and management around the world, I can tell you that the most successful leaders are curious, broadly educated people who can read both a novel and a spreadsheet.

毕竟，我们真的认为，预测一家全球保险公司的未来或辨别拟议立法的政治和社会影响是一个完全基于线性决策树或电子表格上的一组数字的过程吗？2007 年 2 月，雷曼兄弟的所有资产负债表都井然有序，市值创下近 600 亿美元的历史新高。仅仅一年多之后，他们的股价就暴跌了 93%，并申请破产。数字数据掩盖了导致雷曼兄弟破产的更复杂的现实。2003 年和 2004 年，该银行收购了五家抵押贷款机构，其中包括两家在没有任何真实文件的情况下向借款人放贷的次级抵押贷款机构。在房地产繁荣时期，利润空前，但越来越多的人获得了免费资金，而对他们偿还贷款能力的审查却越来越少。与此同时，这些不良贷款与所有更合法的贷款一起被隐藏起来，被打包成复杂的金融产品，称为CDO（担保债务凭证）。任何愿意出去观察的领导者或高管都能看到现实情况。次级抵押贷款市场的大多数借款人不可避免地会违约。不幸的是，对于我们所有在2008年9月将退休储蓄投资于股市的人来说，很少有金融领袖认为值得花时间去关注这些迹象。来自现实世界的数据。当我们停止思考时，受到威胁的不仅仅是我们的智力，还有我们的企业、我们的教育、我们的政府以及我们毕生的积蓄。

After all, do we actually think that figuring out the future of a global insurance company or discerning the political and social implications of proposed legislation is a process based entirely on a linear decision tree or a set of numbers on a spreadsheet? In February 2007, Lehman Brothers had all of its balance sheets in order and reported a record high market cap of close to $60 billion. Little more than a year later, their stock had plunged 93 percent and they were filing for bankruptcy. Numerical data sets obscured the more complex reality that led to the Lehman Brothers collapse. In 2003 and 2004, the bank had acquired five mortgage lenders, including two sub-prime mortgage lenders that loaned money to borrowers without any real documentation. In the midst of a housing boom, the profits were unprecedented, but more and more people were gaining access to free money with less and less scrutiny of their ability to repay any of it. Meanwhile, these bad loans were being hidden away with all of the more legitimate loans, packaged together in complex financial products called CDOs, or collateralized debt obligations. The reality on the streets was available to any leader or executive willing to go out and observe it. It was inevitable that most of the borrowers in the sub-prime mortgage market were going to default. Unfortunately for all of us who had retirement savings invested in the stock markets in September 2008, few financial leaders found it worth their time to take their cues from real-world data. When we stop thinking, it’s not just our intellects that are at stake. It’s our businesses, our educations, our governments, and our life savings.

并非只有我一个人有这种担忧。许多杰出的领导人都在公开呼吁，需要更多受过文科教育的思想家来应对即将到来的未来。洛克希德·马丁公司退休董事长兼首席执行官诺曼·奥古斯丁（Norman Augustine）在2011年为《华尔街日报》撰写了一篇专栏文章，主张在中小学加强人文学科的基础：“历史教育远不止简单地讲述一个国家或文明的故事，它还能培养批判性思考者，使他们能够消化、分析和综合信息，并清晰地表达他们的发现。这些技能是许多学科和学科都需要的。”

I am not alone in my concern. Many of our most prominent leaders are publicly calling out for more liberal arts–trained thinkers to meet this coming future. Norman Augustine, retired chairman and CEO of Lockheed Martin, wrote an op-ed for the Wall Street Journal in 2011 arguing for a stronger foundation in the humanities in our primary and secondary schools: “Far more than simply conveying the story of a country or civilization, an education in history can create critical thinkers who can digest, analyze, and synthesize information and articulate their findings. These are skills needed across a broad range of subjects and disciplines.”

宝洁公司前首席执行官雷富礼 (AG Lafley) 对于如何在当今复杂的管理环境中取得商业成功有一条建议：攻读文科学位。他在《赫芬顿邮报》上写道：“通过学习艺术、科学、人文学科、社会科学和语言，可以培养思维灵活性，从而接受新想法，而这正是在不断变化的环境中取得成功的必备条件。正如一名有抱负的大联盟投手需要强壮的手臂和冷静的头脑才能有效投球一样，一名管理前景也需要接受广泛的教育，以便有效应对模糊性和不确定性。完成广泛的文科课程应该能够让学生培养概念性、创造性和批判性思维技能，这些技能是锻炼头脑的基本要素。”

A. G. Lafley, former CEO of Procter & Gamble, had one single piece of advice for achieving business success in today’s complex managerial environment: pursue a degree in the liberal arts. “By studying art, science, the humanities, social science, and languages,” he wrote in the Huffington Post, “the mind develops the mental dexterity that opens a person to new ideas, which is the currency for success in a constantly changing environment. And just as an aspiring Major League pitcher needs a live arm and a calculating, cool head to pitch effectively, so too does a management prospect need to be educated broadly to respond effectively to ambiguity and uncertainty. Completing a broad liberal arts curriculum should enable a student to develop the conceptual, creative, and critical thinking skills that are the essential elements of a well-exercised mind.”

这些领导人，就像许多其他站在商业、政策和创业前沿的人一样，正在敲响警钟劳动力受教育程度更高。毕竟，不久之前，金融、媒体或政策领域的领导者拥有人文学科背景还是很常见的：美国运通现任首席执行官肯·切诺特 (Ken Chenault) 称，他对历史的深入研究是其领导能力和管理敏锐性的试金石；IBM 前首席执行官萨姆·帕尔米萨诺 (Sam Palmisano) 曾在约翰·霍普金斯大学主修历史；前财政部长汉克·保尔森 (Hank Paulson) 曾在达特茅斯学习英语；1999 年至 2005 年担任惠普公司首席执行官的卡莉·菲奥莉娜 (Carly Fiorina) 称，她本科学习的中世纪历史专业是了解高科技世界的完美基础；迪士尼的迈克尔·艾斯纳 (Michael Eisner) 避开了商业和金融课程，转而主修英语和戏剧；著名投资者卡尔·伊坎 (Carl Icahn) 在普林斯顿大学的哲学专业毕业论文题为“对经验主义意义标准的充分解释问题”；前联邦存款保险公司 (FDIC) 主席希拉·贝尔 (Sheila Bair) 在堪萨斯大学读本科时学习的是哲学；私募股权公司黑石集团董事长兼首席执行官史蒂芬·施瓦茨曼 (Stephen Schwarzman) 在耶鲁大学选择了一门跨学科专业，他将其描述为“心理学、社会学、人类学和生物学，这实际上是对人类的研究”。

These leaders, like so many others at the forefront of business, policy, and entrepreneurship, are sounding the alarm for a better-educated workforce. After all, it was not so long ago when it was commonplace for leaders in finance, media, or policy to have a background in the humanities: Ken Chenault, current CEO of American Express, cited his in-depth study of history as a touchstone for his leadership and managerial acumen; Sam Palmisano, former CEO of IBM, was a history major at Johns Hopkins; Hank Paulson, once secretary of the Treasury, studied English at Dartmouth; Carly Fiorina, CEO of Hewlett Packard from 1999 to 2005, described her undergraduate major in medieval history as the perfect foundation for understanding the high-tech world; Michael Eisner of Disney bypassed business and finance courses, eschewing them for majors in English and theater; famed investor Carl Icahn’s senior thesis in philosophy at Princeton was titled, “The Problem of Formulating an Adequate Explication of the Empiricist Criterion of Meaning”; Sheila Bair, former FDIC chair, studied philosophy as an undergraduate at the University of Kansas; and Stephen Schwarzman, chairman and CEO of the private equity firm Blackstone, chose an interdisciplinary major at Yale that he described as “psychology, sociology, anthropology, and biology, which is really sort of the study of the human being.”

然而，越来越多的人开始认为，与数据分析学位或最新计算机编程技能的在线速成课程的直接效用相比，这些学科显得无关紧要。这种文化转变的结果是，我们不再看到诗歌、雕塑、小说和音乐等事物的价值。当我们贬低人文精神的价值时，我们就失去了探索不同世界的最佳机会。当我读到托马斯·曼的《魔山》这样的伟大小说时，我真切地感受到那种毁灭性的打击。第一次世界大战期间及之后欧洲大陆的景象；当我邂逅像《独角兽的狩猎》这样的中世纪挂毯时，我明白了在文艺复兴初期，法国人民所拥有的意义。而当我参观京都的龙安寺禅园时，石头的布局和纹理也向我展现了日本世界观和美学的精髓。

More and more people, however, have come to view these disciplines as irrelevant when compared with the immediate utility of a degree in data analytics or an online crash course in the latest computer programming skill. The result of this cultural shift is that we stop seeing value in things like poetry, sculpture, novels, and music. And when we devalue humanistic endeavors, we lose our best opportunity for exploring worlds different from our own. When I read a great novel like Thomas Mann’s The Magic Mountain, I can actually feel the devastation of a European continent during and after World War I; when I encounter a medieval tapestry like The Hunt of the Unicorn, I understand what was meaningful to people in France on the cusp of the Renaissance. And when I visit the Ryōan-ji Zen garden in Kyoto, the placement and texture of the stones shows me something essential about the Japanese worldview and aesthetic.

无论你研究的是中国建筑、墨西哥历史，还是苏菲派哲学，这种思维方式都能训练我们综合各种数据，在无需证明或反驳狭隘假设的情况下进行探索，并以同理心去理解特定世界的特殊性。我相信，这种文化交融是理解任何群体的重要训练基础。例如，如果你在一家制药公司工作，你需要了解糖尿病患者的生活，否则你所有的药物研发尝试都注定会失败。假设你制造汽车，你需要了解中国西部司机的生活是什么样的，否则你的汽车将充斥着与全球最大汽车市场不相干的配置。如果你在公共部门工作，你需要社会科学工具来批判性地思考官僚文化。

Whether you are studying Chinese architecture, Mexican history, or the philosophy of the Sufis, this kind of thinking trains our minds to synthesize all types of data, to explore without need of proving or disproving a narrow hypothesis, and to engage empathically with the particularities of a given world. I believe that this type of cultural engagement is an essential training ground for understanding any group of people. If you work for a pharmaceutical firm, for example, you need to understand the world of a person with diabetes, or all your attempts at drug development will surely fail. Say you make cars. You need to know what life is like for a driver living in western China, or your vehicles will be filled with irrelevant features in the world’s largest car market. And if you work in the public sector, you need social science tools to think critically about the culture of bureaucracy.

人文学科的经验教会我们如何想象其他世界。但它们提供的远不止于此。因为当我们能够充分想象其他世界——运用文化知识和对人类经验的解释——我们必然会对自己的世界形成更敏锐的视角。我们学会发现模型和金融创新何时偏离真相。我们识别出从科学事实和实际现实、从现有情况和未来可能性中提炼出的模式，这些模式能够揭示真相。洞察，并最终帮助我们形成真正的视角。从长远来看，洞察总是比被禁锢在数据的牢笼中更有利可图——无论对你的银行账户还是你的生活而言。

Experiences with the humanities teach us how to imagine other worlds. But they offer so much more than that. Because when we can fully imagine other worlds—using cultural knowledge and explanations for our human experience—we inevitably develop a more acute perspective on our own world. We learn to see when models and financial innovations are diverging from the truth. We recognize patterns—distilled from both scientific facts and practical reality, from both existing situations and future possibilities—that shed light on insights and, ultimately, help us form a genuine perspective. And perspectives, in the long run, always prove far more profitable—to both your bank account and your life—than confinement in a cage of data.

这种严谨的文化交融是我称之为“意义建构”的实践的基础。多年来，学者们用“意义建构”一词来描述不同的概念，但我在本书中通篇使用它，仅仅是为了描述一种古老的文化探究实践，这一过程基于一套我们极易遗忘的价值观。通过意义建构，我们运用人类智慧来培养对有意义的差异的敏感性——那些对我们自己和他人都重要的事情。

This rigorous cultural engagement is the foundation of the practice I call sensemaking. Academics have used the term sensemaking to describe different concepts over the years, but I use it here, throughout this book, simply to describe an ancient practice of cultural inquiry, a process based on a set of values we are in great danger of forgetting. With sensemaking, we use human intelligence to develop a sensitivity toward meaningful differences—what matters to other people as well as to ourselves.

在接下来的篇幅中，意义建构将带领我们踏上一段以二十世纪哲学信条为基础的智识冒险之旅。我们将探讨构成人文学科研究的理论和方法，并探讨它们如何帮助我们从非线性数据中提取意义。我们将审视我们获得创造性洞见的真实体验，并以此扫除那些围绕创新和突破性想法持续流传的误导性观念。此外，我们还将与实践大师们会面，探讨人类智慧为何是唯一能够培养洞察力的智慧。

In the pages to come, sensemaking will take us on an intellectual adventure story grounded in the tenets of twentieth-century philosophy. We will look at the theories and methodologies that make up studies in the humanities and discuss different ways that these can help us extract meaning from nonlinear data. We will examine our genuine experience of creative insights and, in so doing, clear away some of the misguided notions that continue to circulate around innovation and breakout ideas. And we will meet master practitioners and look at how human intelligence is the only intelligence that can cultivate a perspective.

我们的文化从未如此被人工智能、机器学习和认知计算的前景所吸引。我们这个世界的政治、金融、社会、技术和环境系统从未如此错综复杂地联系在一起。我们必须提醒自己——以及整个文化——为什么人为因素是理解这个世界最重要的因素。现在就行动起来吧。

Never before has our culture been so seduced by the promises of artificial intelligence, machine learning, and cognitive computing. Never before has our world of overlapping political, financial, social, technical, and environmental systems been so inextricably linked. We must remind ourselves—and the culture at large—why the human factor is the most important factor when it comes to making sense of this world. The time to begin is right now.

第一章

Chapter One

理解世界

Making Sense of the World

真正的天才在于能够评估不确定、危险和相互矛盾的信息。

True genius resides in the capacity for evaluation of uncertain, hazardous, and conflicting information.

—温斯顿·丘吉尔

—Winston Churchill

参观福特汽车公司总部的访客，首先映入眼帘的便是琳琅满目的国旗。它们环绕着位于密歇根州迪尔伯恩的这栋雄伟蓝色建筑的入口，每一面国旗都代表着福特公司在当地开展业务的国家。国旗数量之多，以至于通往大楼正门的长廊都弥漫着联合国大会的氛围。

The first thing a visitor to the headquarters of the Ford Motor Company will notice upon arrival is the flags. They surround the entrance to the imposing blue building in Dearborn, Michigan, each one from a country where Ford has operations. There are so many flags that the long walkway up to the main door of the building has the air of a United Nations assembly.

总部大厅和低层楼依然保持着这种外交氛围——人们来来往往，效率高，无数电梯叮叮当当，生意兴隆。然而，总部的顶层却异常安静。自2014年以来担任总裁兼首席执行官的马克·菲尔兹的办公室就在这里。几乎所有在这里待上一段时间的人，主要目的都是为了保护自己的时间和注意力。

The lobby and lower floors of the headquarters maintain this atmosphere of diplomatic cheerfulness—people come and go with a friendly efficiency, dinging the countless elevators doing brisk business up and down. The very top floors of the headquarters, however, are oddly quiet. This is where Mark Fields, president and CEO since 2014, has his office. The main objective of almost everyone who spends any amount of their day up here is to protect his time and attention.

菲尔兹从他的顶层办公室望出去，可以看到福特园区的广阔景象。访客需要一辆车是有原因的去福特开会；步行走遍园区几乎是不可能的。透过窗户，公司就像一个工程师们制造动力传动系统、刹车和软件的小天地。左边是产品开发总部；右边是营销大楼，矗立在精心修剪的草坪上。

From his penthouse office, Fields looks out and sees the vast expanse of the Ford campus. There’s a reason visitors need a car to go to meetings at Ford; it’s impossible to cover the campus on foot. Through the windows, the company resembles a little country of engineers making power trains, brakes, and software. To the left is the headquarters of product development; and to the right, the marketing buildings tower over well-kept lawns.

马克·菲尔兹凭借这一独特的优势，做出的决策将对全球数十万员工产生深远的影响。但他的视角从根本上受到限制：与大多数CEO一样，他受到来自官方和非官方层层的保护，与外界隔绝。福特员工会花费数月时间准备与他进行一小时的会面，一遍又一遍地演练他可能提出的每一个问题的各个方面和答案。福特的19.9万名员工以直接和间接的方式，为他提供着精心策划的信息流。有些人为了避免成为坏消息的传播者而对问题进行粉饰。而另一些人则以效率的名义，干脆删减描述和细节。每一次对话中的每一次编辑，都让菲尔兹面临着与强大的人类智慧失去联系的危险，而这种智慧可以帮助他做出战略决策。然而，他不可能关注所有事情。在这些限制的框架下，菲尔兹每天都必须做出决定，而这些决策将决定这家年收入超过1500亿美元的公司的未来。

From this singular vantage point, Mark Fields makes decisions that have lasting impact on hundreds of thousands of employees all over the world. But his perspective is fundamentally limited: like most CEOs, he is protected from the world by official and unofficial layers of people. Ford employees will spend months preparing for a one-hour meeting with him, rehearsing over and over again every aspect and responses to every possible question he might have. In ways both direct and indirect, the 199,000 people working for Ford are offering him a highly curated information stream. Some of them are glossing over issues because they don’t want to be the bearers of bad news. Others, however, are simply editing out descriptions and details in the name of efficiency. With every single edit in every single conversation, Fields is in danger of losing touch with potent human intelligence that will help him make strategic decisions. And yet, he can’t pay attention to everything. Somehow, within these limitations, Fields has to make daily decisions that will determine the future of more than 150 billion dollars in annual revenue.

过去，他能够凭借直觉做出许多选择。他在汽车行业拥有数十年的经验，包括担任马自达首席执行官。而且，直到最近，福特的汽车销售模式——利用研究和工程技术开发新功能，以吸引福特主要面向美国市场的车主——仍然非常契合其买家。车主们渴望为先进的技术功能支付更多费用，福特可以沿用1908年首款T型车的成功营销策略：“低价汽车，高品质”。福特凭借其扎实的汽车工程专业知识，不断赢得车主的青睐——与通用汽车不同，福特始终是一家汽车爱好者的公司。简而言之，菲尔兹和许多福特工程师与福特汽车的购买者在同一个世界里成长。

In the past, he was able to use his intuition to guide him through many of these choices. He has decades of experience in the car industry, including serving as the CEO of Mazda. And, until recently, Ford’s model of selling cars—using research and engineering to develop new features to appeal to Ford’s mostly American drivers—was a good fit for its buyers. Drivers were eager to pay more money for technologically advanced features, and Ford could use the same marketing that had proved so successful for their very first Model T in 1908: “High Priced Quality in a Low Priced Car.” Ford consistently won over drivers with its solid expertise in car engineering—unlike General Motors, Ford has always been a car lover’s company. In short, Fields and many of the Ford engineers grew up in the same world as the people buying Ford’s cars.

但是，当生活在另一个世界的人开始购买福特汽车时会发生什么呢？生活在巴西或中国的人们拥有与美国人截然不同的世界观、情感和抱负。对这些人来说，福特扎实的工程技术和中产阶级价值观的历史毫无意义。更重要的是，其特定的高质量功能通常与汽车的价值无关，甚至有损于汽车的价值。福特一直在投资诸如车道辅助系统（一种旨在使车辆保持在白线内的自动化系统）之类的技术，但如果他们的潜在驾驶员生活在一个没有明确车道划分的中国城市，该怎么办？福特已经探索了无人驾驶汽车的想法，但他们的许多新客户生活在印度新德里这样的地方，在那里雇用司机是车主的常态，也是彰显地位的重要方式。

But what happens when people who are living in other worlds start buying Ford’s cars? People living in Brazil or China possess strikingly different worldviews, sentiments, and aspirations than do Americans. To these people, Ford’s history of solid engineering and middle class values is meaningless. What’s more, its specific, high-quality features are often irrelevant or even detriments to the value of the car. Ford had been investing in technologies like Lane Assist—an automated system designed to keep vehicles inside the white lines—but what if their potential drivers live in a Chinese city without clearly demarcated lanes? Ford has explored the idea of driverless cars, but many of their new customers live in places like New Delhi, India, where employing a driver is the norm for car owners and an important way of signifying status.

面对如此众多的问题，像马克·菲尔兹这样的高管精心设计的空间和视角突然显得不那么有利了。他不再基于自身世界的认知来做决策。他需要了解与自身文化截然不同的人们的世界。底特律工程师们所关注的事情很可能与德克萨斯人（比如说，一个正在寻找卡车的人）所关注的事情重叠。但菲尔兹和他在福特的工程师们已经开始比如，他们感觉自己不太了解对于渴望在职业和艺术上建立联系的上海年轻创意人士来说什么是重要的，又或者对于在繁重的工作日程中寻求更多精神反思空间的钦奈企业家来说什么是重要的。

Faced with a multitude of such problems, the carefully designed spaces and perspectives of an executive like Mark Fields suddenly do not seem so advantageous. He is no longer making decisions based on the knowledge of his own world. He needs to understand the worlds of people in cultures vastly different from his own. What matters to the engineers in Detroit is likely to overlap with what matters to, say, a Texan looking for a truck. But Fields and his engineers at Ford have begun to sense that they don’t know enough about what is relevant to a young creative in Shanghai eager to make career and artistic connections, for example, or an entrepreneur in Chennai who is seeking out more space for spiritual reflection in the midst of a grinding work schedule.

当我与像菲尔兹这样的高管合作，帮助他们探索新兴市场中的其他文化和人群时，他们几乎总是用同样的方式描述自己的经历。他们不再仅仅依靠直觉来做出明智的决策。他们说：“我失去了直觉。 ” 他们都想尽快找回它。但是该怎么做呢？

When I work with executives like Fields—helping them to discover other cultures and people in emerging markets—they almost always describe their experience in the same way. They can no longer trust their instincts alone as a guiding light for wise decisions. They say, I’ve lost my intuition. And they all want to get it back—quickly. But how?

要获得马克·菲尔兹所追求的那种理解——对其他世界的理解——只有对文化有深刻的洞察才有可能。如果我们不进行严谨而持续的文化互动，就无法对文化产生有意义的洞察。我所说的“严谨”和“互动”并非指市场调研数据或数据分析。我指的是涉及人文学科的文化研究：阅读一种文化的经典文本，理解其语言，亲身感受其人民的生活方式。而不是“76% 的巴西21至35岁城市居民购买优质咖啡”。这类数据并不能告诉我们任何关于文化的信息。

Gaining the type of understanding that Mark Fields is after—an understanding of other worlds—is only possible with profound insights into culture. And we can’t have a meaningful insight into culture if we don’t embrace a rigorous and sustained engagement with it. When I use the words “rigorous” and “engagement,” I don’t mean market research numbers or data analytics. I mean a study of culture that involves the humanities: reading a culture’s seminal texts, understanding its languages, getting a firsthand feel for how its people live. Not “76 percent of 21-to 35-year-olds living in urban areas in Brazil buy premium coffee.” This kind of data tells us nothing about culture.

以星巴克为例。没错，这家公司的成功依赖于技术和定量分析：他们需要最先进的咖啡机和烘焙机；他们需要精简的供应链、精心设计的移动应用程序以及最新的金融科技驱动公司发展。但公司真正的核心和灵魂——其存在的理由——却基于一种简单却深刻的文化洞察。霍华德·舒尔茨深谙如何将南欧咖啡文化融入美国生活。如今看来，这一切显而易见，但就在35年前，北美的咖啡还意味着一杯温热的福杰士咖啡。舒尔茨的洞见源于他对意大利语言和文化的理解——在接手星巴克之前，他曾前往意大利，研究著名的意大利咖啡馆——同时也体会到美国人对更多共享社区空间的渴望。

Take Starbucks. Yes, the success of the company relies on technology and quantitative analysis: they need the most advanced coffee machines and roasters; they need a streamlined supply chain, well-designed mobile apps, and up-to-date financial technology to drive the company’s growth. But the actual heart and soul of the company—its raison d’être—is based on a simple but profound cultural insight. Howard Schultz understood how to modify the Southern European coffee culture to the contours of American life. Today all this seems far too obvious, but it was only thirty-five years ago that coffee in North America meant a lukewarm cup of Folgers. Schultz’s insight required an understanding of Italian language and culture—he went to Italy and studied the famous Italian coffee bars before taking over at Starbucks—as well as an attunement to an unmet desire in the United States for more shared community spaces.

当我们想要了解人们——了解他们丰富现实世界中的真实存在的人——时，我们需要这种文化智慧。我们需要知道他们的砂锅炖菜在烤箱里烤了一个小时后是什么味道；我们需要知道清晨沙漠中风沙弥漫，刺痛他们的眼睛；我们需要知道他们的诗歌从不使用第一人称单数，并且他们始终将山脉视为遭受攻击时的避风港。以这种方式探究一种文化——实现对其的360度全方位理解——需要我们人性的方方面面：我们必须将我们的智慧、我们的精神和所有感官都投入到这项任务中。最重要的是要记住：如果我们想对另一种文化发表一些有意义的见解，我们必须放下——哪怕只是一点点——构成我们自身文化框架的偏见和假设。当我们决心放弃自我的一部分时，我们将会获得一些全新的意义。我们获得了洞察力。我把培养这种洞察力的实践称为“意义建构”。

When we want to understand people—real people in the rich reality of their worlds—we need this type of cultural intelligence. We need to know how their cassoulet smells after an hour in the oven; we need to know that the sand and dirt blowing in their deserts hurts their eyes in the morning; we need to know that their poetry never uses the first-person singular, and that they have always considered their mountains a safe haven when under attack. Investigating a culture in this way—achieving a 360-degree understanding of it—calls on every part of our humanity: we must bring our intellects, our spirits, and all our senses to the task. Most important to remember: if we want to say something meaningful about another culture, we have to let go—just a little bit—of the biases and assumptions that form the scaffolding of our own culture. When we commit to losing a part of ourselves, we gain something profoundly new in exchange. We gain insight. I call the practice of cultivating these types of insights sensemaking.

什么是意义建构？

What Is Sensemaking?

意义建构是一种植根于人文学科的实践智慧方法。我们可以将意义建构视为算法思维的对立面：意义建构完全基于具体事物，而算法思维则存在于被剥离了其特殊性的信息的无人区。算法思维可以触及广阔的领域——每秒处理数万亿 TB 的数据——但只有意义建构才能深入。

Sensemaking is a method of practical wisdom grounded in the humanities. We can think of sensemaking as the exact opposite of algorithmic thinking: it is entirely situated in the concrete, while algorithmic thinking exists in a no-man’s-land of information stripped of its specificity. Algorithmic thinking can go wide—processing trillions of terabytes of data per second—but only sensemaking can go deep.

我们可以追溯意义建构的根源，追溯到古希腊哲学家亚里士多德，他将实践智慧描述为“phronesis”（智慧）。当一个技艺高超的人展现出“phronesis”时，这不仅仅意味着他们掌握了抽象的原则和规则。“phronesis”是知识与经验的巧妙融合。

We can trace sensemaking’s roots back to Aristotle, the Greek philosopher, who described practical wisdom as phronesis. When a highly skilled person exhibits phronesis, it’s not just that they possess knowledge of abstract principles and rules. Phronesis is an artful synthesis of both knowledge and experience.

在商业世界中，当熟练的交易员能够与市场条件协调一致地运作，当经验丰富的企业管理者能够察觉到涉及数万人的组织中的细微变化时，我们就看到了实践智慧。当一项立法改革实施时，展现实践智慧的政治家能够预见到其选区各个领域将同时发生的一系列事件。许多经验丰富的杰出领导者——知识渊博且经验丰富——将系统、社会和组织描述为他们身体的延伸。它们是身体的一部分，他们也是身体的一部分。

In the business world, we see phronesis when skilled traders perform in concert with market conditions and when experienced corporate managers sense subtle changes in organizations involving tens of thousands of people. When a legislative reform is implemented, a politician exhibiting phronesis can envision the chain of events that will play out in every domain of his or her constituency all at once. Many masterful leaders—knowledgeable and experienced—describe systems, societies, and organizations as an extension of their body. It is a part of them and they are a part of it.

这些人是如何取得如此非凡成就的？虽然这项工作没有捷径——没有五步计划、“生活妙招”或精彩绝伦的PowerPoint演示文稿来自动帮我们实现目标——但有一些基本原则可以帮助我们所有人保持开放的心态，去发现最重要的洞见。这些原则基于人文学科丰富的理论和方法论。我精心设计了每一个理论和方法论，使其与我们算法时代的主流假设直接相悖。

How do these people achieve such extraordinary results? Though there is no shortcut to this work—no five-step plan, “life hack,” or killer PowerPoint to automatically get us there—there are some basic principles that can help all of us stay open to the insights that matter most. These principles are based upon the wealth of theories and methodologies that make up the humanities. I have framed each one of them to sit in direct contradiction to the prevailing assumptions of our algorithmic age.

在接下来的章节中，我将更深入地探讨每一项原则，并提供更丰富的知识背景。我们将与一些大师级的实践者见面，他们基于以下理念，对这种实践进行了各自的解读：

In the following chapters, I will address each principle in more depth and provide a richer intellectual context for them. We will meet the master practitioners who wrestle with their own interpretations of such a practice based on the following ideas:

意义建构的五项原则

The Five Principles of Sensemaking

1. 文化——而非个人

1. Culture—not individuals

2. 厚数据——而不仅仅是薄数据

2. Thick data—not just thin data

3. 大草原——不是动物园

3. The savannah—not the zoo

4. 创造力——而非制造

4. Creativity—not manufacturing

5. 北极星——不是GPS

5. The North Star—not the GPS

1. 文化——而非个人

1. Culture—Not Individuals

诺贝尔奖得主、短篇小说家艾丽丝·门罗曾写道：“那些看似根深蒂固、最为私密和独特的倾向，仿佛随风飘散，如同孢子，四处寻觅，寻找任何合适的落脚点，任何受欢迎的场所。” 我们喜欢将自己视为高度个体化的人，拥有自主的行为模式。然而，尽管现代自由民主国家承诺独立思考，我们对什么是恰当和相关的概念，却源于社会背景。正如敏锐的门罗所言，这种背景决定了什么是恰当和相关的——这些倾向如同“孢子”般四处传播。

Alice Munro, the Nobel Prize–winning short story writer, once wrote, “It’s as if tendencies that seem most deeply rooted in our minds, most private and singular, have come in as spores on the prevailing wind, looking for any likely place to land, any welcome.” We like to conceive of ourselves as highly individual, with our own autonomous modes of behaving. Yet, despite the promise of independent thought in modern liberal democracies, our notions of what is appropriate and relevant come to us through social context. As the astute Munro noted, this context determines what shows up as appropriate and relevant—tendencies that travel “like spores.”

这为什么重要？如果我们想理解一种文化最深刻的内涵，首先必须理解该文化中人们行为背后的原因。这种理解很少——甚至从未——基于个人的言论，甚至他们声称的所作所为。相反，它建立在对世界的理解之上。无论我们身处对冲基金经理、工会员工、艺术家、母亲还是政客的世界，作为人类，我们都会敏感地感受到其他人的行为方式、改变方式以及思考方式。

Why does this matter? If we want to understand the most profound insights of a culture, we must first understand why people in that culture act the way they do. That understanding is rarely—if ever—based upon what individual people say or even on what they claim to do. Instead, it is built around an understanding of worlds. Whether we are in the world of hedge fund managers, union employees, artists, mothers, or politicians, we, as humans, are sensitive to how others in our world do things, change things, and think about things.

哲学可以帮助我们更好地理解这一点。尽管哲学常常被认为是深奥难懂的，但它却是我们分析根深蒂固的文化假设的最有力的智力工具。马丁·海德格尔被许多人视为二十世纪最伟大的哲学家。1927年，他提出这些不言而喻的假设——我们日常生活的氧气——应该被称为“存在”，从而推翻了西方哲学的所有预设。他将其定义为“理解存在的基础”。这种对“我们”的全新理解方式与他的对手哲学家勒内·笛卡尔的主流观点截然相反：我思故我在。海德格尔的“存在”与个体思考、分析或客观地与环境保持距离无关。

Philosophy can help us understand this better. Although it is often considered esoteric, philosophy is our greatest intellectual tool for analyzing deeply held cultural assumptions. Martin Heidegger, considered by many to be the greatest philosopher of the twentieth century, overturned all of the presuppositions of Western philosophy when he argued, in 1927, that these unspoken assumptions—the oxygen of our everyday lives—should be called “Being.” He defined it as “That on the basis of which beings are understood.” This radical new way of conceiving of “us” stood in direct contradiction to the prevailing edicts of rival philospher René Descartes: I think, therefore I am. Heidegger’s “Being” had nothing to do with an individual thinking, analyzing, or standing at a distance—objectively—from a context.

海德格尔以及追随他脚步的一代哲学家认为，纯粹、自足的个体主体能够发挥重要作用的情形寥寥无几——即便有的话。对这批新哲学家而言，社会背景，或称“存在”，不仅仅是我们日常行为的驱动力；它更是现实得以呈现为可理解且有意义的过滤器。例如，如果我们是欧洲中世纪的孩子，我们的身份认同感和抱负必然与教会有关。中世纪的年轻骑士会将所有现象视为他与上帝同等地位的体现。当然，今天的年轻人绝不会想到成为一名骑士——除非是为了选择媚俗或服装。我们的现实——我们认为有意义的一切——都具有高度的语境和历史性。大多数时候，我们无法超越这种语境进行思考。海德格尔认为，人类是由他们所生活的社会所定义的。所有这一切意味着，当福特汽车公司的马克·菲尔兹这样的人想要了解如何在中国、印度和巴西等地销售汽车时，他需要对这些新驱动力的社会背景有更细致的理解。而意义建构是实现这种理解的最快、最有效的方式。需要明确的是，意义建构不是对艺术的肤浅了解——比如随便放一张专辑作为背景音乐，或者在出去喝一杯之前花三十分钟逛逛博物馆展览。意义建构是一种要求很高的文化参与形式；正是它的严谨性才使得它如此有价值。

Heidegger, and the generation of philosophers who followed in his footsteps, argued that there are very few situations—if any—in which the pure, self-contained individual subject has a significant role to play. For this new cadre of philosophers, social context, or “Being,” was not just the driver of our everyday behavior; it was the very filter through which reality showed up as intelligible and meaningful. If we were children in the European Middle Ages, for example, our sense of identity and aspiration would necessarily be in relationship to the Church. A young knight in the Middle Ages would experience all phenomena as a reflection of his place next to God. Today, of course, it would never occur to a young man to become a knight—unless as a choice of kitsch or costume. Our reality—everything that we perceive as meaningful—is highly contextual and historical. And most of the time we are incapable of thinking beyond that context. Humans are defined by the society in which they live, Heidegger argued. All of this means that when someone like Mark Fields at Ford wants to understand how to sell cars in places like China, India, and Brazil, he needs a much more nuanced understanding of the social context of these new drivers. And sensemaking is the fastest and most effective means of achieving this type of understanding. To be clear, sensemaking is not a superficial brush-up on the arts—throwing on an album as background music or cruising through a museum exhibit in thirty minutes before going out for a drink. Sensemaking is a demanding form of cultural engagement; its rigor is precisely what makes it so rewarding.

让我用两位不同的音乐家做一个小小的思维实验来说明这一点：如果你播放爵士乐大师查理·帕克的《萨沃伊》和《戴尔》的录音，你就会回到20世纪40年代哈莱姆区的明顿剧场俱乐部，那里烟雾弥漫，种族紧张的气氛弥漫。你能听到他精湛的技艺如何打破时空的连续性，随着他的演奏速度越来越快，你会体验到一种名为比波普的全新音乐的出现。

Let me give you a little thought experiment involving two different musicians to illustrate how this works: If you put on jazz great Charlie Parker’s Savoy and Dial recordings, you are transported back to Minton’s Playhouse club in 1940s Harlem, where the smoke was thick and racial tensions hung heavy in the air. You can hear how his technical proficiency breaks the space-time continuum and, as his playing gets faster and faster, you experience the emergence of an entirely new kind of music called bebop.

相反，如果你播放大卫·鲍伊 1977 年的专辑《英雄》，并听出那句歌词“我们可以成为英雄，哪怕只有一天”，你也会陷入一种充满愤世嫉俗情绪的青年文化的绝望之中——几乎没有就业机会，也没有对美好未来的希望。

If, instead, you put on David Bowie’s album “Heroes” from 1977 and engage with that one single line “We can be heroes, just for one day,” you open yourself up to the desperation of a youth culture infected with cynicism—little in the way of employment or hope for a better future.

这两首音乐作品都为我们打开了一扇通往另一个世界的大门。我们开始看到二战时期哈莱姆区的爵士音乐家，以及后朋克时代伦敦和纽约街头的年轻人，他们眼中的现实是如何构建的。透过音乐的细微差别，我们逐渐理解了这些特定时代和地点的文化希望与恐惧。我们了解到什么值得庆祝，什么规则——无论是美学、社会还是政治——需要被打破。

Both of these pieces of music offer a direct portal into other worlds. We start to see how reality is structured for a jazz musician in Harlem during World War II and for young people in the post-punk era on the streets of London and New York. Through the nuances of the music, we come to an understanding about the cultural hopes and fears in these specific times and places. We learn what is worth celebrating and what rules—aesthetic, social, or political—need to be broken.

最近一次参观洛杉矶郡立艺术博物馆（LACMA）时，我对此深有体会。我漫步走进展示中世纪晚期伊斯兰艺术的房间，看到一位面容憔悴的老人坐在长椅上，抬头凝视着一幅描绘《恋人聚会》的手稿。水彩画中，金色天使光彩夺目，环绕着亚当的身影，亚当安详地坐在中央。我站在房间后方，以免打扰到他，但他却转过身来跟我说话，脸上噙满了泪水。他告诉我，他是一位来自墨西哥的无证工人，正在为母亲的去世而悲痛。他说，他之所以能与手稿画作中的故事产生共鸣，是因为他清楚地意识到，这位几百年前在陌生的土地上创作的艺术家，对家人也怀有同样的愿望。“他希望他们死后能去到一个美丽而宁静的地方，”他告诉我。然后他想了想，说道：“他一定和我一样。”

I had a profound experience with this on a recent visit I made to LACMA, the Los Angeles County Museum of Art. I wandered into the room displaying Islamic art from the late Middle Ages and I saw an older man with a worn face sitting on a bench and looking up at a manuscript depicting “The Gathering of Lovers.” In the watercolor, brilliantly rendered gold angels surround a figure of Adam, sitting at peace in the center. I stood in the back of the room so as not to disturb the man, but he turned around to speak to me, his face filled with tears. He told me that he was an undocumented worker from Mexico and that he was grieving the death of his mother. He connected with the storytelling in the manuscript painting, he said, because it was clear to him that this artist, working hundreds of years ago in an area of the world utterly foreign to him, had similar wishes for his family. “He wanted them to be in a place of beauty and calm after they died,” he told me. And then he thought for a moment before saying, “He must have been just like me.”

伟大的艺术跨越时代，将我们连接在一起。它引领我们去体会那些位于我们想象边缘的世界。“……就像我一样。”与此同时，它也能揭示塑造我们自身世界、塑造我们自身特定历史时刻的具体假设。

Great art connects us across the ages. It invites us to empathize with worlds at the very edge of our imaginative horizons. “… just like me.” At the same time, it can reveal to us the specific assumptions that shape our own worlds, our own particular moments in history.

有些文化优先考虑会议的效率和秩序，而另一些文化则将会议作为巩固联盟、在参与者之间建立权力的手段。在某些文化中，午餐是两小时的盛宴，而在另一些文化中，午餐只需十分钟就能吃完。在某些圈子里，雄心壮志受到赞赏和赞扬，而在其他圈子里，雄心壮志则遭到贬低和嘲笑。这些潜规则看似遥远，却又近在咫尺。只有当我们敏锐地观察到它们，或者当它们被打破时，它们才会凸显出来。例如，只有当新员工要求获得高管头衔时，公司员工才会意识到这种文化对等级制度的蔑视。

Some cultures prioritize efficiency and order in their meetings, while other cultures use meetings as a way to secure alliances and establish power between players. Lunch is a two-hour feast in some cultures and a ten-minute sandwich in others. Ambition is admired and celebrated in certain circles, and denigrated and mocked in others. These unspoken rules are far away, but so close. They only come to the fore when we keenly observe them or when they break down. It is only when a new hire at work demands an executive title, for example, that company employees become aware of the culture’s disdain for hierarchy.

当我们进行意义建构时，我们不再将房间视为一个堆满个体物品的空间，而是开始观察构成文化现实的结构。在算法思维中，一瓶香水的定义取决于其中含有多少毫克液体；一支笔是一块附着金属的塑料。相比之下，意义建构将万物与其他事物联系起来感知。在约会的世界里，香水就像口红、高跟鞋和短信一样，成为一种装备。钢笔，以及文字处理器、纸张和书籍，都是写作世界的一部分。钢笔、香水、锤子、文字处理器：我们生活中的一切都与其他事物息息相关。没有任何东西存在于个体的真空中。

When we practice sensemaking, we stop seeing a room as a space filled with individual items and we start seeing the structures that form a cultural reality. In algorithmic thinking, a bottle of perfume is defined by how many milligrams of liquid exist within it; a pen is a piece of plastic with metal attached to it. In contrast, sensemaking perceives everything in relationship to everything else. The perfume becomes equipment—along with lipstick, high heels, and text messages—in the world of dating. The pen, along with a word processor and paper and books, is part of the world of writing. Pens, perfume, hammers, word processors: everything in our lives has some bearing on everything else. Nothing exists in an individual vacuum.

哲学家们给这个概念起了很多名字。皮埃尔·布迪厄称之为“惯习”；埃内斯托·拉克劳和米歇尔福柯称之为“话语”，还有一些人称之为“我们的对话”或“谈话”。所有这些思想家都受益于海德格尔，是他第一个发现了所谓的“存在”，或背景实践。

Philosophers give this concept many names. Pierre Bourdieu would call it “habitus”; Ernesto Laclau and Michel Foucault referred to it as “the discourse,” and still others dubbed it “our conversation” or “the conversation.” All of these various thinkers are indebted to Heidegger, who was the first to discover what he called “Being,” or background practices.

尽管哲学家们近一个世纪以来一直在阐述这一概念，但在现代社会，它却常常被遗忘或忽视。在量化分析占据主导地位的领域——首先想到的是企业和金融机构，以及日益增多的教育和医疗机构——这些共享世界和背景实践的概念显得过于激进。想想公司或政治竞选活动试图了解市场和选民的方式：他们询问人们的想法。在焦点小组或问卷调查中，他们将人们带离日常生活，并向他们抛出关于独立想法、产品或政策理念的问题。通过脱离背景的经验——将不同的世界割裂开来，试图拼凑出一个个事实——他们几乎错过了所有能够阐明人类行为的线索。这就是为什么他们的结论大多数时候都是错误的。

Although philosophers have been describing this concept for close to a century now, it is too often forgotten or disregarded in our modern world. In realms where quantitative analysis reigns supreme—corporations and financial firms come to mind, as do, increasingly, education and health institutions—these notions of shared worlds and background practices are radical. Just think about the way companies or political campaigns try to understand markets and voters: they ask people what they think. In a focus group or a survey, they take people out of the context of their regular lives and pepper them with questions about discrete ideas, products, or policy ideas. By decontextualizing experiences—pulling worlds apart in an attempt to create an assembly of facts—they miss almost everything that can shed light on human behavior. This is why their conclusions are wrong most of the time.

“文化而非个人”这一概念，对普遍持有的认为人类行为基于个人选择、偏好和逻辑结构的观念，提供了重要的修正。我们将在第三章深入探讨共享世界的结构及其重要性。

The concept of “culture—not individuals” serves as an essential corrective to the widely held belief that human behavior is based on individual choices, preferences, and logical structures. We will delve deeper into the structure and importance of shared worlds in Chapter Three.

2. 厚数据——而不仅仅是薄数据

2. Thick Data— Not Just Thin Data

如果意义建构关注的是文化，而不是个体，那么意义建构的数据就具有完全不同的质感。例如，对法国文化的研究会很枯燥。如果只包含来自经济合作与发展组织（OECD）的数据，那么它就显得太复杂，太技术化了。那么，那些能够传达大量关于法国生活的触觉和内在数据呢——一块新鲜的面包或一杯波尔多葡萄酒？阅读兰波的诗歌或聆听赛日·甘斯布的歌曲又如何呢？虽然这些活动无疑能给我们带来快乐，但它们也是构建意义的关键数据。

If sensemaking is interested in cultures, not individuals, it follows, then, that sensemaking data has a completely different texture. A study of French culture, for example, would be dry and technical if it only included data from the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD). What about the tactile and visceral pieces of data that communicate so much about French life—a loaf of fresh bread or a glass of Bordeaux? What about reading the poetry of Rimbaud or listening to a song by Serge Gainsbourg? Though these are certainly pursuits that bring us pleasure, they are also pieces of data that are essential to sensemaking.

1973年，人类学家克利福德·格尔茨（Clifford Geertz）创造了“厚描写”（thick description）一词，用以描述他的民族志田野笔记。他不仅对人类行为感兴趣，更关注这些行为与更广阔的文化背景之间的关系。格尔茨在其学术生涯的大部分时间里，致力于探究文化复杂手势的细微差别，以及赋予生活深度的“厚描写”。以眨眼为例：计算机可能将其归类为持续一毫秒的眼部抽搐，但我们都知道，眨眼的含义远不止于此。这个细微的动作能够传达“我不认真”、“我们一起走吧”、“你是个白痴”以及其他许多难以言喻的信息。

In 1973, anthropologist Clifford Geertz developed the term thick description to characterize his ethnographic field notes. He was interested not just in human behavior but in how that behavior related to the greater cultural context. Geertz spent the lion’s share of his academic career writing about the nuances of culturally complex gestures, the thickness that adds depth to life. Take the wink as an example: the computer might classify it as a twitch of the eye lasting for a millisecond, but we all know that a wink can mean so much more. This tiny movement has the ability to communicate “I’m not serious,” “Let’s leave together,” “You’re an idiot,” and so many other, more ineffable messages.

受格尔茨（Geertz）这句话的启发，我喜欢把构建意义的数据称为“厚数据”，因为它表达了一种文化中有意义的部分。厚数据不仅捕捉事实，还捕捉这些事实的背景。例如，86% 的美国家庭每周饮用超过六夸脱（约 6 夸脱）的牛奶，但他们为什么喝牛奶？牛奶是什么样的？一个重 0.09 磅的苹果和一克蜂蜜是薄数据。相比之下，一顿犹太新年餐点里淋上蜂蜜的苹果才是厚数据。

Taking inspiration from Geertz’s phrase, I like to call sensemaking data “thick data” because it expresses what is meaningful about a culture. Thick data captures not just facts but the context of those facts. Eighty-six percent of households in America drink more than six quarts of milk per week, for example, but why do they drink milk? And what is it like? An apple weighing .09 pound and a gram of honey is thin data. A Rosh Hashanah meal with apples dipped in honey, by contrast, is thick data.

试想一下：如果你现在正坐在椅子上，你很清楚把椅子往后推会发出什么声音。如果你掉下一张纸，你会怎样？从四英尺高的地方抛下它，让它飘落直到落地？你知道它离开你双手时的感觉；你知道它下落时会轻轻地来回飘动；你知道它会静静地落地。想一想你所知道的一切。你知道一杯咖啡什么时候有点太冷；你知道雷雨前外面是什么感觉；当你看着伴侣的眼睛时，你知道有什么不对劲。哲学家们称之为我们对世界的熟悉。这是我们处理生活和度过每一天的背景。

Think about it this way: if you are sitting in a chair right now, you know with quite some detail what the sound will be if you push the chair back. What if you drop a piece of paper from four feet and let it float down until it hits the floor? You know how it will feel when it leaves your hands; you know that its fall will be characterized by a gentle wafting back and forth; you know that it will land silently. Just think for a moment about all the stuff you know. You know when a cup of coffee is just a touch too cold; you know how it feels outside just before a thunderstorm; you know something is wrong when you look in your partner’s eyes. Philosophers have called this our familiarity with the world. It is the background upon which we deal with our lives and go through our days.

这种知识并非平庸之辈，而是我们与世界互动的方式。它体现在我们在超市挑选商品的方式、烹饪方式、相互理解的方式以及砍树的方式。我们运用这些知识理解世界，并在其中穿梭。人工智能研究人员不断尝试复制这些知识，却不可避免地犯错。正是这些知识构成了厚数据。

This type of knowledge is not a banal fact; it is the very way we deal with the world. It is how we choose things in the supermarket, how we cook, read each other, and chop down a tree. We make sense of the world and get around in it using this knowledge. It is what AI researchers continually attempt to copy and inevitably get wrong. This is the knowledge that makes up thick data.

由于厚数据不像薄数据那样具有普遍适用性，它常常被认为不够充分或缺乏严谨性。但现实是，我们的生活被厚数据所主宰。当我们在决策中忽略它，或试图忽略它时，我们就是在运用一种错误的人性模型。在商业环境中，这种对人的误解可能会带来灾难性的后果。毕竟，商业几乎总是在押注于人的行为：哪种产品最有可能畅销，哪位员工最有可能成功，客户愿意支付的价格是多少。擅长押注这些行为的公司往往在市场上蓬勃发展。而做出这类致命押注的唯一方法就是更好地了解人。

Because it is not universally applicable like thin data, thick data is often dismissed as insufficient or lacking rigor. But the reality is that our lives are dominated by thick data. When we leave it out of our decisions—or attempt to ignore it—we are working with a faulty model of humanity. In a business context, this misunderstanding of people can have disastrous consequences. After all, business is almost always about making bets on human behavior: which product is most likely to sell, which employee is most likely to succeed, what price is a customer willing to pay. Companies that excel at making these bets tend to thrive in the marketplace. And the only way to make these types of killer bets is to understand people better.

厚数据与薄数据形成鲜明对比——当你观察我们的行动和行为轨迹时，你会得到这样的数据：我们每天旅行多少次；我们在网上搜索什么内容；我们睡了多少个小时；我们有多少社交联系；我们听什么类型的音乐等等。这些数据是通过你浏览器中的cookies、你手腕上的Fitbit智能手环或你手机中的GPS收集的。这些人类行为的特性无疑很重要，但它们并非故事的全部。

Thick data stands in direct contrast with thin data—the sort of data you get when you look at the traces of our actions and behaviors: we travel this much every day; we search for that on the Internet; we sleep this many hours; we have this many social connections; we listen to this type of music, and so forth. It’s the data gathered by the cookies in your browser, the Fitbit on your wrist, or the GPS in your phone. These properties of human behavior are undoubtedly important, but they are not the whole story.

如果说瘦数据试图根据我们的行为来理解我们，那么厚数据则试图从我们与所处众多不同世界的关系的角度来理解我们。正因如此，情绪是厚数据最显著的形式之一。例如，我们可以一致认为办公室里的气氛很沉闷，或者派对才刚刚开始。我们可以体会到沉浸在体育比赛的兴奋之中或政治示威的狂热之中是什么感觉。我们都能感受到某个文化时刻的悲伤——“9·11那天你在哪里？”——也能感受到在新闻中听到勇敢行为时那种具有感染力的喜悦。如果我们的同事告诉我们，她觉得公司现在还没有准备好改变——“周围的压力太大了”——我们会点头表示同意。当我们适应这类数据时，就能感受到周围世界微妙而持续的变化。

If thin data seeks to understand us based on what we do, thick data seeks to understand us in terms of how we relate to the many different worlds we inhabit. This is precisely why moods are one of our most salient forms of thick data. For example, we can agree, between us, that the mood in the office is dull or the party is just getting started. We can know what it is like to be caught up in the excitement of a sports game or the fervor of a political demonstration. We can all feel the sadness of a cultural moment—“Where were you on 9/11?”—as well as the infectious joy that takes hold when we hear about a courageous act on the news. If our colleague tells us that she feels the organization isn’t ready for change right now—There’s too much stress around here—we nod our heads and agree. When we are attuned to this kind of data, we can sense the subtle but constantly evolving changes of the worlds all around us.

为什么这种协调如此重要？毕竟，市场调研和技术报告不就是用来做这些的吗？尽管掌权者认为如此，但领导者和关键的战略思想家几乎总是被层层抽象的概念所包围。我亲眼目睹过许多企业高管的脸——他们训练有素，以展现镇定和能力——在面对这些时，却因震惊而变得苍白。他们无法真正理解自身业务、客户以及世界的本质。经营制鞋公司的高管们经常会免费获得一双鞋——许多人做梦也想不到会去 Foot Locker 或 DSW。他们缺乏关于鞋店现状的真实数据——价格问题、商品陈列问题、尺码缺失问题等等。许多汽车行业的高管自进入汽车行业以来就没有买过自己的车。他们对客户的世界了解多少？如果没有这种亲身体验，这些高管眼前的数据就失去了真实性。背景和色彩都消失了；剩下的只是对世界的抽象描述，而不是世界本身。

Why is this attunement such an imperative? After all, isn’t this what market research and technical reports are for? Despite what people in power assume, leaders and key strategic thinkers are almost always surrounded by layers and layers of abstraction. I have watched the faces of many top executives in the corporate world—faces trained to project composure and competence—turn white with shock when confronted with the raw reality of their business, its customers, and the world. Executives who run companies that make shoes often get their own shoes for free—many wouldn’t dream of entering a Foot Locker or a DSW. They don’t have real data on the reality of going to the shoe store—the problems of price, of presentation, of missing sizes. Many car executives haven’t bought their own vehicle since entering the industry. What do they know about the world of their customers? Without this texture of experience, the data shoved before these executives’ eyes loses any truth. Context and color are absent; all that remains are abstract representations of the world rather than the world itself.

简而言之，高层领导者的想象力和直觉正在枯竭。他们一直依赖枯燥的事实和数据——单薄的数据，被剥夺了所有有机生命。这种饮食或许能帮助他们度过相对稳定的时期，但当市场发生变化时，他们很可能会偏离轨道。在不断变化的环境中，重新与人类的情感——甚至是本能——联系起来至关重要。这正是厚数据发挥作用的地方。

Simply put, the imaginations and intuitions of top leaders are starving. They have been living on a diet of desiccated facts and figures—thin data stripped of all its organic life. This diet may sustain them through periods of relative stability, but they will likely be headed off course when markets shift. In the midst of changing circumstances, it is vital to reconnect with the emotional—even the visceral—context of humanity. This is where thick data comes in.

3. 大草原——不是动物园

3. The Savannah— Not the Zoo

我们要去哪里获取更深入的数据？我们必须从研究人性本身，去理解生活世界的复杂性和美感。这正是我们将要探索的一种哲学方法的基础，它被称为“现象学”，即研究人类经验的学科。通过现象学，我们观察的是存在于社会情境中的人类行为，而不是抽象的数字。这就像观察一群狮子在真实的地面上捕猎一样大草原，以及在动物园里看到它们用碗喂食。严格来说，这两种情况下狮子都在吃东西。你认为哪种情况更真实？

Where do we go to get more thick data? We must start by studying humanity in the full complexity and beauty of the lived world. This is the basis of a philosophical method we will discover called “phenomenology,” or the study of human experiences. With phenomenology, we are observing human behavior as it exists in social contexts, not in abstract numbers. It’s the difference between watching a pack of lions hunt on the actual savannah and seeing them get fed from a bowl in the zoo. The lions are technically eating in both scenarios. Which one do you think holds more truth?

以爱情为例。2012年，“什么是爱情”是谷歌搜索次数最多的关键词。生物人类学家海伦·费舍尔（Helen Fisher）给出了一个答案，获得了大量点击量。基于功能磁共振成像（fMRI）的结果，费舍尔和她的同事得出结论：“浪漫爱情”并非一种情绪，而是一种动机系统——一种不由自主的化学反应。我们爱，是因为它激励我们与潜在的伴侣建立关系。

Take the question of love as an example. In 2012, “what is love” was the most searched query on Google. Helen Fisher, a biological anthropologist, offered an answer that received a significant number of hits. Based on fMRI results, Fisher and her colleagues concluded that “romantic love” is not an emotion, but a motivation system—an involuntary chemical reaction. We love because it incentivizes us to engage in relationships with potential mates.

这就是实验室或动物园里的爱情，但费舍尔的解释并没有告诉我们我们是如何体验爱情的。历史学家告诉我们，浪漫爱情实际上只是一种近代现象。在古印度，爱情被视为对社会结构的危险破坏；在中世纪，爱情甚至被认为近乎疯狂。那么，今天的爱情究竟是什么呢？成千上万的离婚律师会反驳费舍尔关于动机系统的解释。只有通过观察人们在现实世界中的行为和经历，才能洞察爱情的运作方式。

That is what love looks like in the laboratory or the zoo, but Fisher’s explanation tells us nothing about how we experience love. Historians tell us that romantic love is really only a recent phenomenon. In ancient India, love was seen as dangerously disruptive to social structures, and during the Middle Ages, love was considered akin to insanity. What is love today? Thousands of divorce lawyers would argue against Fischer’s explanation of a motivation system. Insights about how love works are only possible by observing what people do and experience in the real world.

研究人类经验的方法论并非关注非凡之事，而是关注我们所有人（或大多数人）的平凡和共通之处。它与“r²”或显著的样本量无关。事实上，相对较少的人数及其处境就足够了。为了充分了解我们所有人共有的行为模式，应该收集并理解这些经验。这种方法能够让领导力与他们所服务的对象真正接触。

The methodology of studying human experience is not interested in what is extraordinary, but what is ordinary and common for all (or most) of us. It isn’t about the “r2,” or the significant sample size. In fact, a relatively small number of people and their situations will suffice. These experiences should be collected and understood in order to fully see the patterns of behavior we all share. It is a method that brings leadership in actual touch with the people they purport to serve.

当然，我经常听到我身边的高管说，他们想要通过发现顾客、客户或员工的“痛点”或“未满足的需求”来帮助他们。在我看来，这些说法仍然传达了一种令人遗憾的距离感。他们居高临下地看待他人，将他们的经验抽象化。如果你想真正了解你身边的人，你必须与他们平视。你必须做他们做的事，看他们所见的。但即便如此，这还不够。如果你真的想了解一种文化，诀窍在于发现它的“灵魂”——它的艺术遗产、它的历史、它的习俗。没有比研究人类经验更好的训练场地来培养这种视角了。

Of course, I often hear executives in my world say that they want to help their customers, clients, or employees by finding their “pain points” or “unmet needs.” To me, these phrases still communicate an unfortunate distance. They are looking down at people and abstracting their experience from on high. If you want to truly understand the people in your world, you must engage with them at eye level. You must do what they do and see what they see. But even that is not enough. If you really want to understand something about a culture, the trick is to see its ghosts—its artistic heritage, its history, its customs. There is no better training ground for such a perspective than the study of human experience.

4. 创造力——而非制造

4. Creativity— Not Manufacturing

在实地考察并参与人文学科以更好地理解世界之后，我们如何通过意义建构获得真正的洞见？在哪些情况下可以运用假设并进行检验？什么时候最好完全不抱有任何先入为主的观念？这些是通过问题推理的不同方式：这是数百年来关于科学方法的争论的核心问题。19世纪末，美国哲学家兼逻辑学家查尔斯·桑德斯·皮尔士因定义了我们用来解决问题的三种推理方式——演绎、归纳和溯因——而闻名，每种推理方式都适用于不同的确定性程度。

After spending time in the field and engaging with the humanities to better understand the world, how do we achieve actual insights through sensemaking? In which situations is it okay to use a hypothesis and test it out? When is it better not to have any preconceived notions at all? These are different ways of reasoning through a problem: a concern at the center of a centuries-old debate about the scientific method. In the late 1800s, American philosopher and logician Charles Sanders Peirce became famous for defining the three kinds of reasoning we use to solve problems—deduction, induction, and abduction—each one appropriate for different levels of certainty.

演绎推理通常被称为自上而下的推理，因为它始于一个更普遍的定律或理论——一个假设——然后尝试将其应用于具体事例。“所有女人都会死。莎莉是女人。”因此，我们可以推断出：“莎莉是凡人。”演绎推理适用于受约束的设置边界的问题，但无法纳入新信息。

Deduction is often called top-down reasoning because it starts with a more general law or theory—a hypothesis—and then attempts to apply it in specific instances. “All women are mortal. Sally is a woman.” Therefore we can deduce: “Sally is mortal.” Deductive reasoning is useful for constrained problems with set boundaries, but it is unable to incorporate new information.

另一方面，归纳推理与演绎推理截然相反。它自下而上，因此从具体的观察开始，然后逐步形成理论。“莎莉是一名医生。”根据我们对莎莉的观察，我们可以补充说：“莎莉刚完成学业。”由此，我们可以推断出一个解释或理论：“莎莉毕业于医学院。”但是，当你进行归纳推理时，你会将自己局限于一套信念——这对于某些类型的已知和未知问题来说当然有效——但对于涉及文化和行为的问题则不再适用。我们可以观察到莎莉是一名医生，然后推断出莎莉上过医学院，但这种框架可能与我们试图解决的问题无关或无意义。如果我们试图在一个完全不同的文化背景下理解莎莉，比如她作为幼儿母亲的世界，或者她作为城镇政治舞台上活跃成员的世界，会怎么样？在这些情况下，归纳推理会在我们了解调查背景之前就将可能的洞见拒之门外。

Inductive reasoning, on the other hand, is the exact opposite of deductive reasoning. It is bottom-up, so it starts with specific observations and then moves up into a theory. “Sally is a doctor.” From our observation of Sally, we can then add: “Sally just finished school.” And from there, we can infer an explanation or a theory: “Sally graduated from medical school.” But when you reason inductively, you have limited yourself to one set of beliefs—all well and good for certain types of problems with set knowns and unknowns—but no longer useful for problems involving culture and behavior. We can observe that Sally is a doctor and then infer that Sally went to medical school, but this framing might not be relevant or meaningful for the problem we are trying to solve. What if we are trying to understand Sally in a completely different cultural context: her world as a mother to small children, or her world as an active member of the local political scene in her town? In these instances, inductive reasoning will shut out possible insights before we even know the context of our investigation.

皮尔斯认为，只有溯因推理（或非线性问题求解）才能产生新的想法。他将这种推理定义为一种有根据的猜测，适用于在观察到没有固定或逻辑解释的现象后做出的推断。以下是一系列观察结果中的一个简单示例：房子里的一扇窗户坏了；珠宝盒不见了；家具被翻倒了，衣服散落在各处。通过溯因推理，我们一跃而上，得出最合理的结论：这房子被盗了。

Peirce contended that only abductive reasoning—or nonlinear problem solving—was capable of generating new ideas. He defined this type of reasoning as a kind of educated guess, appropriate after observing phenomena with no set or logical explanation. Here is a simple example from a series of observations: A window is broken in the house; the jewelry box is missing; the furniture has been overturned, and there are clothes scattered everywhere. Through abductive reasoning, we make a leap into the most reasonable conclusion: The house has been robbed.

对皮尔斯来说，溯因推理就是寻找答案。尽管过去几百年科学蓬勃发展，人们相信工业时代可以征服一切，但皮尔斯在其《逻辑第一规则》（1899年）中，质疑了我们自以为知道的东西。“不要阻挡探究之路，​​”他说道，并概述了我们在推理时会犯下的以下四种错误：

For Peirce, abduction was about looking for answers. While the previous few hundred years had been about the development of science and the belief that the industrial age could conquer anything, Peirce, in his First Rule of Logic (1899), questioned what we thought we knew. “Do not block the way of inquiry,” he said, and he outlined these following four offenses that we commit when we reason:

1. 我们绝对坚信我们是正确的。

1. We make an absolute assertion that we’re right.

2. 我们认为某些事情是不可知的，因为我们没有技术或手段去弄清楚它。

2. We believe something isn’t knowable because we don’t have the techniques or technologies to figure it out.

3. 我们坚持认为，科学的某些元素是完全无法解释和不可知的。

3. We insist that some element of science is utterly inexplicable and unknowable.

4. 我们相信某些法则或真理是处于最终的、完美的状态。

4. We believe that some law or truth is in its final and perfect state.

皮尔士否认任何理论都是“真”，而认为理论可以“接近真”。换句话说，他相信理论总有改进的空间，新的真理也不断涌现。

Peirce rejected the notion that any theory was “true,” while maintaining that it could be “near true.” In other words, he believed there was always room for improvement, and endless potential for new truths to emerge.

不难理解为什么科学家们会驳斥“事情不可能有结果”这一观点——事实并非必然具有决定性。我们都希望自己的工作包含一定程度的确定性，而生活在持续的怀疑阴影下令人不快。皮尔斯在其1877年的论文《信念的固着》中谈到了这种不适：

It’s easy to see why scientists would dismiss the idea that you cannot come to the end of something—that facts are not necessarily conclusive. We all want our work to contain some measure of certainty, and living in the constant shadow of doubt is unpleasant. Peirce speaks to this discomfort in his 1877 essay “The Fixation of Belief”:

怀疑是一种不安和不满足的状态，我们努力摆脱这种状态，进入信仰状态；而信仰是一种平静和满足的状态我们不想回避它，也不想改变对其他任何事情的信仰。

Doubt is an uneasy and dissatisfied state from which we struggle to free ourselves and pass into the state of belief; while the latter is a calm and satisfactory state which we do not wish to avoid, or to change to a belief in anything else.

他最终指出，我们紧紧抓住过时的、有时甚至是愚蠢的想法不放，就是为了避免停留在这种“不安和不满的状态”。换句话说，我们经常做出非常糟糕的决定，只是因为思考这种艰苦的工作太不舒服了。我指的不是演绎或归纳意义上的思考——通过一系列合乎逻辑的线性步骤来推理问题。我指的是那种能带来所有创造性洞察力的思维方式：充满曲折、死胡同和意想不到的突破。溯因推理是混乱的。对于我们大多数人来说，长时间保持这种怀疑状态是极其困难的。但怀疑是唯一能让我们获得新理解的状态。这才是创造力的真实故事。

He ultimately argued that we hold fast to outdated and sometimes downright foolish ideas just to avoid staying in this “uneasy and dissatisfied state.” In other words, we often make really poor decisions just because it is so uncomfortable to do the hard work of thinking. And I don’t mean thinking in the deductive or inductive sense of the word—reasoning through a problem with a logical and linear set of steps. I mean the type of thinking that leads to all creative insights: filled with twists and turns, dead ends, and unexpected breakthroughs. Abductive reasoning is messy. It is extremely difficult for most of us to remain in this state of doubt for an indeterminate amount of time. But doubt is the only state of being that will open us up to new understanding. This is the real story of creativity.

5. 北极星——不是GPS

5. The North Star— Not the GPS

我们似乎生活在一个前所未有的复杂时代。世界告诉我们，周围发生的巨变之快，已令我们无力看清全局。无论是身处电视行业，试图驾驭亚马逊、Hulu 和 Netflix 等流媒体内容提供商的崛起，还是饱受无休止且相互矛盾的健康研究困扰的医学从业者，都很容易接受这些令人难以忍受的复杂性论断。我们只想举手投降，求助于身边的机器：大数据和算法编程肯定能解释这一切。而我们人类，却再也无法做到这一点。

We seem to live in an era of unprecedented complexity. Our world tells us that the pace of the seismic change occurring around us has rendered us incapable of seeing the big picture. Whether we are in the TV industry, attempting to navigate the emergence of streaming content providers like Amazon, Hulu, and Netflix, or medical practitioners barraged by an unending stream of often contradictory health studies, it is easy to accept these claims of overwhelming complexity. We want to throw up our hands and turn to the machines all around us: surely big data and algorithmic programming can make some sense of all of this. We, as humans, no longer can.

请允许我给你一个惊喜：我相信我们的世界实际上并没有比以往更加复杂，也并没有更加难以理解。没错，我们拥有互联网和可穿戴计算设备的普及，但我的祖母经历了两次世界大战的破坏、青霉素的发现，以及大规模生产、投资银行和太空旅行的发明。她经历了农业革命，见证了大规模饥荒，随后出现了如今产量足以满足所有人需求（如果分配得当）的粮食体系。这些只是在她那个时代彻底改变世界的众多创新中的一小部分。是的，我们正在经历变革。变革是翻天覆地的变化吗？我的祖母会说：“并非如此。”

Allow me to surprise you: I believe that our world is actually no more complex than it has ever been, nor is it more incomprehensible. Yes, we have the Internet and the proliferation of wearable computing, but my grandmother experienced the destruction of two world wars, the discovery of penicillin, and the inventions of mass production, investment banking, and space travel. She lived through the agricultural revolution, witnessing mass starvation followed by a food system that now produces more than enough for everyone (when distributed intelligently). These are only a few of the innovations that utterly transformed her world during her time. Yes, we are living through change. Is it seismic? My grandmother would say, “Not really.”

当今世界令人感到无比复杂，因为我们执着于将其整理成一堆事实。大数据让我们觉得自己能够、也应该知晓世间一切。但这种追求是愚蠢的，它会让所有参与其中的人感到精疲力竭、迷失方向。我们如此执着于GPS的指引，却对头顶上闪耀的星空失去了所有的感知。导航工具一直以来都触手可及，但我们必须承担起解读它们的责任。这意味着，高管们需要做好准备，去理解新的、不熟悉的背景——政治、技术、文化——并解读它们在我们日益相互依存的世界中的位置。
