Today’s world feels overwhelmingly complex because we are obsessed with organizing it as an assembly of facts. Big data makes us feel as though we can and should know everything there is to know on earth. But this is a fool’s quest, and it leaves everyone involved feeling depleted and lost. We are so fixated on staring at the oracle of the GPS that we have lost all sensitivity to the stars shining right above our heads. The tools of navigation have always been available to all of us. But we must take responsibility for interpreting them. This means executives need to be prepared to understand new and unfamiliar contexts—political, technological, cultural—and to interpret their place in our increasingly interdependent world.

意义建构最大的贡献就在于此：它教会我们大数据时代领导力的两个基本要素。首先，意义建构可以指导我们选择合适的数据收集环境。毕竟，单纯的数据收集任务在抽象层面上毫无意义。我们收集什么数据？什么目的？怎么做？如果没有某种范式来思考你想研究什么，就不可能研究世界。

Therein lies sensemaking’s greatest offering: it teaches us two essential things about leadership in an era of big data. To begin with, sensemaking can guide us in selecting an appropriate context for data collection. After all, the mere task of collecting data is meaningless in the abstract. What data do we collect? What for? How? It is impossible to study the world without some sort of paradigm for thinking about what you want to study.

其次，意义建构告诉我们如何培养一种视角，将数据整合成一幅富有表现力的肖像。领导者必须找到一个能够运用数据拼凑出丰富世界观的团队，最终的解读能够产生比收集到的数据更深刻的成果。

Secondly, sensemaking shows us how to cultivate a perspective on how data fits together as an expressive portrait. Leaders must find a team who can use data to piece together a richly textured view of the world, in which resulting interpretations can add up to something greater than the data collected.

通过这种方式，意义建构教会我们将注意力放在哪里。我们并非试图了解一切；我们努力去理解某些事物。在复杂的环境中，意义建构练习使我们能够确定真正重要的事情。

In this way, sensemaking teaches us where to put our attention. We don’t try to know everything; we work to make sense of something. In the midst of complexity, a sensemaking practice allows us to determine what actually matters.

例如，食品业务不仅仅关乎市场进入计划、资本投资和产品定位。它还关乎理解我们作为一种文化与食物的关系。我们如何消费食物；如何分享食物；食物对我们意味着什么。战略不仅关乎财务，也关乎文化、人、情感、行为和需求。

The business of food products, for example, is not just about market entry plans, capital investment, and product positioning. It is about understanding how we, as a culture, sit in relationship to food. How we consume it; how we share it; what it means to us. Strategy is about finance but also about culture, people, emotions, behavior, and needs.

意义建构实践并非试图简化人类所有层面的复杂性——就像GPS导航仪通过简化路径来决定旅程一样——而是追随北极星。我们学会在丰富的现实世界中导航，形成一种精准的视角，洞察我们身在何处以及未来将走向何方。如果说算法思维给我们带来了客观性的幻觉——或者说一种来自虚无缥缈的视角——那么意义建构则让我们能够确定自身所在之处。最重要的是，意义建构让我们能够触及我们前进的方向。

Instead of attempting to reduce the complexity of all of these layers of humanity—like a journey determined by the reductions of a GPS—the sensemaking practice follows the North Star. We learn to navigate through the rich reality of our world, developing a finely honed perspective on where we are and where we are headed. If algorithmic thinking offers us the illusion of objectivity—or a view from nowhere—then sensemaking allows us determine where we are. And, most important, sensemaking puts us in touch with where we are headed.

然而，在我们开启这段旅程之前，我们有必要更明确地了解一下，究竟是什么文化在极力推崇用算法理解世界。这种信念在任何地方都最为广泛。“硅谷”。我之所以用引号来称呼它，是因为我指的不仅仅是旧金山湾区南部的那片土地。硅谷如今已成为一种意识形态，一种将硬科学知识置于所有其他知识形式之上的思维模式。它的文化特权如今已渗透到我们现代生活的方方面面，包括商业、教育、医疗、媒体和政府。在探讨意义建构的紧迫性之前，我们必须先更彻底地驳斥硅谷思维模式所秉持的那些假设。

Before we can begin the journey, however, it is important to situate ourselves more specifically in the culture that vehemently advances the tenets of an algorithmic understanding of the world. Nowhere is this belief more widely held than in “Silicon Valley.” I write the name in quotes because I am not just referring to the strip of land in the southern San Francisco Bay Area. Silicon Valley is now an ideology, a mindset that values knowledge from the hard sciences above all other forms of knowing. Its cultural prerogatives have now seeped into every aspect of our modern life, including business, education, health care, media, and government. We cannot talk about the urgency of sensemaking without first making a stop to more fully dismantle the assumptions upheld in a Silicon Valley state of mind.

第二章

Chapter Two

硅谷是一种心态

Silicon Valley Is a State of Mind

“数据！数据！数据！”他不耐烦地喊道。“没有黏土，我做不了砖！”

“Data! Data! Data!” he cried impatiently. “I can’t make bricks without clay!”

——阿瑟·柯南·道尔，《铜滩历险记》

—Arthur Conan Doyle, The Adventure of the Copper Beaches

图书馆将永存；它就是宇宙。至于我们，一切并非皆已书写；我们并非化为幻影。我们漫步于走廊，翻阅书架，重新排列，在纷繁嘈杂、语无伦次的资料中寻找意义的线索，阅读过去和未来的历史，收集我们和他人的思想，时不时地瞥见镜子，从中我们或许能辨认出信息造物。

The library will endure; it is the universe. As for us, everything has not been written; we are not turning into phantoms. We walk the corridors, searching the shelves and rearranging them, looking for lines of meaning amid leagues of cacophony and incoherence, reading the history of the past and our future, collecting our thoughts and collecting the thoughts of others, and every so often glimpsing mirrors, in which we may recognize creatures of the information.

——豪尔赫·路易斯·博尔赫斯，《巴别图书馆》

—Jorge Luis Borges, “The Library of Babel”

在 2013 年与华尔街分析师的电话会议上，马克·扎克伯格告诉投资者，除了优先提高全球连通性和强调知识经济之外，Facebook 还致力于实现新的愿景他称之为“理解世界”。他描述了这种“理解”很快就会是什么样子：“每天，人们都会在图表（Facebook 的算法搜索机制）中发布数十亿条内容和联系，通过这种方式，他们正在帮助构建一个关于世界上所有事物的最清晰的模型。”

In a 2013 conference call with Wall Street analysts, Mark Zuckerberg told investors that, along with prioritizing increased connectivity across the globe and emphasizing a knowledge economy, Facebook was committed to a new vision called “understanding the world.” He described what this “understanding” would soon look like: “Every day, people post billions of pieces of content and connections into the graph [Facebook’s algorithmic search mechanism], and in doing this, they’re helping to build the clearest model of everything there is to know in the world.”

这只是目前硅谷众多宏大宣言中的一个。谷歌的使命宣言是“整合全球信息，使人人皆可访问并从中受益”。2013年，在接受《财富》杂志采访时， Jawbone软件副总裁杰里迈亚·罗宾逊（Jeremiah Robison）解释说，他们推出健身追踪设备Jawbone UP的目标是“理解行为改变的科学”。因创办Twitter和Square Inc.而声名鹊起的杰克·多西（Jack Dorsey）告诉满屋子的企业家，初创企业正在追随甘地和开国元勋们的脚步。在2014年的一份新闻稿中，Uber首席执行官兼联合创始人特拉维斯·卡兰尼克（Travis Kalanick）宣布，随着Uber的“成长和扩张，公司已从一家生机勃勃的硅谷科技初创企业发展成为全球数百万城市居民的生活方式”。通过这项工作，“我们为正义而战”。

This is only one of many grandiose claims coming out of Silicon Valley right now. Google’s mission statement is famously to “organize the world’s information and make it universally accessible and useful.” In a 2013 interview in Fortune, Jeremiah Robison, the vice president of software at Jawbone, explained that the goal with their fitness tracking device Jawbone UP was “to understand the science of behavior change.” Jack Dorsey, of Twitter and Square Inc. fame, told a room full of entrepreneurs that start-ups are following in the footsteps of Gandhi and the Founding Fathers. In a 2014 press release, Uber’s CEO and cofounder Travis Kalanick announced that with Uber’s “growth and expansion, the company has evolved from being a scrappy Silicon Valley tech start-up to being a way of life for millions of people in cities around the world.” With this work, “we fight the good fight.”

与美国经济低迷和政治僵局的持续叙事形成鲜明对比的是，硅谷愿景注入了希望和乐观。因此，硅谷的主导精神在美国文化生活中日益流行，随着我们对科技设备的依赖日益加深，以及我们日常生活越来越多地发生在互联网上，它扮演着更重要的角色。与任何社区一样，硅谷拥有强大的共同文化和愿景，这种文化和愿景它的成功归功于它。它的那些老掉牙的口号现在已经渗透到主流话语中：从“共享经济”到“跨越式发展”到“向前失败”到“精益创业”。尽管说法不同，但意识形态保持不变。承诺是技术将解决它——无论它是什么。解决方案肯定是革命性的。硅谷没有人会在创办一家初创公司时说：“我们将在过去五十年里所做的所有小的、渐进式的改变的基础上，在 X 领域做出小的、渐进式的改变。”一切都是颠覆：与过去彻底决裂，展望未来。

In contrast to the persistent narrative of American economic malaise and political gridlock, the Silicon Valley vision provides an infusion of hope and optimism. As a result, the reigning ethos of Silicon Valley has grown popular in American cultural life, assuming a greater role as our attachment to our technological devices has grown, and more and more of our daily life happens on the Internet. Like any community, Silicon Valley has a strong shared culture and outlook, one that it credits for its success. Its well-worn mantras have now seeped into mainstream discourse: everything from the “sharing economy” to “leapfrogging” to “fail forward” to the “lean start-up.” Despite the different phrases, the ideology remains the same. The promise is that technology will solve it—whatever it is. And the solution is sure to be revolutionary. No one in Silicon Valley ever launches a start-up by saying, “We will make small, incremental changes in the field of X based on all of the small, incremental changes that have been made over the last five decades.” Everything is a disruption: a clean break from the past leaning far forward into the future.

这种文化颠覆了我们教育子女的方式、经商的方式，以及我们对自身公民身份的认知。在此过程中，硅谷要么轻视人文教育，要么将其与21世纪的工作脱节。颇具影响力的风险投资家马克·安德森（Marc Andreessen）在其2014年的博客文章《文化冲突》（Culture Clash）中指出，文科教育落后于文化潮流，这体现了这种思维方式。他写道：“对于那些不深入数学、科学和技术的人来说，理解未来的世界将变得更加困难。”PayPal创始人兼投资者彼得·泰尔（Peter Thiel）甚至设立了泰尔奖学金（Thiel Fellowship），资助年轻创业者放弃大学学业，以便他们能够快速推进自己的创业项目。

The culture has upended the way we educate our children, the way we do our business, and the way we conceive of ourselves as citizens. In the process, Silicon Valley either belittles humanities-based education or renders it irrelevant to the work of the twenty-first century. Influential venture capitalist Marc Andreessen reflects this way of thinking when he argued in his 2014 blog post “Culture Clash” that the liberal arts are behind the cultural curve. “For people who aren’t deep into math and science and technology,” he wrote, “it is going to get far harder to understand the world going forward.” PayPal founder and investor Peter Thiel went so far as to establish the Thiel Fellowship, which pays young entrepreneurs to forgo university studies so that they might fast-track their start-up projects.

那么，在这种心态下，什么才是有价值的呢？让我们批判一下这种意识形态中一些主要的假设，以便更好地理解它是如何改变我们对知识生活的看法的。在“硅谷”心态下，意义建构从未如此匮乏，也从未如此迫切地需要。

So what is valued in this state of mind? Let’s critique some of the main assumptions at play in this ideology so we can better understand the way it is changing our notions of an intellectual life. In a “Silicon Valley” state of mind, sensemaking has never been more lacking or more urgently needed.

颠覆性创新背后的假设

Assumptions behind Disruptive Innovation

在硅谷，关于“颠覆”的讨论非常热烈。成功的企业家颠覆传统的做事方式；他们“颠覆”的不仅仅是销售产品，而是市场。当我们解读这种“颠覆”中隐含的假设时，就能深刻洞察硅谷对创新和进步的理解。用硅谷的话说，颠覆一个行业意味着“之前”和“之后”的彻底决裂。这体现了科学思维，即提出一个假设，并认为它具有可操作性和“正确性”，直到它被证明是错误的或被取代。只要这个假设经得起推敲，它就优先于所有先前的研究。当然，这只是暂时的；新的假设最终会取而代之。这是一门不断发展的学科。

There is a lot of talk about “disruption” in Silicon Valley. Successful entrepreneurs upend traditional ways of doing things; they “disrupt” a market, rather than simply selling a product. When we unpack the assumption implicit in this “disruption,” we gain a keen insight into the way that Silicon Valley thinks about innovation and progress. Disrupting an industry, in Silicon Valley parlance, suggests a clean break between “before” and “after.” This reflects scientific thinking, wherein a hypothesis is presented and it is regarded as operational and “true” until it is shown to be false, or is superseded. As long as that hypothesis holds up to scrutiny, it takes precedence over all previous work. This, of course, is temporary; a new hypothesis will eventually take its place. It’s a discipline that’s always moving forward.

这种思维方式与人文学科的思想传统形成鲜明对比。人文学科的思想传统并不主张知识的彻底断裂，也不认为过去的经验过时或过时。相反，它关注的是主导力量和态度如何塑造当代文化，以及恢复那些因时间流逝或空间距离而（有意或无意地）被遮蔽的知识和理解的可能性。正如T.S.艾略特在其1940年的诗歌《东科克》中所写：“唯有战斗才能恢复失去的一切/并一次又一次地找到和失去。”

This way of thinking stands in sharp contrast to the intellectual tradition of the humanities, which does not suggest clean breaks in knowledge, and does not regard past experience as outmoded or outdated. Instead, it focuses on the ways in which dominant powers and attitudes shape contemporary culture, and the possibility of recovery of knowledge and understanding that have been obscured (either intentionally or not) by the passage of time or the distance of space. As T. S. Eliot wrote in his 1940 poem “East Coker”: “There is only the fight to recover what has been lost / And found and lost again and again.”

但硅谷文化认为人文学科与职业生活几乎无关。颠覆就是拒绝既有的东西。硅谷想要彻底打破知识的积累。因为这种“颠覆”反映了一种普遍的认为创新需要无所畏惧的改变意愿以及与过去的决裂，这几乎只与年轻人有关。硅谷推崇缺乏经验的人，因为这样更容易承担风险。马克·扎克伯格在 2007 年斯坦福大学的一次活动上对与会者说：“年轻人就是更聪明”，这句话概括了一种流行的态度。风险投资家维诺德·科斯拉在 2011 年班加罗尔的一次科技活动上也呼应了这一观点，“45 岁以上的人基本上不会再有新想法了”。在这种环境下，拒绝传统的知识生活是理所当然的。一位不愿透露姓名的分析师告诉《纽约客》记者乔治·帕克：“如果你是硅谷的一名工程师，你就没有动力去读《经济学人》。”

But Silicon Valley culture feels that the humanities have little relevance to professional life. To disrupt is to reject what has come before. Silicon Valley wants a radical break with accumulated knowledge. Because this “disruption” reflects a widely held belief that innovation requires a fearless willingness to change and a break with the past, is it almost exclusively associated with youth. Silicon Valley celebrates inexperience because it makes it easier to take risks. Mark Zuckerberg summed up a popular attitude when he told attendees at a Stanford event in 2007 that “young people are just smarter.” Echoing this idea, venture capitalist Vinod Khosla told the audience at a 2011 tech event in Bangalore that “people over forty-five basically die in terms of new ideas.” In this environment, rejection of traditional intellectual life is de rigueur. An unnamed analyst told New Yorker journalist George Packer, “If you’re an engineer in Silicon Valley, you have no incentive to read The Economist.”

这种态度体现在对量化的痴迷上，对硅谷的年轻人来说，量化是智慧和经验的替代。量化有多种形式，其中包括“量化自我”运动，其追随者使用设备追踪和量化自身行为的各个方面。它也反映了美国社会普遍的量化趋势：在医疗保健、教育、政府以及个人生活中，量化无处不在。如今，我们通过“大数据”一词对此耳熟能详。

One way this attitude manifests itself is in an obsession with quantification, which for the youth of Silicon Valley is a stand-in for the knowledge of wisdom and experience. Quantification takes many forms, among them the “quantified self” movement, where adherents use devices to track and quantify aspects of their behavior. It also reflects a broad trend in American society toward quantification: in health care in education, in government, in our personal lives. This is now familiar to us through the term big data.

大数据背后的假设

Assumptions behind Big Data

大数据关注的是相关性，而非因果关系。它可以建立统计上显著的关系，但无法解释其背后的原因。随着数据集越来越大，出现具有误导性的统计显著相关性的风险也越来越大——这就像大海捞针。大数据提供信息，却不提供解释。对此，经济学家兼记者蒂姆·哈特福德 (Tim Hartford) 在 2014 年《金融时报》的一篇文章中写道： “大数据并不能解决几个世纪以来困扰统计学家和科学家的问题：洞察力的问题，推断正在发生的事情的问题，以及弄清楚我们如何进行干预以使系统变得更好的问题。”

Big data concerns itself with correlation, not causation. It can establish a statistically significant relationship, but it cannot explain why it is so. And with increasingly large data sets, there is an increased risk of misleading statistically significant correlations—it can appear that there are many needles in a very large haystack. Big data offers information without explanations for it. As economist and journalist Tim Hartford put it in a 2014 article for the Financial Times, “Big data does not solve the problem that has obsessed statisticians and scientists for centuries: the problem of insight, of inferring what is going on, and figuring out how we might intervene to change a system for the better.”

当大数据取代传统研究方法，而不是与传统研究方法并行时，会发生什么？谷歌流感趋势的案例为我们提供了一个突出的例子。2008年，谷歌的研究人员希望探索利用搜索词预测疾病大范围爆发的可能性。通过分离并追踪谷歌上与流感相关的搜索词，研究人员推测，他们可以比美国疾病控制与预防中心（CDC）的数据更早地预测流感爆发。研究人员利用一种被他们称为“临近预测”的技术，将他们的理论付诸实践，并将结果发表在《自然》杂志上。从各方面来看，这似乎都是一个巨大的成功。谷歌搜索预测的流感爆发比CDC的数据提前了两周。

What happens when big data is used instead of traditional research methods, rather than alongside them? The case of Google Flu Trends provides us with a salient example. In 2008, researchers at Google wanted to explore the idea of using search terms to predict widespread outbreaks of illness. By isolating flu-related queries on Google and tracking them, the researchers postulated that they could predict an outbreak of the flu sooner than the data from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Using a technique they dubbed “nowcasting,” the researchers put their theory into action and published the results in Nature. By all accounts, it seemed like a grand success. The Google queries were predicting flu outbreaks two weeks sooner than data coming from the CDC.

随后，谷歌流感趋势开始失灵。它错过了 2009 年的整个 H1N1 流感大流行，并严重高估了 2012-13 年流感季的流感爆发情况。在截至 2013 年的两年期间，科学家估计谷歌流感趋势在 108 周中 100 周的预测都偏高。到底出了什么问题？除其他问题外，谷歌的算法容易受到任何与流感季节相关但与实际流感爆发无关的查询的影响。因此，像“高中篮球”和“鸡汤”这样的搜索触发了流感警告——纯粹是偶然的关联，与流感病例没有真正的因果关系。这是因为大数据并不关心解释原因。相反，它反映了经验主义者的心态。大数据想要从等式，拥抱演绎思维，摒弃归纳探究模式。有了足够的数据，数字本身就能说明一切，无需理论。但是，正如我们在谷歌流感趋势案例中所发现的那样，需要更深入的分析才能使相关性产生影响，并建立因果关系。大数据无法简单地摆脱对传统研究方法的依赖；它的意义仍然源于对它的解读。尽管硅谷竭尽全力，但大数据永远不会保持中立。

And then Google Flu Trends started to fail. It missed the entire H1N1 pandemic in 2009 and wildly overestimated flu outbreaks in the 2012–13 season. In a two-year period ending in 2013, scientists estimated that Google Flu Trends predictions were high in 100 out of 108 weeks. What went wrong? Among other problems, Google’s algorithm was vulnerable to any queries that were related to flu season but not related to actual flu outbreaks. Therefore, searches like “high school basketball” and “chicken soup” ticked off a flu warning—correlation by pure chance with no real causal relationship to a case of the flu. This is because big data doesn’t care about explaining why. Instead, it reflects an empiricist’s mindset. Big data wants to remove human bias from the equation, embracing deductive thinking and jettisoning inductive modes of inquiry. With enough data, the numbers speak for themselves and you don’t need theory. But, as we discovered in the case of Google Flu Trends, deeper analysis is required for correlations to have implications, and to establish causality. Big data cannot simply shake off its reliance on traditional research methods; its meaning still comes out of its interpretation. Try as Silicon Valley might, big data will never be neutral.

尽管像谷歌流感趋势这样的案例暴露了大数据的局限性，硅谷的数据布道者们仍在继续宣扬大数据。他们的论点基于克里斯·安德森2008年发表在《连线》杂志上的一篇如今已成为传奇的文章，题为《理论的终结》。文章认为，我们过去解释系统的方式——通过模型和假设——正变得越来越不切实际，越来越难以接近真相。2008年，互联网、智能手机和CRM软件已经提供了海量数据。“数字说明了一切，”安德森写道，并引用了谷歌研究总监彼得·诺维格等商业领袖的话。“所有模型都是错误的，而且你越来越不需要它们就能取得成功。”最终，安德森采纳了诺维格的观点，并付诸实践：

Despite examples like Google Flu Trends that expose the limitations of big data, Silicon Valley’s data evangelists continue to proselytize. They base their arguments on a now-legendary 2008 Wired magazine article entitled “The End of Theory” by Chris Anderson. According to the article’s argument, the way we explained systems in the past—through models and hypotheses—is becoming an increasingly irrelevant, crude approximation to the truth. In 2008, the Internet, smartphones, and CRM software were already delivering a superabundance of data. “The numbers speak for themselves,” Anderson wrote as he quoted business leaders like Peter Norvig, director of research at Google. “All models are wrong, and increasingly you can succeed without them.” Ultimately, Anderson took Norvig’s ideas and went to town with them:

在这个世界上，海量数据和应用数学取代了所有其他可能发挥作用的工具。从语言学到社会学，所有关于人类行为的理论都被彻底颠覆了。忘记分类学、本体论和心理学吧。谁知道人们为什么这么做？关键在于他们做了什么，而我们能够以前所未有的精准度追踪和衡量它。有了足够的数据，数字就能说明一切。

This is a world where massive amounts of data and applied mathematics replace every other tool that might be brought to bear. Out with every theory of human behavior, from linguistics to sociology. Forget taxonomy, ontology, and psychology. Who knows why people do what they do? The point is they do it, and we can track and measure it with unprecedented fidelity. With enough data, the numbers speak for themselves.

这些公司信奉数据的目的论，认为数据越多，收益也就越大：为消费者带来更好的结果，更准确地理解消费者的需求和愿望，并为整个社会带来更好的结果。但数据越大真的就越好吗？

These companies have embraced a teleology of data, where more data will yield progressively more: better results for consumers, a more accurate understanding of consumers’ needs and wants, and better outcomes for society at large. But is bigger really better?

用数百万的样本量来理解世界，与其他类型的探究截然不同。大数据或许能告诉我们一些关于人的事情，但它对个人的了解却少之又少。例如，如果硅谷不承认人类行为总是嵌入在特定情境中，它又能告诉我们多少关于某种情况的真相呢？

Understanding the world with a sample size in the millions is a radical departure from other types of inquiry. Big data may tell us something about people, but it can tell us precious little about individual persons. How much truth about a situation can Silicon Valley tell us, for example, if it doesn’t acknowledge that human behavior is always embedded in a context?

19世纪实用主义者威廉·詹姆斯在回应同时代的还原论者时，批判了这种幼稚的数据处理方法。在他1890年出版的《心理学原理》一书中，詹姆斯写道：“没有人拥有过一种单独存在的简单感觉。意识……是由丰富的客体和关系构成的。” 白天鹅在红光下呈现红色；要理解天鹅的颜色，我们还必须了解光的属性。换句话说，事实总是存在于特定的语境中，将它们分解成离散的数据点会使它们变得毫无意义且不完整。

Nineteenth-century pragmatist William James critiqued this naïve approach to data when he responded to the reductionists of his era. In his 1890 book, The Principles of Psychology, James wrote: “No one ever had a simple sensation by itself. Consciousness… is of a teeming multiplicity of objects and relations.” A white swan seems red in a red light; to understand the color of swans, we also have to understand the properties of light. Facts, in other words, always live in a context, and hacking them into discrete data points renders them meaningless and incomplete.

无摩擦技术背后的假设

Assumptions behind Frictionless Technology

硅谷流行一个概念，那就是“无摩擦”技术。它是硅谷创新的标准。当技术运行流畅、直观，无需任何人类以思想或情感形式输入时，它就可以被视为无摩擦的。在这种情况下，技术成为现实生活的无缝组成部分。但这些技术究竟意味着什么？技术对人类的思想和努力意味着什么？我们是否应该将科技在生活中扮演的角色视为理所当然？或者，在某些时候和情况下，我们是否应该更深入地思考所使用的​​技术？随着硅谷对无摩擦技术的思考方式日益普及，它将塑造人们认为令人兴奋的创新类型，以及值得资助和研究的工作，从而缩小——而不是扩大——我们对可能性的感知。

One popular concept in Silicon Valley is “frictionless” technology. It’s the standard for innovation in the Valley. Technology can be deemed frictionless when it operates smoothly and intuitively, without requiring any human input in the form of thoughts or emotions. In these instances, technology becomes a seamless part of real life. But what do these sorts of technologies mean for human thought and effort? Should we all take for granted the role of technology in our lives, or are there times and situations where we want a more thoughtful engagement with the technology we use? As Silicon Valley’s way of thinking about frictionless technology grows popular, it will shape the kind of innovation that people think is exciting, and the work that merits funding and study, narrowing—rather than expanding—our sense of possibility.

2010年，谷歌时任首席执行官埃里克·施密特在接受《华尔街日报》采访时表示：“大多数人并不想让谷歌回答他们的问题……他们希望谷歌告诉他们下一步该做什么。” 这反映了互联网文化以及更广泛的西方文化和公共生活的微妙转变，应该引起警惕。当我们在谷歌上搜索或在Facebook上发帖时，这些平台不断变化的算法塑造着我们获取的关于朋友、关于世界动态、关于自身健康和福祉的信息。硅谷以人们容易忽视的方式塑造着我们获取的信息，所有这些都是为了更有效地满足我们的需求和偏好。

In a 2010 interview in the Wall Street Journal, Google’s then-CEO Eric Schmidt argued, “Most people don’t want Google to answer their questions… they want Google to tell them what they should be doing next.” This reflects a subtle shift in the culture of the Internet, and in Western culture and public life more broadly, that should raise red flags. When we search on Google or post on Facebook, the ever-changing algorithms that underpin these platforms shape the information we get about our friends, about what’s going on in the world, about our health and well-being. In ways that people overlook, Silicon Valley shapes the information we get access to, all in the name of tailoring it more effectively to our needs and preferences.

人们常说，这种个性化会导致两极分化。过滤机制会向人们提供反映其观点的内容，并屏蔽他们可能不认同的人，从而使公共领域变得越来越缺乏活力。互联网活动家伊莱·帕里瑟（Eli Pariser）将此称为“过滤泡沫”。

One oft-made point is that this personalization leads to polarization. By feeding people content that reflects their views and shielding them from people they may disagree with, filtering mechanisms make the public sphere less and less dynamic. Internet activist Eli Pariser dubbed this the “filter bubble.”

“无摩擦技术”的危险不在于它能为我们做什么或不能做什么，而在于它如何塑造我们的思维。当数据能够准确地反映既定事实时，我们又何必去寻找新的信息，学习不同的知识，突破辩论或既有观念的界限呢？观点和偏好？这就是记者、评论员和政治分析家所说的“后真相时代”。在硅谷的心态下，我们更在意的不是主动寻求真相，而是参与那些让我们感到肯定和认可的讨论和体验。

The dangers of “frictionless technology” lie not in what it can or cannot do for us, but in how it shapes our thinking. Why seek out new information, why learn something different, or push the boundaries of debate or previously accepted ideas, when data can serve up exactly what reflects already-established outlooks and preferences? This is what journalists, commentators, and political analysts have dubbed the “post-truth era.” In a Silicon Valley state of mind, we care less about actively seeking out the truth than we do about engaging in discourse and experiences that make us feel affirmed and acknowledged.

毋庸置疑，硅谷本身及其整体文化中发生的所有创新都带来了巨大的益处。没有人主张彻底废除所有尖端技术或创业精神，正是这些正是硅谷文化在全球经济中如此重要的组成部分。这里批判的是硅谷悄无声息地侵蚀着我们的知识生活。人文学科，或者说我们描述世界丰富现实（包括历史、政治、哲学和艺术）的传统，正被硅谷的各种假设所诋毁。

It goes without saying that there are tremendous benefits to all of the innovations happening in both the real Silicon Valley and in its culture at large. No one is arguing for completely doing away with all of the cutting-edge technology or the spirit of entrepreneurship that makes this culture such a prominent player in our global economy. The critique here is of Silicon Valley’s quiet, creeping costs on our intellectual life. The humanities, or our tradition of describing the rich reality of our world—its history, politics, philosophy, and art—are being denigrated by every assumption at play in Silicon Valley.

当我们相信科技能拯救我们，相信我们无法从过去吸取任何教训，相信数字本身就能说明一切时，我们就会陷入危险的诱惑之中。我们只会寻求灵丹妙药般的答案，而不是投入艰苦的努力去拼凑真相。

When we believe that technology will save us, that we have nothing to learn from the past or that numbers can speak for themselves, we are falling prey to dangerous siren songs. We are seeking out silver bullet answers instead of engaging in the hard work of piecing together the truth.

意义建构是对硅谷所有这些误导性假设的纠正。即使我们如今拥有强大的计算能力，我们也别无选择，只能静下心来，深入思考问题，并在人类细致耐心的观察下努力解决它们。在接下来的章节中，我将揭示如何做到这一点的路线图。

Sensemaking is a corrective to all of these misguided assumptions of Silicon Valley. Even with the magnificent computational power now at our disposal, there is no alternative to sitting with problems, stewing in them, and struggling through them with the help of careful, patient human observation. In the chapters to follow, I will reveal the road map for how to do just that.

第三章

Chapter Three

文化——而非个人

Culture—Not Individuals

社会先于个人而存在。任何无法过共同生活，或自给自足到不需要共同生活，从而不参与社会的人，要么是野兽，要么是神。

Society is something that precedes the individual. Anyone who either cannot lead the common life or is so self-sufficient as not to need to, and therefore does not partake of society, is either a beast or a god.

——亚里士多德，《政治学》

—Aristotle, Politics

在审视硅谷盛行的意识形态假设之后，人们会认为，当今世界的公司和组织应该对在人类行为上押下重注抱有相对的信心。如今，通过机器学习可以获得海量数据集，并且一个涵盖“世界上所有知识”的潜在模型正在构建中，还有什么需要思考的呢？人类行为：已成定局。

After examining the assumptions of the ideology so prevalent in Silicon Valley, one would think that companies and organizations in today’s world would feel a relative sense of confidence about making big bets on human behavior. With massive data sets now available through machine learning and a potential model of “everything there is to know in the world” in the making, what more is there left to ponder? Human behavior: it’s in the bag.

当然，现实情况是，企业和组织常常对如何在重大变革的时刻继续前进感到茫然。领导层已经失去了想象和直觉的能力，无法预知世界——以及他们自己的企业或机构——未来将如何发展。

The reality, of course, is that businesses and organizations are often in a fog about how to move forward through moments of great change. Leadership has lost the ability to imagine and intuit how the world—and their own business or institution—might be evolving.

通过我为我的公司 ReD Associates 提供咨询服务，我花了很多时间在这些类型的人身上的组织——其中一些是地球上最陷入困境的公司。当我说“陷入困境”时，我并不是指这些公司必然在丢失市场份额，也不是指它们在内部权力动态中苦苦挣扎——尽管这两种情况通常都是事实。我所说的“陷入困境”是指组织内部的整个文化都被一种毫无方向的恐慌情绪所笼罩。德语中有一个词可以完美地描述这种情绪：Scheue 。它指的是马被黄蜂蜇伤的那一刻。Scheue简洁地捕捉到了在难以理解的大量数据点中挣扎着采取行动的氛围。

Through my consulting work with my company, ReD Associates, I spend much of my time in the belly of these types of organizations—some of the most troubled companies on the planet. When I say “troubled,” I don’t mean that these companies are necessarily losing market share or that they are struggling in the midst of internal power dynamics—although both of these things are often true. What I mean by “troubled” is that the entire culture inside the organization is seized by a mood of directionless panic. The Germans have a word that perfectly describes this mood: Scheue. It refers to the moment a horse is stung by a wasp. Scheue succinctly captures the atmosphere of flailing attempts at action amid an indecipherable deluge of data points.

当然，大型企业并非唯一经历“Scheue”的文化。想想我们个人如何应对气候变化这样的危机。我们对此充满焦虑，却常常不知如何以任何有意义的战略性方式向前迈进。有些人在科学研究上摸索，试图拼凑出一个有效的行动方案，而大多数人只是瘫痪地四处走动，深夜里被日益增长的恐惧和不安所折磨。

Of course, major corporations are not the only cultures that experience Scheue. Think about our own responses as individuals to a crisis like climate change. We are filled with anxiety about it, but we often have no idea how to move forward in any meaningful, strategic way. Some of us muck about in the science, trying to piece together a plan of effective action, while most of us simply walk around paralyzed, stricken late at night with a growing sense of fear and dread.

意义建构为我们提供了一条突破这种恐惧和担忧的道路。我提供的分析工具源自我对哲学、人类学、文学、历史和艺术等学科的深入研究。当我接手一位新的企业客户时，我首先着手的始终是对世界的理解。

Sensemaking offers us a path forward through this type of fear and dread. The analytical tools I bring to the table are culled from an engagement with disciplines like philosophy, anthropology, literature, history, and the arts. And the very first place I start when I take on a new corporate client is always with an understanding of the world.

我所说的“世界”，当然是指客户和竞争对手的世界。但首先，也是更为根本的，我指的是对公司本身世界的理解。任何一家公司内部的现实是如何构建的还是其他？哪些假设被广泛接受？人们为什么做事？世界会奖励那些挑战正统观念的人吗？这个世界里的人是否对自己销售的产品充满好奇？他们的工作流程是如何从一个部门流向另一个部门的？所有这些问题——以及更多其他问题——构成了公司的世界。

When I say “the world,” I mean the world of the customers and the competitors, of course. But first, and much more fundamentally, I mean an understanding of the world of the company itself. How is reality constructed inside any one company or another? What assumptions are widely held? Why do people do things? Does the world reward those who challenge orthodoxy? Is it a world where people are curious about the products they sell? How do their work streams flow from one department to another? All of these questions—and so many more—make up the world of the company.

如果你是一名会计师、品牌经理或公司律师，当你走进公司总部的大门时，你很可能会发现一切都井然有序，似乎合情合理。但如果你对世界感兴趣——从人文学科的角度进行分析——你会发现，在这样的文化中，发生的事情往往显得荒谬。我经常看到一些公司在某些方面投入资金，仅仅是因为他们一直以来都在这些方面投入资金；他们也经常削减那些对整个公司的核心和灵魂至关重要的开支。做出这类决定是因为数字加起来合理——精简是必要的，或者他们正在与竞争对手对标目标——但对于任何观察公司现实情况的人来说，这些决定都毫无意义。事实上，在高度不确定的环境下，这样的决定可能非常有害，足以彻底摧毁一家公司的未来。

If you are an accountant, or a brand manager, or a corporate lawyer, chances are you walk through the doors of your company’s headquarters and things appear relatively orderly. They seem to make sense. But if you are interested in worlds—an analysis culled from the humanities—it is often absurd what is happening in the middle of such cultures. I routinely see companies investing money in things for no other reason than that they have always invested money in such things; they also routinely cut things that are vital to the heart and the soul of the entire company. These types of decisions are made because the numbers add up—streamlining is deemed necessary or they are benchmarking their goals against competitors—but the decisions make no sense to anyone observing the reality of the company’s world. In fact, such decisions—in the midst of a highly uncertain climate—can be detrimental enough to completely undermine a company’s future.

这是一个重要的区别：对世界的整体理解与对电子表格中一排排数字的更碎片化的理解之间的区别。人文学科让我们接触到这种更全面的视角。在这家公司工作是什么感觉？或者使用它的产品是什么感觉？哲学再次引导我们理解这些不同的现实是如何构建的。正如我们之前在第一章中，这种区分指向了一场持续了两千年的哲学争论。身为人意味着什么：身为我们又意味着什么？例如，如果你是一位追随笛卡尔“我思故我在”传统的哲学家，你就会假设现实是通过理性和分析性的思维过程构建的。我们之所以为人，是因为我们思考。换句话说，当人类从抽象和理论的视角看待世界时，其自身处于最佳状态。

This is an important distinction: the difference between a holistic understanding of a world versus a more atomized understanding of rows of numbers in a spreadsheet. The humanities put us in touch with this more holistic perspective. What is it like to work in this company? Or to use its products? Philosophy, again, can guide us in our understanding of how these different realities are constructed. As we discussed earlier in Chapter One, this distinction points to a philosophical debate that has been going on for two thousand years. What does it mean to be human: what does it mean to be us? If, for example, you are a philosopher following in the tradition of Descartes—“I think, therefore I am”—you assume that reality is constructed through a rational and analytical thought process. We are human because we think. In other words, humanity is at its best when it is approaching the world from an abstract and theoretical perspective.

但近百年来，欧洲大陆的哲学家们已经摆脱了这种对现实的分析性理解。构成现象学传统的不同思想家更感兴趣的是对人性的语境理解。我们之所以为人，是因为我们存在于不同的社会语境中。这种哲学认为，真正使我们成为人的，是我们理解和关心共同世界的能力，而不是像笛卡尔那样坐着，透过窗户“思考”生活的能力。

But more recently, over the last century, philosophers in continental Europe have broken away from this analytical understanding of our realities. The different thinkers who make up the phenomenological tradition were more interested in a contextual understanding of humanity. We are human because of the way we exist within different social contexts. This philosophy argued that it was our ability to understand and care about our shared worlds that actually makes us human, rather than the ability to sit, like Descartes, and “think about” life as though seeing it through a window.

在意义建构的过程中，我们并非试图探究人们对事物的“思考”。观点和感知在很大程度上无关紧要。相反，我们扎根于人文学科，这使我们能够更深入地探究。我们感兴趣的是揭示支配不同现实的结构。作为这一现象学传统的先驱，海德格尔主张将经验——更不用说人——视为不可分割的世界，在其中我们无法将心灵与身体、人与环境分离。现象学家并非旨在瓦解科学方法作为理解物理学的工具。或科学——相反，他们声称这些方法根本不足以理解人们。

In a sensemaking process, we are not trying to find out what people “think” about things. Opinions and perceptions are largely irrelevant. Instead, our grounding in the humanities allows us to go deeper. We are interested in uncovering the structures that govern different realities. Heidegger, at the forefront of this phenomenological tradition, argued for a view of experience—not to mention people—as inextricable worlds, in which we cannot separate mind from body, person from environment. The phenomenologists did not aim to dismantle the scientific method as a tool for understanding physics or science—rather, they claimed that these methods simply weren’t sufficient for making sense of people.

海德格尔认为，我们所有人都应该研究的主要课题是“存在被理解的基础”。是什么将世界维系在一起？人们行为背后的假设是什么？

Heidegger argued that the main topic we should all study is “that on the basis of which beings are understood.” What is holding the world together? What are the assumptions underlying what people are doing?

为什么笛卡尔哲学和现象学哲学之间的区别如此重要？毕竟，我们不是哲学系的学者。这对我们日常生活有什么影响？你们中的许多人可能已经同意——是的，我们存在于社会背景中；那又如何？我在这里要告诉你们，这种区别——我们对人性的错误理解——对我们生活的方方面面都有着广泛的影响。当我们对人性的理解错误时，我们就会把一切都搞错。当我走进一家正处于危机中的公司时，各种各样的人会告诉我他们各种不同的想法。然后，他们会递给我备忘录和其他文件，其中包含更多他们的想法。紧接着，他们还会收到大量关于客户和竞争对手想法的定量数据——通常以千兆字节为单位。这些关于“思考”的数据量非常庞大——这些分析是从笛卡尔对人性的理解中提炼出来的——但如果不研究世界，这些数据就毫无意义。一切的根源是什么？是什么将它们维系在一起？这些人究竟基于什么在做这些事、说这些话？只有深入探究这些问题，我们才能找到一条有意义的前进之路。

Why does this distinction between Cartesian and phenomenological philosophy matter? After all, we are not academics in a philosophy department. What difference does it make to all of us in our daily lives? Many of you probably already agree—yes, we exist within a social context; so what? I am here to tell you that this distinction—our erroneous understanding of humanity—has wide-ranging implications for all aspects of our lives. When we get our understanding of humanity wrong, we get everything wrong. When I walk into a corporation in the midst of a crisis, all sorts of different people will tell me all sorts of different things about what they think. Then they hand me memos and other paper containing even more of their thinking. And then these are followed by reams of quantitative data about what their customers and their competitors think—often arriving in gigabytes. This is a vast quantity of data on “thinking”—analysis culled from a Cartesian understanding of humanity—but it is essentially meaningless without studying the world. What underlies everything? What holds it all together? Based on what are these people doing and saying these things? Only when we engage in an investigation of these questions can we find a way forward that makes sense.

这正是福特汽车公司在深入了解驾驶员世界时发现的。

This is precisely what the Ford Motor Company discovered when they took an immersive dive into the world of their drivers.

林肯的气味

The Smell of Lincoln

在福特公司园区内数十栋建筑中的一栋里，有一条看似不起眼的走廊，尽头是一段通往地下室的楼梯。然而，一旦走下楼，映入眼帘的却是一片名副其实的汽车坟场。这个如同锅炉房般宽敞的空间，是福特工程师们拆解竞争对手汽车的地方。旧车的外壳一字排开，拆下来的零部件则堆放在附近。经过碰撞测试并烧毁的轮胎和合金轮毂散落在地板上，墙上摆放着一些桶，上面贴着“油布”和“二手汽车零件”等标签。

In one of Ford’s many dozen buildings on their corporate campus, there is an innocuous corridor ending in a flight of stairs down to the basement level. Once downstairs, however, a veritable car graveyard is revealed. This cavernous space—resembling a boiler room—is where the Ford engineers dismantle their competitors’ cars. Shells of former cars are lined up while their ripped-out components sit in piles nearby. Tires and alloy wheels that have been crash-tested and burnt up are strewn across the floor, and barrels with labels like “oily rags” and “used auto parts” line the walls.

在尘土飞扬的地板、霓虹灯和轰鸣声中，有一扇笨重的钢门。门后，一束美丽温暖的白光倾泻而下，洒满这片汽车坟场。在这间位于地下室的洁白房间里，福特精心设计了一个故事板体验，探索其豪华汽车品牌林肯在2030年的未来。林肯的标志性气息——所有林肯经销店里弥漫的柑橘香味——从门后飘散到整个公司的工程部门。这是奢华的气息，福特想要更多。

Amid the dusty floors, neon lights, and growling noises, there is a hulking steel door. And from behind that door, a beautiful, warm white light floods out into the car graveyard. In this pristine white room tucked into the basement, Ford has created a choreographed storyboarding experience that explores the “Future of Lincoln,” their luxury car brand, in the year 2030. The signature smell of Lincoln—the citrusy scent in all Lincoln dealerships—wafts out from behind the doors into the engineering bowels of the entire company. This is the smell of luxury, and Ford wants more of it.

如果你不是住在底特律，你可能会觉得林肯这个豪华品牌几年前就消失了，这完全可以理解。如今，林肯这个名字在汽车话题中并不常见。2015年，林肯的销量实际上是六年来最高的——报告称售出了10.1万辆——但林肯仍然远远落后于它在底特律的劲敌凯迪拉克。宝马、奔驰和奥迪等德国竞争对手遥遥领先。在销售方面，他们甚至懒得在竞争市场分析中提及林肯。

Unless you live in Detroit, you could be forgiven for assuming the Lincoln luxury brand disappeared years ago. It’s not a name that comes up often in car talk these days. In 2015, Lincoln actually had its strongest sales earnings in more than six years—they reported 101,000 vehicles sold—but Lincoln is still trailing far behind Cadillac, its arch nemesis in Detroit. German rivals like BMW, Mercedes, and Audi are so far ahead in sales, they barely even bother to bring up Lincoln in their competitive market analysis.

与二十世纪中叶的早期相比，这个品牌已经衰落到了何种程度。一切始于 1938 年福特汽车公司总裁埃德塞尔·福特 (Edsel Ford) 在欧洲巡演时。他带着“纯正欧陆式”汽车的愿景回到底特律。著名汽车设计师 ET“鲍勃”格雷戈里 (Et Bob Gregorie) 胜任了这项任务，到了二十世纪四十年代，新款 Continental 驶下装配线，进入美国最著名的环球旅行者的车道。在接下来的二十年里，从猫王埃尔维斯·普雷斯利 (Elizabeth Taylor) 到弗兰克·辛纳屈 (Frank Sinatra)，每个人都拥有一辆林肯。但直到 1961 年，林肯 Continental 才真正崭露头角。这款新车型是设计师埃尔伍德·恩格尔 (Elwood Engel) 传奇职业生涯的巅峰之作，当肯尼迪在达拉斯巡演期间在他的黑色林肯车里遇刺时，它在美国人的心灵上留下了不可磨灭的印记。

How far the brand has fallen from its early days in the middle of the twentieth century. It all started when Edsel Ford, the chief of the Ford Motor Company, toured Europe in 1938. He returned to Detroit with a vision for a car that was “strictly continental.” Famed car designer E. T. “Bob” Gregorie was up to the task, and by the 1940s the new Continentals were rolling off the assembly lines and into the driveways of America’s most famous jet-setters. For the next two decades, everyone from Elvis Presley to Elizabeth Taylor to Frank Sinatra owned a Lincoln. But it was 1961 when the Lincoln Continental came into its own. The new model was the culmination of designer Elwood Engel’s legendary career, leaving an indelible mark on the American psyche when JFK was shot in his black Lincoln on a tour through Dallas.

然而，到了20世纪70年代和80年代，福特对豪华车市场失去了兴趣。他们流畅的设计沦为庸俗之作，其核心往往是标准的福特工程技术，而非豪华。林肯在美国市场上的市场份额持续下滑，不仅输给了梅赛德斯和宝马等新晋品牌，也输给了其本土竞争对手凯迪拉克。到了90年代，林肯的客户甚至转向了其他福特产品。福特Fusion和重新设计的金牛座——如今配备了丰富的豪华配置——都开始蚕食林肯大幅缩水的豪华车市场份额。

By the 1970s and ’80s, however, Ford lost its feel for the luxury car market. Their sleek designs gave way to kitsch, often with standard Ford engineering—not luxury—underneath. Lincoln continued to lose ground to the U.S. market newcomers like Mercedes and BMW, as well as to their original hometown rival Cadillac. By the ’90s, they were even losing customers to other Ford products. The Ford Fusion and a reimagined Taurus—now offering a wide variety of luxury features—both started to encroach on Lincoln’s vastly diminished share of the luxury market.

如今，这个曾经辉煌的品牌仅占据豪华车市场的5.5%，其客户群的平均年龄为65岁。林肯已成为一种负担；公司高管甚至考虑彻底关闭它。他们该如何让这个品牌重获新生呢？

Today, the once-storied brand holds just 5.5 percent of the luxury car market, and the average age of its customer base is 65. Lincoln has become a liability; executives within in the company even considered killing it off entirely. How could they begin to make the brand relevant again?

要完全回答这个问题，我们必须首先回归意义建构的最根本原则：对世界的理解。借鉴海德格尔的思想，我们首先要探索“存在被理解的基础”。这不仅考察豪华汽车及其驾驶者的世界，也考察福特本身的文化。福特文化如何构想驾驶体验？这与客户世界的现实又有何不同？

To fully answer that question, we must first go back to the most fundamental principle of sensemaking: an understanding of worlds. Taking our cue from Heidegger, we start by exploring “that on the basis of which beings are understood.” This is an examination of the world of luxury cars and their drivers, but also of the culture of Ford itself. How does the Ford culture conceive of the driving experience? And how is that different from the reality of the world of its customers?

首先，福特是一家拥有悠久卓越工程历史的公司。他们始终以打造卓越汽车和超越驾驶者期望为荣。他们希望人们喜爱他们的汽车，并努力兑现对客户的承诺。但他们的工作方式——也是其赖以生存的基础——是由工程和技术创新驱动的。这与汽车工程师的世界息息相关，而与驾驶者的世界则关系不大。亨利·福特曾有一句名言：“如果我问人们想要什么，他们会说更快的马。” 这句话表达了福特文化的核心假设：科技功能和选配让驾驶变得有意义。这一假设的结果——“基础”——意味着福特内部的不同工程师会根据他们自己作为密歇根州白人男性中产阶级对驾驶者导航系统需求的看法，改进他们各自的特定部件——比如导航系统。在整个过程中，所有这些独立的汽车工程部件最终组合成整辆车。与此同时，福特工程师们会努力使这一切看起来协调一致、引人入胜。

To begin with, Ford is a company with a long history of engineering excellence. They have always taken tremendous pride in making great cars and exceeding drivers’ expectations. They want people to love their cars and they work hard to deliver on that promise to their customers. But the way they work—that on the basis of which—is driven by engineering and technological innovations. It has everything to do with the world of car engineers and not much to do with the world of their drivers. Henry Ford famously said, “If I had asked people what they wanted, they would have said faster horses.” This statement articulates the assumption at the heart of the Ford culture: technological features and options make driving meaningful. The result of this assumption—the “basis on which”—meant that different engineers working within Ford would improve upon their specific component—the navigation system, say—based largely on their own white, male, middle-class Michigan view of what drivers want from a navigation system. Throughout the process, all of these individual car engineering components would come together into the vehicle. Meanwhile, the Ford engineers would work to make it all seem cohesive and appealing.

当然，和任何其他大型跨国公司一样，福特对林肯的市场份额以及现有和目标消费群进行了大量的研究。如果他们希望重振林肯并使其成为一个相关的豪华品牌，他们就需要接触一个特定的消费者群体：比现有的林肯消费者群体更年轻、受教育程度更高、更具全球意识和创造力。与二三十年前中国和印度等地新兴的中产阶级不同，这些年轻消费者已稳居中上阶层。他们在物质舒适的环境中长大，因此对浮夸的炫耀性消费十分谨慎。对他们来说，“豪华”一词意味着完全不同的东西。福特对三十年后大多数豪华车购买者将会走向何方的理解，依赖于他们对“不同的东西”的战略把握。

Of course, like any other major global corporation, Ford had a surfeit of research on Lincoln’s market share and its current and intended consumer base. If they had any hope of reviving Lincoln and making it a relevant luxury brand, they needed to reach a particular class of consumers: younger, better educated, more globally minded and creative than the existing consumer group of Lincoln drivers. Unlike the emerging middle-class drivers of twenty or thirty years ago in places like China and India, these young drivers are securely in the upper middle class. They were raised in material comfort, so they are circumspect about flashy conspicuous consumption. For them, the word luxury means something completely different. Ford’s understanding of where the majority of luxury car buyers will be in thirty years relies on their strategic grasp of what that “something different” amounts to.

该公司的研究精准地捕捉到了这部分人群的薄弱数据——他们“思考”的内容——以及许多关于他们驾驶体验的有用统计数据，例如体重和人体工程学。但福特对这些消费者的世界——他们构建现实的方式——的理解有限。意义建构提供了缺失的连接点。

The company’s research accurately captured the thin data of this demographic—what they “thought” about—as well as many useful statistics about their bodies behind the wheel, such as their weight and ergonomics. But Ford had limited understanding of the world of these consumers: the way they constructed their reality. Sensemaking provided the missing connective tissue.

我们与福特合作开展了一项大规模的民族志研究项目，旨在探索这一特定群体的驾驶体验。研究首先在美国和中国的城市开展，研究了该群体。尽管研究清楚地表明，豪华车市场的未来也将转向印度和俄罗斯，但福特的领导层最初却拒绝了在这两个国家开展研究的想法。这体现了每个大公司内部都存在着相互冲突的优先事项。包括这些新兴市场对于长期战略目标来说很有意义——三十年后，每家豪华汽车制造商都希望在印度站稳脚跟——但短期内的时间和资源压力仍然使其成为一项具有挑战性的提议。

We partnered with Ford to conduct a large-scale ethnographic research project to explore the driving experience for this particular group. This started by studying the group in cities in the United States and China. Though the research was clear that the future of the luxury car market was also moving to India and Russia, leadership at Ford initially resisted the idea of conducting research there. This is a testament to the conflicting priorities that exist inside every large corporation. Including these emerging markets made sense for the long-term strategic goals—in thirty years, every luxury carmaker will want a stronghold in India—but the short-term pressures of time and resources still made it a challenging proposition.

当所有研究要素准备就绪后，我们的研究人员开始在美国、中国、印度和俄罗斯的城市对60名受试者进行研究。到达目的地后，他们创建了“车辆生态学”，以描述每位驾驶员周围复杂的社会结构网络。他们与受试者的妻子、丈夫、姐妹、兄弟、邻居和朋友共度时光。在半年的时间里，他们对这60名受试者中的每一个人都构建了丰富的理解网络。研究人员追踪并编码了实地笔记、照片、访谈、日记以及其他形式的定性数据收集中包含的所有信息后，一个模式变得异常清晰：汽车的未来与实际驾驶体验几乎没有关系。研究人员注意到，95%的时间里，汽车都没有被使用——要么停在车库里，要么停在街上。而剩余5%的实际驾驶时间，大部分都花在了乏味的交通拥堵上。讽刺的是，福特工程设计对驾驶的关注却让很多消费者感到不满，因为驾驶体验在他们的用车体验中只占了很小一部分。福特想要吸引的那些司机基本上都陷入了永久的交通堵塞。

When all of the pieces of the study were in place, our researchers set out to study sixty subjects in cities in the United States, China, India, and Russia. Once there, they created “vehicle ecologies” to describe the complex network of social structures that existed around each and every driver. They spent time with wives, husbands, sisters, brothers, neighbors, and friends. Over the course of half a year, they created a rich web of understanding around each one of the sixty subjects. After researchers had tracked and coded all of the information contained in their field notes, photographs, interviews, journal entries, and other forms of qualitative data gathering, one pattern became strikingly clear: the future of the car had very little to do with the actual experience of driving. The researchers noted that 95 percent of the time, cars were not being used—either sitting in the garage or on the street. And most of the remaining 5 percent of actual driving time was spent in the tedium of traffic. Ironically, Ford’s engineering focus on driving left a lot of consumers dissatisfied because driving was such a small part of their car experience. The drivers Ford intends to woo are basically in permanent gridlock.

如果他们与汽车的关系不再仅仅关乎驾驶，豪华也不再仅仅关乎品牌或保险杠上耀眼的金牌，那么是什么赋予了车内的意义？他们从车内——以及车外——的体验中寻求什么？意义建构能够揭示他们世界的结构。提供了对这种新型“汽车体验”的基本理解。

If their relationship to the car is no longer just about the driving and luxury is not a brand or flashy gold plates on a bumper, what creates meaning inside the vehicle? What do they seek out from their experience inside—as well as outside—the car? Sensemaking’s ability to reveal the structure of their worlds provided the essential understanding into what this new kind of “car experience” might look like.

一位来自莫斯科的 37 岁参与者描述了他独自驾车出行时无忧无虑的自由感觉。他养成了大声播放俄罗斯嘻哈音乐并将双手放在仪表盘上进行即兴演奏的习惯——这些事情他做梦也不会想到会在车里做。他的故事——以及其他类似的故事——表明，奢华是一种在完全私密空间中表达自我的体验。一位来自孟买的 38 岁女子告诉研究人员，她非常珍惜与最亲密的朋友和家人在车里度过的时光。“我们去果阿的时候，”她说，“我们真的很喜欢在天黑时开车。仅仅是一起坐在灯光下就感觉很棒。这是一种享受。”她的观察和经历与研究中的其他人相似。她的观点阐明了在设计精美的空间中体验亲密联系、热情好客和有意义的联系的奢华。对于该群体的其他成员，比如一位来自孟买的31岁钻石珠宝商来说，奢华就像一套移动办公套件，让雄心勃勃的企业主能够更好地服务外地客户。“提供无缝衔接的客户体验有助于我的业务蓬勃发展，”他告诉研究人员。

One 37-year-old participant from Moscow described the freedom of feeling carefree on his solo car trips. He created a ritual of blasting Russian hip-hop and jamming with his hands on the dashboard—things he wouldn’t dream of doing anywhere else but in the context of the car. His story—and others like it—revealed that luxury is an experience of self-expression in a completely private space. A 38-year-old woman in Bombay told researchers how much she cherished time in the car with her closest friends and family. “When we go to Goa,” she said, “we really enjoy driving when it is dark. Just sitting in the glowing light together is so nice. It is a pleasure.” Her observations and experiences paralleled others in the study. Her vision articulated the luxury of experiencing bonding, hospitality, and meaningful connections in a beautifully designed space. For other members of the group, such as a 31-year-old diamond jeweler from Mumbai, luxury is a mobile office suite that allows ambitious business owners to dote on clients coming in from out of town. “Making the client experience seamless helps my business to flourish,” he told the researchers.

总而言之，意义建构揭示了这些消费者所追求的一系列具体体验：从更时尚的社交场所，到私密的表达空间，再到更专注、更高效的环境。对不同世界的细致理解赋予了林肯一套全新的高层次目标，为驾驶者提供与皮革纹理或前大灯光学元件无关的整体体验。福特意识到推动设计和工程过程所需的奢华体验：福特等公司对汽车的构想的彻底转变。

All total, sensemaking revealed a handful of specific experiences that these consumers are seeking out: everything from more stylish opportunities for bonding to spaces for private expression to contexts for a more intense focus and productivity. This detailed understanding of different worlds gave Lincoln a new set of high-level objectives, delivering something holistic to the driver that had nothing to do with the grain of the leather or the optics on the headlights. Ford realized that luxury experiences needed to drive the design and engineering process: a total transformation in how a company like Ford conceives of the car.

一旦福特开始关注这些体验，就再也无法孤立地看待汽车中的任何设备了。物体——无论是车窗按钮、方向盘还是防抱死制动系统——都在关系世界中运作，我们或许可以称之为“意义链”。我们甚至可以进一步扩展这个想法，说所有的工具、所有的设备——我们周围的一切——都是一个系统，承载着我们“为了……而做”的事情。一把锤子只有在用来盖房子、搭建庇护所、拥有一个家、获得安全感时，才是一把锤子。我喝可乐是为了保持清醒、为了高效工作、为了成功、为了养家糊口。

Once Ford started to focus on these experiences, there was no way to consider any of the devices in the car in isolation. Objects—be they a window button, a steering wheel, or an antilock braking system—function within relational worlds, what we might call “chains of meaning.” We can even extend this idea further by saying that all tools, all pieces of equipment—the stuff that surrounds us—are a system for our “in order to’s.” A hammer is only a hammer when it is used in order to a build a house in order to create a shelter in order to have a home in order to feel secure. I drink Coke in order to stay awake in order to be productive in order to be successful in order to provide for my loved ones.

以一位参与研究的中国男士为例：他家有一台意式浓缩咖啡机。这在意大利或美国并不稀奇，但在拥有悠久而丰富的茶文化的中国，喝咖啡的人并不多见。这个家庭会去苏门答腊等地探险，寻找稀有的咖啡豆，并带回家与人分享。这种探索是他们共处时光的组织原则。在“意义链”中，他们寻找稀有的咖啡豆，是为了感受自己思想开放、充满好奇，是为了感受自己最好的一面，是为了感受到充满活力。

Consider an example from a Chinese man who participated in the study: his family had an espresso-style coffee machine. That would not be remarkable in Italy or in the United States, but in China, with such a long and rich tea culture, coffee drinkers are less common. This family would go on adventures to places like Sumatra to seek out rare coffee beans and bring them home to share. This type of quest was the organizing principle for their time together. In “chains of meaning,” they sought out rare coffee beans in order to feel like open-minded and curious people in order to feel like the best versions of themselves in order to feel fully alive.

为了真正理解福特对豪华车设计流程的彻底重塑，有必要了解一下其他豪华车目前对驾驶者的承诺。在梅赛德斯以奥迪为例，其整体设计语言——肌肉感十足的后尾箱，宛如一只即将扑向猎物的猛猫，以及醒目的前仪表盘——都讲述了一个充满肾上腺素的故事：驾驶者如同喷气式飞机驾驶员般飞驰而过。这体现了豪华车市场的普遍理念：驾驶者追求速度和刺激。

To truly understand Ford’s radical reimagining of the luxury car design process, it is helpful to examine what other luxury vehicles are currently promising their drivers. In a Mercedes or Audi, for example, the entire design language of the car—the muscular rear hips that resemble a cat about to pounce and the prominent front dashboard—tell an adrenaline-infused story of a driver zooming forward like a jet pilot. These are the general assumptions of the luxury car market: drivers want speed and thrill.

和福特一样，这些汽车制造商也在努力将公路上的幻想变成未来无人驾驶汽车的现实。福特大多数竞争对手的回应是描绘一种车内生产力的景象。如果豪华车主实际上不在开车，那他们一定是在工作。这些豪华车的效果图上，通常显示三四个人坐在可旋转的白色汽车座椅上，周围环绕着通用的按钮和屏幕——“社交媒体”和“蓝牙”等标签醒目地显示着。这种“工作”景象听起来很滑稽，正是因为它太过普通，缺乏语境。他们试图将其他世界（例如办公室世界）的领域全部移植到汽车上。

Like Ford, these carmakers are also struggling to translate the fantasy of the open road into the reality of a future with a driverless car. The response from most of Ford’s competitors is to offer up a vision of productivity inside the car. If luxury car owners are not actually driving, then they must be working. The renderings of these luxury vehicles often show three or four people sitting in swiveling white car seats with generic buttons and screens surrounding them—labels like “social media” and “Bluetooth” are prominently displayed. This vision of “work” feels comical precisely because it is so generic and devoid of context. They are attempting to transplant domains wholesale from other worlds—taking the world of the office, for example—and plop them into the car.

在沃尔沃的汽车中，无人驾驶技术的前景更加模糊。他们的效果图总是显示人们直视仪表盘。他们不再需要开车，但沃尔沃对于这种自由可能带来什么却缺乏令人信服的愿景。他们的典型乘客似乎正处于生存危机之中，对车内新自由的憧憬感到麻木。

In Volvo’s cars, the promise of driverless technology is even more vague. Their renderings always show people staring straight ahead at the dashboard. They no longer need to drive, but Volvo has no compelling vision for what that freedom might offer. Their prototypical passengers seem to be in the midst of an existential crisis, paralyzed by the prospect of their new freedom in the car.

而其他豪华汽车品牌则在外观上讲述一种激进的体验——以每小时 150 英里的速度在高速公路上飞驰，拼命地试图控制动力超强的汽车——福特对车内“工作”有着抽象的理解，但更注重对真实用户以及他们乘坐和使用车辆的体验的理解。创新和工程设计由此而来。

Whereas other luxury car brands were telling the story of an aggressive experience on the exterior—racing down the freeway at 150 miles per hour desperately trying to control an overpowered vehicle—with an abstract conceit about “work” on the inside, Ford is prioritizing an understanding of real people and their experiences of being in and using a vehicle. From there, innovation and engineering follow.

当然，谈论这种意义建构时，不可能不承认领导力在重大战略转变中的作用。意义建构表明，如果福特想要重塑林肯，就需要彻底重组整个公司架构。这意味着要改变这家规模如同小国般庞大、拥有数千名员工、深植于美国文化超过一个世纪的悠久历史的公司的发展方向。这样的时刻需要充满灵感和勇气的领导力，而马克·菲尔兹正是胜任这项任务的。在林肯发展历程中，菲尔兹已在探索如何以最佳方式带领福特迈向无人驾驶汽车的未来。他能够感觉到，以功能为中心的现有产业架构已不再适用。让技术和工程引领创新，整个公司正在逐渐脱离其实际消费者。

Of course, it is impossible to speak about this kind of sensemaking without also acknowledging the role of leadership in major strategy shifts. Sensemaking revealed that if Ford wanted to revamp Lincoln, they needed to completely reorganize their entire corporate structure. This would mean rerouting the path of a company that is the size of a small country, an organization with thousands of employees and a rich history embedded in American culture for more than a century. Such a moment calls for inspired and courageous leadership, and Mark Fields was up to the task. In the midst of the Lincoln story, Fields was already exploring how best to bring Ford into a future of driverless cars. He could sense that the existing industrial structure focused around features was no longer relevant. By letting technology and engineering lead the innovation, the entire company was becoming out of touch with its actual consumers.

与福特其他战略转型同步进行，菲尔兹运用这些意义建构洞见，推动了整个公司岗位和流程的重组。员工不再认为自己“从事技术工作”，而是专注于“技术如何服务于人们及其体验”。美国消费者——以及底特律的文化——已不再是唯一的视角。菲尔兹正在运用从各种研究中提炼出的意义建构洞见，将整个公司的视角全球化，摒弃“客户”和“用户”等抽象单位，转而围绕经销商、驾驶员和乘客展开对话。

In tandem with other strategic shifts occurring in Ford, Fields used the sensemaking insights to drive the reorganization of jobs and processes across the entire company. Employees no longer think of themselves as “working on technology.” Instead, their work is focused on “how technology serves people and their experiences.” And the American consumer—along with the culture of Detroit—has ceased to be the sole perspective. Fields is using sensemaking insights culled from a variety of studies to globalize the outlook of the entire company, doing away with abstract units like “customers” and “users” and shifting into conversations around dealers, drivers, and passengers.

未来几年，菲尔兹将围绕一个战略目标：福特汽车公司将完全围绕真实用户及其世界的体验进行创新。因此，“汽车”——曾经是公司存在的理由——正在成为众多关系世界中的一件物品。福特正在从一家汽车制造商转型为一家融合技术和交通服务的混合型公司。马克·菲尔兹将掌舵，在公司从底特律驶向这个美丽新世界的征程中，保持公司的凝聚力。

In the coming years, Fields is rallying around one strategic goal: The Ford Motor Company will innovate entirely around the experiences of actual people and their worlds. As a result of this, “the car”—once the company’s raison d’être—is becoming just one object in entire series of relational worlds. Ford is shifting from being an automaker into a hybrid technology and transportation services company. And Mark Fields is at the helm to keep the company cohesive while they navigate away from Detroit into this brave new world.

无论我们怎么想，我们并非个体；我们所说的话往往对我们的实际行为影响甚微。我们每个人都身处特定的情境之中。如果我们要理解人类行为，就必须理解情境，这是一个关于整体与原子化的争论。汽车只是一个物体；除非我们能够理解将驾驶员与社会世界连接起来的意义链，否则我们无法解读任何关于驾驶员的信息。

Despite what we may think, we are not individuals; what we say often has very little bearing on our actual behavior. We are, all of us, situated in a context. If we are to understand human behavior, then we must understand context, an argument for the holistic versus the atomized. A car is just an object; we cannot interpret anything about its driver until we have access to the chains of meaning that connect the driver to a social world.

我们越了解世界，越了解社会环境如何影响我们的行为，就越能体会到培养解读技能的意义。在本章后面，我将讨论如何从熟练走向精通这项技能。

The more we understand about worlds—and the ways in which social contexts pull our actions out of us—the more we can appreciate what it means to develop interpretive skills. Later in this chapter, I will discuss how we move from proficiency to mastery in this skill building.

不过，首先我想给大家讲一个关于我遇到的一位名叫妮可·波伦蒂尔的女士的简短故事。我之所以分享她的故事，是因为它完美地诠释了我们如何通过共同的情境获得技能和人生意义。我把它比作世界存在的情感证明，是抵御主流文化日益试图将我们的知识原子化、量化和缩减其深度的一道堡垒。讽刺的是，尽管这个故事证明了人文学科的力量，但它的主题直接来自脑科学的史册。

First, however, I want to tell you a brief story about a woman I met named Nicole Pollentier. I share her story with you because it perfectly illustrates how we acquire skills and meaning in our lives through our shared contexts. I liken it to an emotional proof of the existence of worlds, a bulwark against mainstream culture’s increasing attempts to atomize, quantify, and reduce the depth of our knowledge. Ironically enough, though this story offers a testament to the power of the humanities, its subject matter comes to us straight from the annals of brain science.

如何制作玉米粉蒸肉

How to Make Tamales

2012年冬天，妮可·波伦蒂尔（Nicole Pollentier）去了一趟塔吉特（Target）。对她身边的大多数购物者来说，这简直是一次再平常不过的经历。匹兹堡的这家塔吉特，依旧是樱桃红的靶心，依旧是大号购物车。然而，对波伦蒂尔来说，这件普通的事却意义非凡。就在两个月前，她从水泥楼梯上摔下来，遭受了创伤性脑损伤。自2011年11月4日事故发生以来，这次塔吉特之行是她第一次尝试走出公寓和诊所，去探索外面的世界。

It was the winter of 2012 and Nicole Pollentier was taking a trip to Target. For most of the shoppers around her, it couldn’t have been a more mundane experience. This particular Target in Pittsburgh had the same cherry-red bull’s eye, the same big-bin shopping carts. For Pollentier, however, the simple errand was a momentous event. Only two months before, she had suffered a traumatic brain injury after falling down a flight of cement stairs. The outing to Target was her first attempt to navigate the world outside of her apartment and her doctors’ offices since her accident on November 4, 2011.

硬膜下出血；蛛网膜下腔出血；颅骨骨折；颞骨和颅底骨折。这些短语构成了 Pollentier 用来向神经科医生和她自己描述她目前状况的新语言。她的工作记忆，即保存和处理新信息或已存储信息的能力，受到了严重损害。“你的工作记忆就像一个候诊室，”Polentier 告诉我。“所有信息都涌入这里，大脑判断哪些重要，哪些不重要，并立即决定哪些应该丢弃。如果某件事被认为很重要，大脑会在五分钟内还是五年内判断它是否重要。”

Subdural hemorrhage; subarachnoid hemorrhage; skull fractures; temporal bone and basilar skull fractures. These phrases formed the new language Pollentier used to describe her current condition to her neurologists as well as to herself. Her working memory, or the holding and processing of new or already stored information, was particularly impaired. “Your working memory is like a waiting room,” Pollentier told me. “Everything comes in here and the brain determines what is important and what is not important, making decisions instantaneously about what should be discarded. If something is deemed important, the brain then decides if it’s important in five minutes or in five years.”

在脑损伤之前，波伦蒂尔一直是一位颇有成就的诗人，所以这间“等候室”——她的工作记忆——对她的创作至关重要。“即使在小时候，”她告诉我，“我也能感觉到后来，当我的大脑回忆诗歌创作的素材时，我会看到所有东西都闪闪发光，当它们进入我的小等候室时，会发出“叮叮叮”的声音。它们被存放在诗歌创作区。这和“记住车辆登记”区的感觉总是很不一样。

Up until her brain injury, Pollentier was an accomplished poet, so this “waiting room”—her working memory—was essential to her work. “Even as a kid,” she told me, “I could feel when my brain was remembering things for poetry later on. I would see things as all aglow and when they entered my little waiting room, there was a ‘ding ding ding.’ They were stored in the poetry-making section. That always felt very different than the ‘remember car registration’ section.”

但波伦蒂尔的脑损伤让她几乎无法进行诗歌创作。事实上，她的伤势非常严重，甚至连最日常的差事都难以完成——比如去塔吉特百货。“我走进那家商店，就忍不住哭了起来。感官超负荷，真是让人困惑。就像孩子们兴奋不已，但这种兴奋突然变成了泪水和疲惫。我只能站在过道里哭。”

But Pollentier’s brain damage made it next to impossible for her to engage in poetry making. The injury was so severe, in fact, that she found it difficult to complete even the most routine of errands—Target, for example. “I walked in that store and I just started to cry. The sensory overload: it was so confusing. Like when kids get really excited but the excitement turns into tears and exhaustion all of a sudden. All I could do was stand in the aisle and cry.”

波伦蒂尔回到公寓，几个月来，她只出门去看医生——神经科医生、神经精神病学家和其他脑科专家。她不仅无法写诗，甚至连一些她最喜欢的诗歌和歌词都记不住。“我还记得歌词里的一句话，然后一切都变得一片空白。这些歌词我几十年来反复弹唱过。这种感觉和‘哦，它就在我的舌尖上’截然不同。一切都被抹去了。我不断地想起萨特的《禁闭》。被困在虚无之中。一片广阔的虚无。那种感觉真是太可怕了。”

Pollentier returned to her apartment and, for several months, she left only to see doctors—neurologists, neuro-psychiatrists, and other brain specialists. Not only was she incapable of writing poetry, she couldn’t even remember some of her favorite poetry and song lyrics. “I would remember one phrase from lyrics and then everything would go completely blank. These were lyrics I had played and sung over and over again for decades. It was a very different sensation than saying: ‘Oh, it’s on the tip of my tongue.’ Everything was wiped clean. I kept thinking of No Exit by Sartre. Trapped in nothing. A wide expanse of nothingness. It was absolutely terrifying.”

对于波伦蒂尔来说，一个存在的问题仍然存在：她如何理解她的世界？

For Pollentier, one single, existential question remained: How would she make sense of her world?

从硅谷的角度来看，Polentier 问题的答案可以在自然科学中找到。他们的理论关于心智运作方式的理论被称为“心智计算理论”，即认为大脑就像一台用0和1的数值编码的计算机一样工作。谷歌工程主管雷·库兹韦尔是这一理论的主要支持者之一，他2012年出版的《如何创造心智》一书描述了我们的灵魂和心智是如何成为我们大脑这台伟大计算机的机械部件的。他的论文被称为心智模式识别理论（PRTM），将我们的大脑皮层描述为一种基本的算法功能。他认为，我们已经在利用工程流程来解构和增强大脑中负责感知、记忆和批判性思维的部分。

From a Silicon Valley perspective, the answer to Pollentier’s question can be found in the natural sciences. Their theory for how the mind works is called “computational theory of the mind,” or the idea that the brain works like a computer encoded in numerical renderings of zeros and ones. The head of engineering at Google, Ray Kurzweil, is one of the leading proponents of this idea, and his 2012 book How to Create a Mind describes how our soul and mind are mechanistic parts of the great computer of our brain. His thesis is called pattern recognition theory of mind, or PRTM, which characterizes our neocortex as a basic algorithmic function. He argues that we are already using engineering processes to deconstruct and augment the parts of our brain responsible for perception, memory, and critical thinking.

在这种情况下，波伦蒂尔的困境与其说是一场存在主义的清算，不如说是一场处理能力和诊断能力的危机。据库兹韦尔等科学家称，她的大脑可能很快就会被拆开，分成离散的碎片进行分析。例如，当她描述失去歌词记忆后感到“空虚”时，库兹韦尔可能会安慰她，承诺会通过一种类似USB端口的机制，将这些歌词“上传”回她的大脑。

In this scenario, Pollentier’s dilemma is less an existential reckoning and more a crisis of processing power and diagnostics. According to scientists like Kurzweil, her brain could soon be taken apart and analyzed in discrete bits. When she described feeling “empty” at the loss of her memory of song lyrics, for example, Kurzweil might comfort her with the promise of “uploading” these song lyrics back into her brain through a mechanism similar in function to a USB port.

然而，波伦蒂尔的实际康复过程与雷·库兹韦尔设想的算法思维截然不同。摔倒数月后，她又开始离开公寓，跑腿办事，拜访朋友。她在一家博物馆做兼职。最终，波伦蒂尔再次渴望写诗，但她不知道该如何写。

Pollentier’s actual recovery, however, looked nothing like Ray Kurzweil’s vision of an algorithmic mind. Many months after her fall, she started to leave her apartment again to run errands and visit with friends. She took a part-time job working at a museum. And, eventually, Pollentier felt a longing to write poetry again. But she had no idea how.

去年冬天一个凉爽的日子，她醒来后突然很想吃玉米粉蒸肉。这种对食物的渴望本身就很不寻常，因为各种药物和她持续的疼痛让她胃里一阵翻江倒海。但天气的某些变化——阳光的清爽和空气中微微的寒意——让她心中升起了一种感觉。今天是“玉米粉蒸肉日”。

Then, on a cool day last winter, she woke up with a surprising craving for tamales. To even experience a craving for food at all was unusual because the various medications and her constant pain left her stomach queasy. But something about the weather—the crispness of the sun and the slight bite in the air—triggered a sensation in her. It was “tamale day.”

波伦蒂尔描述了她是如何走进自家小厨房的，当时她并没有完全意识到自己的意图。她开始给铸铁煎锅调味，而从那一瞬间起，她说自己心中涌起了一种极其强烈和好奇的冲动。她抓起一支铅笔，在一张纸片上写了些什么。

Without being fully aware of her own intentions, Pollentier described how she wandered into her small kitchen. She began to season her cast iron skillet and, from the experience of that action, she said she had the most intense and curious impulse. She grabbed a pencil and wrote something down on a scrap of paper.

“是所有这些因素的结合：煎锅，当天的心情，橄榄油和辣椒的香味。我能感觉到它以不同的方式储存在我大脑的候诊室里。我想，‘哦，我肯定把它藏起来了。’就在那一刻——当我把铅笔放在餐巾纸上时——我突然敏锐地意识到一件事：我正在写一首诗。”

“It was the combination of all those things: the skillet, the feeling of the day, the smell of the olive oil and chili peppers. I could feel it getting stored in my brain’s waiting room differently. I thought, ‘Oh I am definitely tucking this away.’ And at that moment—as I was putting pencil to the napkin—I suddenly became acutely aware of one thing: I was writing a poem.”

多年来，波伦蒂尔总是在圣诞节做玉米粉蒸肉，而这一天也感觉像过圣诞节一样。时值初冬，天气凉爽，太阳低垂。正是在这种特殊的环境下，她突然想起了如何做玉米粉蒸肉。这段记忆与遵循菜谱或理想膳食的概念无关。相反，它的回归与在小厨房里来回走动，与对玉米泥、香料、油和滚烫煎锅的独特质感的触感息息相关。玉米粉蒸肉在带盖的篮子里冷却时，她回到了那张纸上，完成了她的新诗——这是她三年多前脑损伤后的第一首诗。她称之为“在神经可塑性城市中构建路径”。

For years, Pollentier had made tamales on Christmas Day, and this day felt like a Christmas kind of day. It was early winter. It was cool outside and the sun was low in the sky. It was within this particular context that she suddenly remembered how to make tamales. This memory had nothing to do with following a recipe or the idea of an ideal meal. Instead, its return had everything to do with moving back and forth in the space of the small kitchen and the touch and perception of the particular textures of mashed corn and spices and oils and a piping-hot skillet. While the tamales were cooling in a covered basket, she went back to her scrap of paper and finished her new poem—the first one since the brain injury over three years ago. She called it “building pathways in the neuroplastic city.”

…我忘了怎么记住

… I forget how to remember

像单词一样的单词

the words that are like words

就像其他词一样

that are like other words

用途不同

with uses that are different

或者是房子的阴影暗示着其他的东西

or are houses to shadows that suggest other things

然后我又想起了一切

and then it all comes back to me

当一位技艺精湛的诗人从零开始创作时，这意味着什么？如果用硅谷的场景来描述波伦蒂尔的创作历程，大概是这样的：“我今天要写一首诗。我应该从一首关于窗外那棵树的诗开始吗？我会拿出一支铅笔，坐在书桌前，然后一字不差地写下来。什么是六行诗？什么是换行？没错。就是这样。现在——终于——树的概念被记录在纸上了。”

What does it mean when a skilled poet starts again from scratch? A Silicon Valley scenario of Pollentier’s journey might look something like this: “I am going to write a poem today. Should I begin with a poem about the idea of the tree out the window? I will take out a pencil, sit down at my desk, and then write it down, word by word. What is a sestina? What is a line break? Yes. There it is. And now—at last—the idea of a tree is captured on paper.”

但她技能的重现却与此截然不同。当波伦蒂尔重新掌握烹饪和诗歌知识时，这些技能并非以循序渐进或离散任务的方式回归。尽管计算心智理论让我们相信这一点，但波伦蒂尔的大脑并非一次处理一个输入或计算。在那个冬日，烹饪和写作的整个结构与无数细致的感官、质感和细微差别一同回归到她心中。相反，她的大脑展现出一个由意义和技能交织的世界组成的密集网络。雷·库兹韦尔希望我们将我们的灵魂、精神以及对艺术的热爱，视为大脑中纯粹的生物过程来分析。然而自然科学永远无法充分解释妮可·波伦蒂尔如何仅仅通过做玉米粉蒸肉就恢复了写诗的能力。

But the reemergence of her skills looked nothing at all like that. When Pollentier regained access to her knowledge of cooking and poetry, the skills didn’t come back to her in incremental steps or discrete tasks. Despite what the computational theory of mind would have us believe, Pollentier’s brain did not process one input or calculation at a time. On that winter day, the entire structure of cooking and writing returned to her in tandem with a myriad of detailed senses, textures, and nuances. Her brain revealed itself, instead, to be a dense web of worlds with overlapping meanings and skills. Ray Kurzweil would like us to analyze our souls, our spirits, and our love of art as pure biological processes in the brain. But the natural sciences will never adequately explain how Nicole Pollentier recovered her ability to write poetry simply by making a tamale.

文化参与和掌握阶段

Cultural Engagement and the Stages of Mastery

我们大多数人永远不会遭受创伤性脑损伤。有些人可能没有经历过失去诗歌等艺术天赋，然后再恢复的经历。我们中很少有人能够如此独特地理解自身的认知能力，以及它们可能如何受到挑战。从这些方面来看，波伦蒂尔正在踏上一段非凡的大脑疗愈之旅。

Most of us will never suffer from a traumatic brain injury. Some of us may not relate to the loss—and then the recovery—of an artistic talent like poetry. Very few of us will ever be so uniquely positioned to understand our own cognitive abilities and how they might be challenged. In all these ways, Pollentier is on an extraordinary journey toward healing her brain.

然而，妮可·波伦蒂尔的故事在某种程度上应该引起我们所有人的共鸣。与主导硅谷文化的心理理论相反，她的案例向我们展示了我们如何学习、思考和生活在不同的世界中。在烹饪的世界里，如果没有其他所有重要的事物——食材、盘子、客人等等——使用菜刀就毫无意义。对于波伦蒂尔来说，如果没有她试图描述的世界的肌肉记忆，诗歌创作就不可能实现。当她伸手去拿左边的橄榄油和右边的纸片时，她的行动是被社会环境从内心深处召唤出来的。

In one particular way, however, Nicole Pollentier’s story should resonate with all of us. Contrary to the theory of mind that dominates the Silicon Valley culture, her case shows us how we learn, think, and live in worlds. Using a kitchen knife is meaningless without everything else significant in the world of cooking: ingredients, plates, guests, and so forth. Poetry is impossible for Pollentier without muscle memories of the worlds she is attempting to describe. When she reaches out for the olive oil to her left and the scrap of paper to her right, her actions are summoned from deep within her by the social context.

加州大学伯克利分校哲学教授、海德格尔杰出诠释者休伯特·德雷福斯在其著作《心灵超越机器》中，概述了一种技能现象学，直接挑战了计算心智理论。他的解读为理解波伦蒂埃的康复及其含义提供了一些见解。德雷福斯认为，人类学习和技能不能简化为根据既定公式进行的理性计算。相反，他认为，当人们学习一项新技能时，他们会经历一系列精通的阶段。早期阶段由学习到的计算规则和理性计算的应用定义，但后期阶段则以精细磨练的直觉为特征，这种直觉在我们意识层面之下运作。这种直觉开始在意想不到的模式之间建立相似之处，并最终重塑所有曾经被视为神圣不可侵犯的规则。

In his book Mind Over Machine, Hubert Dreyfus, the preeminent interpreter of Heidegger and professor of philosophy at the University of California, Berkeley, outlines a phenomenology of skill that directly challenges computational theory of mind. His interpretation provides some insight into Pollentier’s recovery and its implications. Dreyfus argues that human learning and skill cannot be reduced to rational calculations according to set formulas. Instead, he maintains that, as people learn a new skill, they progress through a series of phases of mastery. Early stages are defined by the application of learned computational rules and rational calculation, but later stages are characterized by a finely honed intuition that works below the level of our awareness. This intuition begins to draw parallels between unexpected patterns and, ultimately, to reinvent all the rules once considered sacrosanct.

德雷福斯与其兄弟合作发展出的理念，提供了一个框架，帮助我们理解专家如何通过融入文化和社会背景而达到精湛的成就。正如波伦蒂尔只有进入诗歌世界才能写诗一样，我在本书后面介绍的大师们，只有在完全沉浸在自己选择的领域中时，才能发挥出最大的潜能。这就是人类智慧的运作方式，它精密复杂，令人惊叹。德雷福斯详细阐述了这一过程的发生过程。以下是我对他五个阶段过程的总结：

Dreyfus’s ideas, developed in collaboration with his brother, provide a framework for understanding how experts achieve mastery through an engagement with culture and social context. Just as Pollentier can only ever write poetry when she can access the world of poetry, the masters I introduce later in the book become most effective once they have fully immersed themselves in the world of their chosen endeavors. This is how human intelligence works, and it is a marvel of sophistication. Dreyfus breaks down how such a progression happens. Here is my summary of his five-stage process:

第一阶段：新手。在技能习得的第一阶段，新手会习得基于情境中“无上下文”元素来决定行动的规则。德雷福斯将根据预先学习的规则对这些元素的操控称为“信息处理”。例如，新手司机在达到特定速度时会换挡，无论他是否在上坡或引擎运转速度有多快——因为他知道应该以该速度换挡。或者，再举一个例子，商学院的新手只需输入市场份额，抽样调查结果，并将生产成本代入成本利润模型计算出市场分析结果。

Stage 1: Novice. In the first stage of skill acquisition, the novice acquires rules for determining actions based on “context-free” elements of a situation. Dreyfus calls the manipulation of these elements according to prelearned rules “information processing.” This is what happens when, for example, a beginning driver shifts gears in the car when he hits a certain speed regardless of whether he’s going uphill or how fast the engine seems to be working—because he understands that he’s supposed to shift at that speed. Or, to take another example, a novice business school student simply plugs in market share, sample survey results, and production costs into a cost-profit model to calculate a market analysis.

第二阶段：高级初学者。第二阶段的学习者能够根据先前的经验识别模式。这些模式是“情境化的”（与“脱离上下文”相对）。例如，狗主人能够识别自家狗独特的吠叫声，或者棋手能够识别过度伸展的局面。初级侍酒师可以将脱离语境的元素（例如葡萄酒的年份、品种和产地）融入到已学的公式中，以帮助判断某瓶酒是否“好”。然而，这些规则只能帮助他走到这一步——其余的判断则基于他之前对同一年份和产地葡萄酒的体验。第一阶段和第二阶段的关键区别在于，高级初学者学会运用先前的经验，而不是简单地遵循脱离语境的预先学过的公式。

Stage 2: Advanced Beginner. The second-stage learner is able to recognize a pattern based on prior experience. These patterns are “situational” (in contrast to “context-free”). For example, a dog owner’s recognition of his dog’s distinctive bark, or the chess player’s recognition of overextended positions. A beginning novice sommelier can take decontextualized elements, such as a wine’s vintage, varietal, and region, and insert them into learned formulas to help determine if a particular bottle is “good” or not. However, these rules only take him so far—the rest of his judgment is based on his previous experience with wines from that year and region. The key difference between the first and second stages is that the advanced beginner learns to apply prior experience, rather than simply follow context-free prelearned formulas.

第三阶段：胜任。在第三阶段，与上下文无关的因素和情境因素的数量非常庞大，这迫使学习者采用层级化的决策程序，以便优先考虑与情境最相关的因素。例如，一位胜任的销售主管会首先确定所有销售目标是否都已达成。如果没有，她会与每个销售团队会面，询问他们为何业绩不佳。当四个团队中有三个告诉她产品线产品过多时，她会主动与上司沟通，精简产品清单。在层级结构中的每个决策过程中，她只会关注众多因素中的几个。影响整个项目。例如，她不会试图辨别团队在数字方面遇到的困难是否存在不那么理性的原因。这种行为是一种理性的解决问题的过程，它利用先前的经验和计算规则来执行任务。

Stage 3: Competence. In the third stage, the number of context-free and situational elements is overwhelming, which forces the learner to adopt a hierarchical procedure for decision making that helps prioritize the most relevant elements of the situation. A competent head of sales, for example, will first determine if all of the sales goals are being met. If not, she will meet with each one of her sales teams and ask them why they are struggling with their numbers. When three of the four teams tell her that there are too many products in the line, she will initiate a conversation with her boss to winnow down the product list. During each decision in the hierarchy, she pays attention to only a few of the immense number of factors impinging on the overall project. She does not, for example, attempt to discern if there is a less rational reason for her team’s struggles with their numbers. This type of behavior is a rational problem-solving process that makes use of both prior experience and computational rules for executing tasks.

第四阶段：熟练。熟练的学习者会快速、流畅、投入地学习，这种学习方式并非理性地运用规则，而是能够识别从过去经验积累中浮现出的模式。熟练的学习者会从整体上看待问题，而不是将各个元素视为独立的个体，并根据规则理解这些元素之间的关系并采取行动。在威廉·吉布森2003年的小说《模式识别》中，主人公凯西·波拉德对衍生的公司标识产生了一种直觉的、本能的、生理上的负面反应。她无法解释标识的哪些部分出了问题——只有整体才能引发本能反应，并决定行动的方向。

Stage 4: Proficiency. A proficient learner engages in a rapid, fluid, and “involved” behavior that is not characterized by rational application of rules. Rather, it is characterized by recognition of patterns that emerge out of the accumulation of past experience. The proficient learner sees the situation in its totality, rather than as discrete elements whose relationship can be understood and acted upon based on rules. In William Gibson’s 2003 novel Pattern Recognition, the protagonist Cayce Pollard has an immediate, intuitive, and physically negative reaction to derivative corporate logos. It is impossible for her to explain which components of the logos are off—it’s the thing in its entirety that evokes a visceral response and determines the course of action.

第五阶段：专业知识。当一个人获得专业知识时，他们对实践的参与程度会变得如此深入，以至于在这个过程中几乎没有理性思考。“专家的技能已经成为他的一部分，他无需意识到这一点，就像他无需意识到自己的身体一样。”在这个最高水平的能力下，决策是非理性的（也就是说，对情况的评估缺乏有意识的分析分解和重组）。这是“基于具体经验积累和……的复杂熟练行为”。无意识地将新情况识别为与记忆中的完整情况相似。”例如，小说大师科尔森·怀特黑德在其 2016 年出版的《地下铁路》一书中描述了其中涉及的模式识别过程。当他问自己这个问题时，他产生了强烈的本能反应：“如果地下铁路是一条真实的铁路会怎样？”他以此作为全书的开端，依靠他的专业直觉将他童年记忆中的流行寓言时刻编织进去。“我最早沉浸在奇幻之中可能是《阴阳魔界》的重播，”他告诉《纽约时报》。 “奴隶女孩科拉从真正的地下铁路出来，看到一座摩天大楼：那是一个典型的《阴阳魔界》时刻，你朝错误的方向迈出一步，突然间你就进入了一个偏离方向的世界。”

Stage 5: Expertise. When someone acquires expertise, their level of involvement with their practice becomes so involved that little rational thought goes into the process. “An expert’s skill has become so much a part of him that he need be no more aware of it than he is of his own body.” At this highest level of competency, decision making is arational (that is, assessment of the situation lacks conscious analytic decomposition and recombination). This is “involved skilled behavior based on an accumulation of concrete experiences and the unconscious recognition of new situations as similar to whole remembered ones.” Masterful novelist Colson Whitehead, for example, described the pattern recognition process involved in his 2016 book The Underground Railroad. He had a strong visceral response when he asked himself the question: “What if the Underground Railroad was a real railroad?” Using that as a launching conceit for the book, he relied on his expert intuition to weave in pop fabulist moments he remembered from his childhood. “My earliest immersion into the fantastic was probably reruns of The Twilight Zone,” he told the New York Times. “Slave girl Cora emerging from the literal underground railroad and seeing a skyscraper: That’s a quintessential Twilight Zone moment, where you take a step in the wrong direction and suddenly you’re in a world a little off to the side.”

当技艺精湛的球员沉浸在自己的技艺中时，效果往往令人叹为观止。他们能够以令人激动的方式展现自己的世界，并开启新世界的各种可能性。以尼克斯队著名球员、后来的罗德学者和总统候选人比尔·布拉德利为例，在他状态正佳的时候：“过肩投篮其实没有名字，”约翰·麦克菲在1965年《纽约客》上撰写的比尔·布拉德利的个人简介文章中写道。“他看都没看，就把球从头顶扔进了篮筐。他解释说，没必要看，因为‘你会逐渐意识到自己身在何处’。”正确的动作并非由演员决定，而是直接源于整体情境。这是一种身体上的——而非大脑的——全然引人入胜的体验。

When the extremely skilled are absorbed in their craft, the effect is uncanny. They have the ability of revealing their world—and opening up possibilities for new worlds—in thrilling ways. Take Bill Bradley, the famed Knicks player and later Rhodes scholar and presidential candidate, when he was really on his game: “The over-the-shoulder shot had no actual name,” John McPhee wrote in his 1965 New Yorker essay profiling Bill Bradley. “He tossed it, without looking, over his head and into the basket. There was no need to look, he explained, because ‘you develop a sense of where you are.’” The proper course of action is not determined by the actor; rather, it emerges directly from the totality of the situation. It is a bodily—not cerebral—and totally absorbing experience.
