我们必须承认他们的文化，将这种关系从操纵转变为合作。

We had to acknowledge their culture to transform the relationship from a manipulation to a collaboration.

2006年1月7日，一位名叫吉尔·卡罗尔的年轻美国记者在巴格达阿德尔区遭蒙面枪手伏击绑架。卡罗尔的司机成功逃脱，但她的翻译却在现场被枪杀，随后被遗弃。卡罗尔被绑架的消息——这是伊拉克战争期间第31起针对外国记者的此类袭击——引起了国际社会的震惊和热烈的支持。

On January 7, 2006, a young American journalist named Jill Carroll was kidnapped in the Adel district of Baghdad after being ambushed by masked gunmen. Carroll’s driver managed to escape, but her interpreter was shot dead on site and then abandoned. News of Carroll’s kidnapping—the thirty-first such attack on foreign journalists during the war with Iraq—was met with international alarm and an outpouring of support.

近两周没有卡罗尔的消息，直到 1 月 17 日，半岛电视台播放了一段她的视频。吉尔·卡罗尔的声音被剪掉了，她头上没有戴帽子，头发凌乱，两名身着黑衣、戴着面具的男子分别站在她身旁，手里拿着枪。第三名男子站在她身后，也身着黑衣，戴着面具，手里拿着一本书，高举过她的头顶。视频要求在72小时内释放所有被关押在伊拉克监狱的女性，否则卡罗尔将立即被处决。

Nothing was heard from Carroll for close to two weeks and then, on January 17, Al Jazeera showed a video featuring her. Jill Carroll’s voice had been edited out, her head was uncovered and her hair disheveled, and there were two men all in black with masked faces standing on either side of her holding guns. A third man was standing directly behind her—also in black with a masked face—holding a book above her head. The video demanded that all the women in Iraqi jails be released within 72 hours, or Carroll would face immediate execution.

在这样的危机时刻，联邦调查局会召集一支技艺精湛的谈判专家团队，制定下一步行动方案。克里斯·沃斯在联邦调查局工作了二十多年，曾担任联邦调查局危机谈判部门的首席国际绑架谈判专家。他至今仍记得第一次看到卡罗尔被公开的视频的那一刻。由于多年的训练，他能够立即解读视频中的信息。

In a moment of crisis like this, the FBI calls upon a team of highly skilled negotiators to navigate the next steps. Chris Voss, an FBI agent for more than two decades, was the lead international kidnapping negotiator in the FBI’s crisis negotiation unit. He remembers the moment he saw the first released video of Carroll. Because of his years of training, he was immediately able to decode its message.

“案件一开始，看起来就很糟糕，”他告诉我。“视频里，很明显他们已经对她做出了判决。那个男人拿着一本书站在她身后，这说明她已经被更高权力审判定罪了。他们把这事儿说成不是谋杀，而是国家正当的处决。”

“When the case started, it looked really bad,” he told me. “In that video, it was clear that they had already passed judgment on her. The guy is standing behind her with a book, and that is communicating that she has been tried and convicted by a higher power. They are framing this not as a murder, but as a justified execution by a state.”

和沃斯的所有谈判一样，他在卡罗尔案中的首要任务是确定究竟是谁在与谁谈判。他认为绑架者的要求是设下圈套，因为美国人——或者任何其他人——都无法实际评估伊拉克监狱里关押了多少女性，更不用说确定她们是否能在短短几天内获释。这一要求的大胆程度，对沃斯来说，是第一个警示信号：绑架者实际上并没有与西方任何人谈判。

As in all of Voss’s negotiations, his first priority in the Carroll case was to determine who, exactly, is negotiating with whom. He described the kidnappers’ demand as a setup because there was no realistic way for the Americans—or anyone—to assess how many women were in the Iraqi jails, much less determine whether they might be freed in a matter of only days. The audacity of the request was the first warning sign to Voss that the kidnappers were not, in fact, negotiating with anyone in the West.

“我们不是那个视频的观众。他们正在说话。”中东那些犹豫不决的人。正因为如此，我们的下一步必须找到一种能引起同一群人共鸣的沟通方式。

“We are not the audience for that video. They are speaking to the undecided in the Middle East. Because of that, our next step had to be a way of communicating that resonated with that same group of people.”

在这种微妙的谈判中——主要通过媒体平台进行——许多挑战都围绕着如何有效地指导家属向媒体传递信息。这些信息随后会被传播到世界各地。

In this type of delicate negotiation—orchestrated primarily through the theater of the media—many of the challenges revolve around effectively coaching family members in the messages delivered to the press. These messages are then broadcast out across the world.

“在我们处理卡罗尔案的时候，”沃斯向我解释道，“我们已经逐渐了解了伊拉克叛乱分子最关心的文化主题。如果我们希望将这种关系从操纵转变为合作，就必须承认他们的文化。”

“By the time we worked on the Carroll case,” Voss explained to me, “we had come to develop an understanding of the cultural themes that mattered most to these insurgents in Iraq. We had to acknowledge their culture if we had any hope of transforming the relationship from a manipulation to a collaboration.”

对沃斯来说，这种转变始终始于积极倾听，也终于积极倾听；他称其为我们解决复杂社会问题时最未得到充分利用的工具。但只有当我们怀有一种特殊的同理心时，积极倾听才有可能。我们可以将其比作我在第四章中描述的分析性同理心。

For Voss, this transformation always begins and ends with active listening; he calls it our most underutilized tool in solving complex social problems. But active listening is only possible when we engage with a particular kind of empathy. We can liken this to the analytical empathy I described in Chapter Four.

“说清楚这种同理心不是什么几乎更容易：它不关乎友善；它不关乎赞同；它不关乎喜欢对方。它只是直接的观察，然后清晰地表达你所看到的。我可以同情圣战者约翰，一个恐怖分子刽子手。这与赞同他的行为无关。”

“It’s almost easier to say what this type of empathy is not: It’s not about being nice; it’s not about agreeing; it’s not about liking the other side. It is just straight observation and then an articulation of what you see. I can be empathic with Jihadi John, a terrorist executioner. It doesn’t have anything to do with approving of his actions.”

沃斯凭借以往案件的经验以及精湛的谈判技巧，与团队精心策划了正确的信息。这一策略涉及向所有与媒体接触的人——包括家属和政界人士——传达信息。

Using his experience with previous cases and his well-developed skills with this type of negotiation, Voss worked with his team to meticulously craft the right message. This approach involved sending out messages to everyone in contact with the media—including family members and politicians.

“当有人问起吉尔·卡罗尔一案时，我们会说：‘你们看到他们让她不戴头巾，这是多么不尊重她吗？他们违反了自己的规矩。’然后政客、媒体、家属，他们都会说：‘是啊，你说得对。’然后他们会在所有媒体露面中重复这种不尊重的观念。我们无法向他们解释我们的信息。他们必须通过我们来发现，然后才能全情投入地重复这种观念。”

“When anyone asked us about the Jill Carroll case, we would say, ‘Did you see how they disrespected her by leaving her head uncovered? They broke their own rules.’ And then politicians, media, family, they would all say: ‘Yeah. You’re right.’ And then they would repeat this same idea about disrespect in all of their media appearances. We can’t explain our message to them. They have to discover it through us so they can repeat it with their full emotional investment.”

这种媒体操纵只是多管齐下策略中的一步。与此同时，沃斯的团队正在与吉尔·卡罗尔的家人合作，指导他们如何进行谈话。

That media manipulation was one step in a multipronged strategy. Simultaneously, Voss’s team was working with Jill Carroll’s family and coaching them on their talking points.

任何有效的谈判都需要始于表达一个不容置疑的事实。对于不容置疑的事实，无论站在哪一边，都无法提出异议。人们总是想说，‘她是无辜的’，或者‘他们不应该绑架她’。媒体上的这些信息适得其反。它们只是在对我们说话。我们需要与中东那些犹豫不决的人对话。

“Any effective negotiation always needs to begin by expressing an inarguable truth. With an inarguable truth, no one can disagree no matter what side they are on. People always want to say, ‘She’s innocent,’ or ‘They shouldn’t have kidnapped her.’ These messages in the media are counterproductive. They are only speaking to us. We needed to speak to the undecided in the Middle East.”

卡罗尔家族的几位成员——包括她的母亲和姐姐——并不完全相信如此严格的剧本有什么好处。他们想用自己的语言表达愤怒、恐惧和悲伤。然而，吉尔·卡罗尔的父亲吉姆·卡罗尔却同意了。沃斯知道，让吉姆·卡罗尔作为信使，是对叛乱分子的一种尊重，因为在中东文化中，所有荣誉都源于父亲。他与CNN达成了独家媒体协议，允许一名摄影师拍摄吉姆·卡罗尔只讲述剧本的片段，不包含其他采访问题或分析。这段视频随后将直接发送给半岛电视台。

Several members of the Carroll family—including her mother and sister—were not fully convinced of the merits of such a strict script. They wanted to express their fury, fear, and sadness in their own words. Jim Carroll, Jill Carroll’s dad, however, agreed. Voss knew that using Jim Carroll as the messenger would be a cue of respect to the insurgents because in Middle Eastern cultures, all honor flows through the father. He arranged for an exclusive media agreement with CNN where a cameraman could film Jim Carroll stating only his script, with no other interview questions or analysis. This video would then be sent directly to Al Jazeera.

“我们指导了吉尔·卡罗尔的父亲整个治疗过程。我们一开始就有一个不容置疑的事实：“吉尔·卡罗尔不是你们的敌人。” 随后，我们继续向中东的观众发出呼吁：“吉尔·卡罗尔一直在报道伊拉克人民的困境。” 最后，吉姆·卡罗尔说：“等你们让她走，她还会回去继续做同样的报道。”

“We coached Jill Carroll’s dad on the entire approach. We started with an inarguable truth: ‘Jill Carroll is not your enemy.’ From there, we continued to make an appeal to the viewers in the Middle East. ‘Jill Carroll had been reporting on the plight of the Iraqi people.’ And then finally Jim Carroll said, ‘When you let her go, she will go back to doing the same reporting.’”

这段视频未经剪辑就被发给了中东媒体。虽然沃斯和他的团队无法左右播出的时间和地点，但他们确信叛乱分子迟早会看到它。直到后来吉尔·卡罗尔获释后，沃斯才得知吉姆·卡罗尔的言论对她的获释起到了至关重要的作用。

The video went out unedited to Middle Eastern media sources. Although Voss and his team had no influence over when and where it aired, they had confidence that the insurgents would see it at some point. It was only later, upon Jill Carroll’s release, that Voss learned that Jim Carroll’s words played a powerful role in her release.

吉尔·卡罗尔告诉我们，绑架者在半岛电视台看到她父亲时，说：‘你父亲是个正直的人。’在中东，如果有人说你父亲是个正直的人，那真是轰动。你和你的家人周围都笼罩着一层荣誉的盾牌。几周后，他们公布了她的下一个视频，视频里她独自一人，头发上戴着头巾。

“Jill Carroll told us that when her kidnappers saw her father on Al Jazeera, they said: ‘Your father is an honorable man.’ In the Middle East, if someone says your father is an honorable man, bang. There is a shield of honor around you and everyone in your family. The very next video that they released with her a few weeks later, she is by herself and her hair is covered with a headscarf.”

第三段也是最后一段视频于2006年2月9日发布。视频中，吉尔·卡罗尔身着伊斯兰服饰，继续恳求各方支持她的获释，但她的声音出现在视频中，而且她独自一人坐着，周围没有武装人员。

A third and final video was released on February 9, 2006. In it, Jill Carroll sits in full Islamic dress. She continues to plead for support with her release, but her voice is included in the video and she sits alone with no armed men standing around her.

“第三段视频里，没有任何威胁的感觉，”沃斯解释道。“我很清楚，这些人只是想办法让她走，挽回面子。她很平静，看起来被照顾得很好。他们对内容有百分之百的控制权，所以当我们看到那段视频时，就知道她是安全的。”

“In the third video, there was no sense of a threat,” Voss explained. “It was clear to me that these guys were just trying to figure out how to let her go and save face. She was calm and she looked very well taken care of. They have one hundred percent control of the content, so when we saw that video, we knew she was safe.”

同年 3 月 30 日，吉尔·卡罗尔正式获释。她走进位于巴格达的逊尼派伊拉克伊斯兰党办公室，告诉那里的官员，在被囚禁的60多天里，她得到了照顾和人道待遇，最终毫发无损地获释。

On March 30 of that same year, Jill Carroll was officially released. She walked into the Sunni Iraqi Islamic Party offices in Baghdad and told officials there that she had been freed unharmed after being cared for and treated humanely during her more than sixty days in captivity.

沃斯的独特技能将敏锐的情商与他对中东文化的经验和了解完美融合。如果没有这些优势，他在吉尔·卡罗尔案中的成功是不可能实现的。“我喜欢把谈判定义为情商的升级版，”沃斯说道。“成功的关键在于掌控对方的情绪。在人质劫持事件中，情绪可能看起来比平时更强烈，但这并不意味着它们有什么不同。”

Voss’s particular skill set synthesized an acute emotional intelligence with his experience and knowledge of the Middle Eastern culture. His success with the Jill Carroll case would not have been possible without either of those strengths. “I like to define negotiation as emotional intelligence on steroids,” Voss said. “The key to success is navigating the other person’s emotions. In a hostage situation, emotions might seem to be larger than normal, but it doesn’t mean they’re any different.”

凭借其谈判技巧，他能够理解多种不同语境下的叙事和信息，从而应对高风险局势：他自身的语境、美国媒体的语境、绑架者的语境，以及最终关注事件进展的中东民众的语境。他将每一种语境都融入到他更宏大的策划中：最终目标是确保卡罗尔获释。

Through his interpretive skills as a negotiator, he approached a high-stakes situation with an understanding of narrative and messaging in several different contexts: his own, the context of the American media, the context of the kidnappers, and, finally, the context of the Middle Eastern population watching the unfolding drama. He played each and every context as part of his greater orchestration: the goal of a securing a release for Carroll.

我们过去常说，最危险的谈判是你浑然不知的谈判。恐怖分子在影片中威胁美国人，究竟是谁的目标？他们不在乎美国人的反应。他们想的都是圣战约翰，他现在可是万人迷。全球各地都有想成为圣战约翰的恶棍。他们都想加入他们。

“We used to say the most dangerous negotiation is the one you don’t know you’re in. Who is a terrorist’s target by threatening an American on film? They don’t care how Americans respond. They are thinking about Jihadi John, who is now a heartthrob. They have miscreants around the globe who want to be Jihadi John. They all want to join up.”

尽管世界各地有多家媒体和政界人士为吉尔·卡罗尔发声，每一个努力都是她最终获释的因素，但卡罗尔说，在她父亲的视频在电视上播出后，绑架者立即开始区别对待她。

Although there were several other media and political efforts around the globe advocating for Jill Carroll—each one a factor in her ultimate release—Carroll reported that her captors started treating her differently immediately after the video of her father was shown on TV.

“打击恐怖主义最有效的武器之一就是真相，”沃斯说道。“真相是吉尔·卡罗尔并非绑架者的敌人。她的父亲说出了这个真相，全世界也都重复了这句话。”

“One of the most effective weapons against terrorism is the truth,” Voss stated. “The truth was that Jill Carroll was not the enemy of her captors. Her father spoke that truth, and the rest of the world repeated it.”

成为鉴赏家

Becoming a Connoisseur

希拉·希恩 (Sheila Heen)、玛格丽特·维斯塔格 (Margrethe Vestager) 和克里斯·沃斯 (Chris Voss) 都找到了一种运用阐释技巧成功探索世界的方法。为了帮助我们更好地理解这一点，我提供了一个常与美术或烹饪相关的词：鉴赏家 (connoisseur)。在我们的意义建构之旅中，我想追溯这个词的法语词源：动词connaître 的意思是“熟悉”或“了解某人/某地”。精通—— connaissance——是一种在知识体系中探索的方式。

Sheila Heen, Margrethe Vestager, and Chris Voss have all found a way to successfully navigate their worlds with interpretative skills. To help us to understand this better, I offer up a word often associated with the fine arts or culinary endeavors: connoisseur. For our sensemaking journey, I would like to return the word to its French origins: the verb connaître means “to be acquainted with” or “to know somebody/a place.” Mastery—connaissance—is a way of navigating through a body of knowledge.

我们在所选事业上走得越远——无论是教学、人质谈判还是政治——我们就越能对知识进行分类。以烹饪肉类的技巧为例。在美国，我们认识到五个阶段，从一分熟（rare）开始，到全熟（well-done）结束。然而，在法国，肉类和烹饪文化要丰富得多。法国厨师必须在九个不同的类别中做出选择，从蓝纹牛排（bleu）——轻轻触碰热锅，内部完全是生的牛排——一直到碳化牛排（carbonisé），或者非常熟，甚至外面像皮革一样。在法国烹饪中，一分熟（rare）和五分熟（medium rare）之间有一个非常重要的点——一点（à point） ——在美国是无法要求的。随着我们在理解中积累更多经验，我们发现了更多的分析类别。这就是成为一名鉴赏家：这是探索世界的一种方式。

The further we go into our chosen endeavors—whether they be teaching, hostage negotiation, or politics—the more we can categorize our knowledge. Consider techniques for cooking meat. In the United States we recognize five stages, beginning with rare and ending with well-done. In France, however, the culture of meat and cooking is much richer. French chefs must navigate among nine different categories, beginning with bleu—a steak that has lightly touched a hot pan, remaining completely raw inside—all the way up to carbonisé, or extremely well-done and even leathery on the outside. There is a very important spot between rare and medium rare in French cooking—à point—that one cannot ask for in the United States. As we add more experience to our sensemaking, we discover more analytical categories. This is the process of becoming a connoisseur: it is a way of navigating through the world.

回想一下希拉·希恩：她的学习历程以对课堂氛围的了解日益加深为特征。现在，她能够识别课堂上更多样的情绪，并因此能够成功地引导学生掌握教学时机。如果课堂气氛冷淡、安静，到处都是疲惫或孤僻的面孔，她就会加入一些幽默和趣味。另一方面，如果课堂上充满了反抗和愤怒——那些不愿出席的管理人员——她就会想办法将自己的兴趣与他们的利益结合起来。她把自己融入到他们的团队中，鼓励他们向她倾诉他们的挫败感。

Recall Sheila Heen: her journey is characterized by an ever-increasing knowledge of the atmosphere of her students in the room. She is now able to recognize many more moods in her classroom and, as a result, she can navigate successfully toward her teaching moments. If the room is cold and quiet, filled with tired or withdrawn faces, she knows to add in some humor and playfulness. If, on the other hand, it is a room filled with defiance and anger—managers who don’t really want to be in attendance—she finds a way to align her interests with theirs. She puts herself on the same team with them and encourages them to confide their frustrations in her.

起初，我专注于笔记，全神贯注于如何向学生讲解内容。经过多年的小组教学，我对教学材料有了足够的信心，教学过程也更加自然流畅，我也能更好地融入课堂氛围。我能从学生的表情中看到更多东西。谁在认真听讲，谁不在听，谁愿意用幽默的方式与学生互动，谁比较沉默寡言。

“Early on I would be attached to my notes and I was putting all my attention on how to explain the content to my students. After years and years of working with groups, I felt confident enough in the material to let the teaching come more automatically, and I could tune into the room. I could see so much more on the faces of the students. Who was paying attention and who was not, who was open to engagement with humor and who was more reticent.”

随着教学达到一定水平，这些社交敏锐度的分析类别也更加精湛。Heen不仅能够识别她与每位学生之间存在的动态，还能识别学生之间的不同关系。在她早期的职业生涯中，她可能将某个人视为领导者，而将另一群人视为该领导者手下的管理者。随着时间的推移，这些类别发展出数十种甚至数百种不同的方式，用于对团队内部层级关系进行分类。房间里。Heen 成为了人际关系和社会氛围的鉴赏家。

As her teaching reached a level of mastery, these analytical categories of social acuity increased even more. Heen was able to recognize not only the dynamics that existed between her and each individual student but the different relationships between the students themselves. Earlier in her career, she might have recognized someone as the leader, and another group of people as managers under that leader. Over time, these categories exploded into dozens and even hundreds of different ways of categorizing the relationship to the hierarchy within the room. Heen became a connoisseur of human relationships and social moods.

她描述了自己在伦敦给满屋子位高权重的银行家授课的情景。“每个人都很重要，房间里没有等级之分。正因如此，我知道我可以利用地位，并以此作为一种教学工具，享受其中的乐趣。有一次我忘了给后面一张桌子讲话，就开了个玩笑，把它叫做‘辅导桌’。整个教室都充满了欢笑和善意。这句话用在银行业25位最有权势的人身上再合适不过了。它让我们所有人都敞开心扉，互相学习。”

She described a moment when she was teaching to a room filled with high-powered bankers in London. “Everyone was important and there was not a lot of pecking order to the room. For that very reason, I knew I could use status and have some fun with it as a teaching tool. When I forgot to address a table in the back, I made a joke and called it the ‘remedial table.’ The entire room lit up with laughter and goodwill. It was just the right thing to say to twenty-five of the most powerful people in banking. It opened all of us up to learn from each other.”

对于欧盟委员玛格丽特·维斯塔格来说，意义建构知识的特点是对整个政治体系内不同节奏的日益敏感。在政坛摸爬滚打了二十年后，她如今能够发现别人看不到的潜在改革机会。同样，她也知道什么时候无法推动某件事的进展。

For Margrethe Vestager, the EU commissioner, sensemaking knowledge is characterized by an increasing sensitivity to different rhythms within the whole of the political system. After two decades in politics, she can now see opportunities for possible reforms that others cannot see. And, by the same token, she also knows when she can’t move something forward.

“什么时候做和做什么一样重要，”她向我解释道。“启动一项新倡议或政治计划的窗口期通常很短。我摸索着理解这一点。人们准备好了吗？他们现在能接受更多的改变吗？当我们这样做的时候，人们的情绪会是什么样的？”

“When to do something is as important as what to do,” she explained to me. “The window to launch a new initiative or a political program is often so small. I feel my way to understand this. Are people ready for this? Can they take more change now? What emotional state will people be in when we do this?”

谈判专家克里斯·沃斯学会了如何解读他人声音中不同的情绪。他的倾听技巧能够帮助他判断何时存在合作的可能性。“当你开始留意对话中隐含的积极和消极因素时，你就可以有针对性地强化积极因素，弱化消极因素，”他说。“虽然这可能还不够，“你总是可以以某种方式依靠它。这绝对需要练习，而且它绝对是一项容易消失的技能。”

And Chris Voss, the negotiator, has learned to navigate through the varying emotional registers in other people’s voices. His listening skills guide him in assessing when there is openness for possible collaboration. “When you begin to get an ear for the positives and negatives implied in the conversation, you can specifically choose to reinforce the positives and diminish the negatives,” he said. “And although it might not be enough, you can always lean into it in some way. It definitely takes practice and it is absolutely a perishable skill.”

在所有这些旅程中，人们总幻想着某个模型或理论能够将所有因素统合到一个框架下：比如可以接入的GPS，或者在黑暗中提供导航的卫星。然而，真正的行家明白，没有唯一的正确答案。导航并非关注一切，而是巧妙地诠释事物。

On all of these journeys, the siren song is that there will be a model or a theory of everything that will organize all of the various factors under one framework: the GPS to plug in or a satellite to provide guidance through the dark. The true connoisseur, however, understands that there is no one right answer. Navigation is not about paying attention to everything. It is about artfully interpreting something.

Heen 更加注重等级制度在教学中的作用。当她走进教室时，她能够感知到自己的地位会被如何看待，以及如何化解或提升这种地位，从而更好地营造学习环境。

Heen pays more attention to the role that hierarchy plays in her teaching. When she enters a room, she is able to sense how her own status will be received and how to either diffuse that status or elevate it in order to gain traction for a better learning environment.

维斯塔格需要了解其政治行动的次要和次要后果。为此，她对欧盟治理体系的了解，如同其亲密朋友一般。她能够洞悉所接触的新体系，了解其是紧张、兴奋、充满希望还是沮丧。这些知识指导着她决定哪些类型的变革是可能的。

Vestager needs to know the secondary and tertiary consequences of her political actions. To do this, she has developed her knowledge of the EU’s system of governance as if it is an intimate friend. She can get a read on a new system she encounters and know if it is stressed out, excited, hopeful, or despondent. This knowledge guides her decisions about what types of changes are possible.

沃斯敏锐地意识到操纵的细微之处。无论是在调查、设置路障还是绑架谈判中，他总是在寻找机会，将操纵转化为合作。他擅长在不使用任何手段或武力威胁的情况下，让人们与他对话。

Voss is keenly aware of the nuances of manipulation. Whether he is in an investigation or a barricade situation or a kidnapping negotiation, he is always looking for windows of opportunity to shift manipulation into collaboration. He excels at getting people to talk to him without using leverage, or threatening force.

三位大师都以这种方式，从各自的技艺中培养出一种视角。正是这种视角最终引领我们走向鉴赏力：审美判断。导航由此成为一种诠释艺术。无论是科学还是人文领域，通往同一目的地的道路有很多条。哪一条最美？哪一条最引人注目？哪一条最强大？哪一条最令人愉悦？算法可以达到优化，但只有人类——艺术家、思想家、数学家、企业家、政治家——只有具备洞察力的人才能解读目的地的意义。大师们毕生致力于追求这种诠释。这就是他们理解世界的方式。

In this way, all three of these masters have cultivated a perspective from within their given craft. And it is this perspective that ultimately leads to the most defining aspect of connoisseurship: aesthetic judgment. This is where navigation becomes an interpretive art. In both the sciences and humanist endeavors, there are many possible roads to the same destination. Which one is the most beautiful? The most compelling? The most powerful? The most pleasing? An algorithm can arrive at optimization, but only a human being—an artist, a thinker, a mathematician, an entrepreneur, a politician—only someone with a sense of perspective can interpret the meaning of the destination. Masters spend their entire lives in pursuit of this interpretation. This is how they make sense of the world.

意义建构的炼金术

The Alchemy of Sensemaking

在加州纳帕谷29号公路旁，一座灰色的谷仓矗立在一片数英亩的圣乔治砧木葡萄园中，其简洁的建筑线条体现了另一个时代的韵味。谷仓前悬挂着一个用绳索打结的秋千，一辆普锐斯孤零零地停放在小小的停车场里。这就是科里森酒庄，德高望重的酿酒师凯茜·科里森的故乡。近四十年来，她一直以自己的方式酿造纳帕谷赤霞珠。

Just off Route 29 in California’s Napa Valley, a gray barn with the clean architectural lines of another era stands watch over several acres of St. George rootstock vineyards. A knotted rope swing hangs in front of the property, and one lone Prius is parked in the small lot. This is the Corison Winery, home to the venerable Cathy Corison, a winemaker who has been making Napa Valley Cabernet on her own terms for close to forty years.

虽然谷仓内部简陋——没有正式的品酒室，摆放着酒瓶和酒杯的野餐桌与酒罐和木桶并排摆放——但科里森出来见我时，却散发着一种沉静的力量。如今年过花甲的科里森在纳帕谷社区赢得了自己的声誉。她从加州大学戴维斯分校（美国首屈一指的葡萄酒研究机构）获得酿酒学硕士学位后，开始在纳帕谷工作。

Though the interior of the barn is humble—there is no formal tasting room, and picnic tables holding wine bottles and glasses sit side by side with wine tanks and wood barrels—Corison exudes a quiet power when she comes out to meet me. Now in her early sixties, Corison has earned her stripes in the Napa Valley community. After graduating with a master’s degree in enology from the University of California at Davis, the country’s preeminent wine studies program, she started working in the Napa Valley.

禁酒令颁布后的几年里，纳帕谷的葡萄酒业只有几家不起眼的葡萄园和大量的甜葡萄酒。我们所知的现代葡萄酒业开始于 20 世纪 60 年代中期，这得益于加州大学的研究。随后，在 1976 年——就在科里森来到纳帕之后——加州葡萄酒在与法国葡萄酒评论家的盲品中击败了法国葡萄酒，这让以法国为主的葡萄酒界大为震惊。随着新葡萄酒和新酿酒方法的出现，纳帕谷成为了葡萄酒生产的热点。与传统的欧洲葡萄园不同，美国酿酒师全面采用了冷发酵等技术：通过将葡萄放入双层壁的不锈钢桶中，酿酒师可以在其中通入冷却剂来控制发酵，从而酿造出更新鲜、更爽脆的美国白葡萄酒。

In the years following Prohibition, the wine industry in the Napa Valley consisted of a few sleepy vineyards and a lot of sweet wine. The modern wine industry as we know it began to emerge in the mid-1960s, supported by research done at the University of California. Then, in 1976—right after Corison showed up in Napa—the wine world, dominated by the French, was stunned when California’s wines bested their French counterparts in a blind tasting with French wine critics. Napa Valley became a hotbed of activity with the emergence of new wines and new ways of making wine. Unlike the traditional European vineyards, American winemakers fully embraced technology like cold fermentation: by placing the grapes in a stainless steel vat with double walls, the winemakers were able to pass a coolant through them to control the fermentation, leading to fresher and crisper American white wines.

科里森成长于这些新技术兴起的时代。她和加州大学戴维斯分校的同学们最初都是通过技术培训的视角来酿酒的，对那些老一辈的种植者缺乏科学知识感到不屑。如今，四十年过去了，科里森对酿酒有了不同的看法。“老一辈人有很多智慧。我们自以为是，但知道得越多，就越觉得无知。”

Corison came of age when these types of new technologies were emerging. She and her fellow UC Davis graduates initially approached winemaking through the lens of their technical training, holding the older growers in disdain for their lack of scientific knowledge. Now, four decades later, Corison sees things differently. “There was a lot of wisdom from the old-timers. We were full of ourselves, but the more you know the less you know.”

到20世纪80年代末，科里森已经为著名酒庄Chappellet酿酒近十年。位于纳帕谷山上的Chappellet葡萄园经历了几季的干旱，因此科里森和她的团队从Rutherford Bench山下采购了一些额外的葡萄。这片“台地”由排水良好的冲积土壤构成，与山上的岩石地形不同。最重要的是，这片台地砾质壤土——由大致等量的沙子、粉砂和粘土组成——因此具有良好的保水能力和排水性。壤土中的葡萄藤在春夏两季能够获得生长所需的水分。砾石使土壤排水良好，因此当雨水停止时，葡萄藤会停止生长，专注于成熟。

By the late 1980s, Corison had been making wine for the famous label Chappellet for close to a decade. The vineyards of Chappellet, up in the hills of Napa Valley, had gone through a few seasons of drought, so Corison and her team sourced some additional grapes from down on the Rutherford Bench. This “bench” is made up of well-drained alluvial soils, unlike the rocky terrain up in the hills. Most important, the bench is gravelly loam—composed of roughly equal parts of sand, silt, and clay—so it has great water-holding capacity but excellent drainage. Vines in loam soil get the water they need to grow in the spring and summer. Gravel makes the soil well-drained so when the rains stop coming, the vines stop growing and focus on ripening.

科里森解释说：“如果赤霞珠在应该成熟的时期生长，它就会保留青涩的风味。”赤霞珠的成熟度以红色、蓝色、紫色和黑色水果风味的演变以及青涩气息的消失为标志。“然而，如果葡萄藤停止生长，忙于成熟，就有机会让葡萄完全成熟，而不会使糖分过高。”

“If Cabernet is growing when it ought to be ripening its fruit, it maintains green flavors,” Corison explained. Ripeness in Cabernet Sauvignon is marked by the evolution of red, blue, purple, and black fruit flavors and the disappearance of green notes. “If the vine stops growing and gets busy ripening, however, there is a chance to get grapes fully ripe without the sugars getting too high.”

当科里森和她的团队开始从这些冲积壤土中寻找葡萄时，她突然顿悟，知道自己想要酿造什么样的葡萄酒。“我内心深处有一种酒，需要释放出来，”科里森告诉我。“我只能这样形容它。它既强劲有力，又优雅优雅。无论你做什么，赤霞珠都会很强劲，但对我来说，优雅与强劲的交汇更令人着迷。当我们从山谷深处寻找葡萄时，我了解到，这种需要释放的酒生长在卢瑟福台地。”

When Corison and her crew began sourcing grapes from these alluvial loam soils, she had a revelation about the kind of wine she wanted to make. “There was a wine inside me that needed to get out,” Corison told me. “That’s the only way I can describe it. It was both powerful and elegant. Cabernet is going to be powerful no matter what you do, but it’s way more interesting to me at the intersection of elegance. When we sourced grapes from down in the valley, I learned that this wine that needed to get out grows on the Rutherford Bench.”

从1987年开始，科里森怀揣着这一愿景，开始酿造自己的葡萄酒。她找到了产能过剩的酒庄，并利用他们的设备酿造纳帕谷赤霞珠。1995年，她和丈夫买下了一块从卢瑟福延伸到圣赫勒拿的小块土地。之前所有人都拒绝了这块地，因为他们认为需要重新种植葡萄藤，并拆除上面的旧地皮。科里森和丈夫继续前进，把这块废弃的土地改造成了谷仓。用来安置他们的设施。他们没有把老藤重新移植到圣乔治砧木上。相反，他们珍惜它们。

Starting in 1987, Corison embraced this vision and began making her own wines. She found wineries with excess capacity and used their facilities to create her Napa Valley Cabernet. In 1995, she and her husband bought a small plot of land that runs from Rutherford to St. Helena. Everyone else had turned down the land because they assumed that the vines would need to be replanted and the old property on it torn down. Corison and her husband forged ahead, turning the derelict property into a barn to house their facility. And they did not replant the old vines on St. George rootstock. Instead, they celebrated them.

这些葡萄藤真是聪明——它们又老又聪明。我认为这和根系的深度有关。当所有年轻的葡萄园都饱受酷暑之苦时，它们却能优雅而有型地度过。它们知道该怎么做。

“Those vines are just wise—they are old and wise. I think it has to do with root depth. They come through heat spells with grace and style when all the younger vineyards are really hurting. They know what to do.”

当时，纳帕谷的风尚盛行大胆奔放。加州的新世界酿酒师倾向于延长葡萄在葡萄藤上的陈年时间，以保持浓郁的香气和口感。这些葡萄酒的酒精度开始远超14%。一些评论家称赞它们“醇厚”，而另一些人则嘲讽地称之为“水果炸弹”。20世纪80年代末90年代初，纳帕谷越来越不像一个农业社区，而越来越像富人和名人的游乐场。葡萄酒的醇厚反映了这些饮酒者的奢华品味。

During this time, the fashion in Napa Valley was big and bold. New World winemakers in California tended to let the fruit sit longer on the vine for powerful aromas and flavors. The alcohol levels of these wines began to stretch well above 14 percent. Some critics lauded them as “lush,” while others derisively referred to them as “fruit bombs.” In the late 1980s and early 90’s Napa Valley looked less and less like an agricultural community and more and more like a playground for the rich and famous. The lushness of the wines reflected the grandiosity of these drinkers.

这些更为醇厚的葡萄酒的“数据”在科学上都是正确的。这些葡萄酒在技术上都经过验证，结构完整。酿酒师能够清晰地描述他们“成熟”葡萄酒的特性：葡萄的糖分、酸度和pH值都在合适的范围内。

The “numbers” of these more robust wines were all scientifically correct. The wines were all technically sound, with structural integrity. The winemakers could clearly state the properties of their “ripe” wines: the sugar, acid, and pH levels of the grapes all measured in an appropriate range.

然而，成熟度的各个方面却讲述了一个更加微妙的故事。“每年的成熟度都不一样，”科里森解释说。“如果你不在葡萄园里亲眼目睹，你真的无法真正了解。成熟度只是其中的一部分。葡萄藤在成熟季节结束时会感到疲惫，过一段时间就会放弃。当它们放弃的时候，真正的成熟就结束了。挑战就在于：让所有因素在恰当的时间汇聚在一起。一个伟大的年份是所有这些因素都恰到好处地汇聚在一起。这既是生物学和化学的结合，也是“炼金术。从技术层面来说，还有很多东西我们不明白。”

The aspects of ripeness, however, tell a much more nuanced story. “Ripeness happens at different numbers every year,” Corison explained. “If you are not out in the vineyard, seeing it, you don’t really know. Numbers are just a piece of it. The vines get tired by the end of the ripening season and can give up after a while. And when they give up, true ripening ends. That is the challenge: to make all the components converge at just the right time. A great vintage is when all those factors converge right where you want them. It’s biology and chemistry, but also alchemy. There is so much we don’t understand on a technical level.”

关心

Care

科里森用来描述她的葡萄酒和酿酒工艺的每一个字眼，都传达着她与土地的深厚情谊。这些葡萄藤并非用科学的属性来衡量：例如pH值、盐度和石灰含量等土壤适宜性指标。相反，她用“古老而睿智”来形容它们，并赋予它们“优雅而别致”的气质。

Every single word Corison uses to articulate her wine and her winemaking conveys her relationship to the land. These vines are not measured in scientific properties: the pH, salinity, and lime content of their soil suitability, for example. Instead, she describes them as “old and wise,” with “grace and style.”

我们拥有充足的热量和阳光，即​​使在像2011年这样的寒冷季节，也能保证葡萄的成熟。由于寒冷的夜晚和雾气的笼罩，我们拥有美妙的天然酸度。而这片土地上的单宁口感如天鹅绒般柔滑。如果你测量单宁的含量，你会得到一个非常大的数字。但单宁并非单一的分子；它们是一类分子，其性质从粗糙涩到柔软丝滑，变化多样。这正是我喜欢基奇兰水果的原因：它们有水果的香味，但单宁却如此甜美。口感极佳。

“We have all the heat and sunshine we need to get the grapes right—even in a cold season like 2011—but because of the cold nights and the fog coming in, we have beautiful natural acidity too. And the tannins in [this] corner of the world come in feeling like velvet. If you were to measure the tannins, you’d get a very big number. But tannins are not one molecule; they’re a class of molecules that can range from harsh and astringent to soft and velvety and beautiful. And that is what I love about benchland fruit: there are fruit flavors, but the tannins are so luscious. They feel good.”

科里森永远无法从电子表格或摩天大楼87层的办公室里获得这种视角。她知道单宁如天鹅绒般柔滑，因为她已经品尝了近四十年。最终，她之所以能够拥有这种审美判断，是因为她所处的特定环境。简而言之，凯茜·科里森对此非常在意：“我在欧洲葡萄酒上积累了经验。我品尝了足够多的产自那片土地的老赤霞珠，深谙其优雅。对我来说，酿造一款能够长久陈年，并在瓶中展现精彩韵味的葡萄酒，是一种道德责任。”

Corison could never gain this type of perspective from a spreadsheet or an office on the 87th floor of a skyscraper. She knows the tannins feel like velvet because she has been tasting them for close to forty years. Ultimately, she can hold this aesthetic judgment because of how specifically she is situated in her context. To put it simply, Cathy Corison gives a damn: “I cut my teeth on European wines. And I tasted enough of the old Cabernets from that neck of the woods to know elegance. It’s a moral imperative for me to make a wine that will be long-lived and do interesting things in the bottle.”

当你拥有洞察力，当你真正在乎时，你就能直觉地感知什么是重要的，什么是微不足道的。你能看到事物之间的联系，并了解哪些数据、输入和知识才是重要的。关怀是连接所有这些的纽带。

When you have a perspective—when you actually give a damn—you intuitively sense what’s important and what’s trivial. You can see what connects with what, and you know the data, input, and knowledge that matter. Caring is the connective tissue that makes all these things possible.

相反，缺乏关怀往往是我在咨询过程中遇到的许多商业和组织挑战的根源。随着时间的推移，随着管理日益专业化，你能在高管层感受到一种虚无主义或意义的丧失。这种虚无主义在大型企业文化中最为明显，在这种文化中，管理本身被视为一种职业，与公司实际生产或经营的产品没有紧密的联系。如果工作中的满足感来自于管理——重组、优化运营、招聘新员工和制定战略——而不是来自于创造有意义的东西，会发生什么？当你生产的是美容产品、软饮料、快餐还是乐器时，当你感觉无关紧要时，你会作何感想？

Conversely, a lack of care is often at the root of many of the business and organizational challenges I encounter in my consulting. Over time, as management has become increasingly professionalized, you can sense a kind of nihilism or loss of meaning in the executive layers. This nihilism is strongest in large corporate cultures where management is seen as a profession in and of itself, with no strong connection to what the company actually makes or does. What happens when satisfaction in work comes from managing—reorganizing, optimizing the operation, hiring new people, and making strategies—and not from producing something meaningful? How do you feel when it doesn’t really matter whether you make beauty products, soft drinks, fast food, or musical instruments?

没有关怀，一切都是“正确的”，没有什么是“真实的”。马丁·海德格尔声称，关怀——或者他所谓的“ Sorge”（关怀）——正是我们之所以为人的原因。他所说的“关怀”并非指与事物或人之间明确的情感联系，而是指某件事物对你来说重要，对你来说具有意义。正是这种关怀使我们能够以非常复杂的方式与事物互动，也正是这种关怀使我们能够发现与世界互动的新方式。

Without care, everything is “correct” and nothing is “true.” Martin Heidegger claimed that care—or what he called Sorge—is the very thing that makes us human. He didn’t mean “care” as an explicit emotional connection with things or people, but rather in the sense that something matters to you, is meaningful to you. It is this care that enables us to interact with stuff in very complex ways, and it is also this care that enables us to see new ways of interacting with the world.

如果你从事美容行业，如果你不关心美容产品的含义，你就无法理解关于美容理念的文化见解。如果你从事汽车行业，你必须关心汽车和交通——否则，人类的驾驶现象对你来说毫无意义。如果不用心，你就无法看到更宏观的意义和洞察力，而只会看到离散的数据点——以赛亚·伯林所说的“无数只蝴蝶”。

If you are in the beauty business, you simply can’t make sense of cultural insights regarding beauty ideals if you don’t care about the meaning of beauty products. If you are in the car industry, you have to care about cars and transportation—otherwise, the human phenomenon of driving will not make sense to you. Without care, you stop seeing the bigger picture of meaning and insight and you only see discrete data points—what Isaiah Berlin referred to as “so many individual butterflies.”

正是用心，让凯茜·科里森聆听到葡萄酒的召唤，它正试图“逃离”她。也正是用心，让她有勇气年复一年地坚持酿造。如今，用心已成时尚，而十年前，它却并非如此。用心如同指引她前进方向的北极星，让她在葡萄酒和烹饪潮流的更迭中，不被分心或被耽搁。

Care is what allowed Cathy Corison to hear the call of the wine trying to “get out” of her. And care is what gives her the courage to continue to make it, year after year after year. Today it is in fashion. Ten years ago, it was not. Care provides her with a North Star so she doesn’t get distracted or waylaid throughout these cycles of wine and culinary fashion.

以葡萄酒咨询集团Enologix的创始人Leo McCloskey为例。Cathy Corison的葡萄酒从来都不是只关注数字，而McCloskey则围绕着“酿酒就是数字”这一理念，构建了一整套商业模式。凭借全球最大的葡萄酒数据库，他每年品尝数百种葡萄酒，然后将它们分解成赋予其独特色泽、风味和香气的各个化合物。

Consider Leo McCloskey, founder of a wine consulting group called Enologix. Whereas Cathy Corison’s wine is never just about the numbers, McCloskey has developed an entire business model around the belief that winemaking is all about numbers. With the world’s largest wine database, he tastes hundreds of wines a year and then breaks all of them down into the individual compounds that give them their unique color, flavor, and fragrance.

他如何处理这些信息？首先，他会为客户进行计算机测试，帮助确定一个季节最重要的时刻：何时采摘葡萄。这会对葡萄酒进行逆向工程，将其分解成各个组成部分，并将每个元素雾化。这些结果会与他庞大的数据库进行比较——这些数据库会结合采集的葡萄园状况数据（例如降雨量和水位）以及酿酒过程细节（例如使用的酒桶类型和发酵时长）进行计算。所有这些模型都为酿酒师提供了一种创造虚拟葡萄酒版本的方法：通过不同的因素来调整特定元素，类似于创建梦幻橄榄球联赛。当葡萄酒准备装瓶时，Enologix 还有最后一项功能：他们的计算可以相当准确地预测该葡萄酒在《葡萄酒观察家》杂志臭名昭著的 100 分制上的得分。

What does he do with all this information? He begins by running computer tests for his clients to help determine the most important moment of the season: when to pick the grapes. This reverse-engineers the wines, stripping them down to their component parts and atomizing each and every element. These results get compared with his vast database—calculated along with captured data about conditions in the vineyard, such as the rainfall and water levels and winemaking process details like the types of barrels used and the length of fermentation. All of these models give winemakers a way to create virtual versions of their wine: playing with different factors to tweak particular elements, akin to creating a Fantasy Football League. When the wine is ready to go in the bottle, Enologix has one final offering: their calculations can predict with a fair amount of accuracy how the wine will score on the infamous 100-point scale in Wine Spectator.

这是一种“点球成金”的酿酒方法，在一个坚守手工酿酒文化的文化中，这是一种大胆的举动。麦克洛斯基没有透露客户的名字，但他主要服务于那些试图保持勃艮第和阿尔萨斯等旧世界文化中著名的传统酿酒方法的小型葡萄园。这些客户以及业内一些消息人士认为，麦克洛斯基可以为酿酒师提供一些有价值的东西。但任何与凯茜·科里森相处过的人都知道，这种价值不过是海市蜃楼。麦克洛斯基的“黑匣子”里没有任何东西能够持久。通过采取完全客观的数据处理方式——将一瓶葡萄酒中的化合物视为与其更大背景分离的原子化元素——麦克洛斯基完全有可能在今天酿造出优质葡萄酒。但他永远无法酿造出经久不衰的佳酿。这是因为在选择背后缺乏诚信，缺乏审美——没有人真正关心。这只是技术上的精准，却没有灵魂。

It’s a Moneyball approach to winemaking, an audacious move in a culture that holds firmly to its identity as an artisanal craft. McCloskey does not reveal the names of his clients, but he primarily serves the smaller vineyards attempting to stay close to the traditional methods of winemaking made famous in Old World cultures like Burgundy and Alsace. These clients, and several sources in the industry, believe that McCloskey has something valuable to offer winemakers. But anyone who spends time with Cathy Corison knows that this value is a mirage. Nothing in McCloskey’s “black box” has any lasting point of view. By taking an entirely objective approach to the data—and treating the compounds in a bottle of wine as atomized elements discrete from their greater context—McCloskey has every chance of helping to make good wine today. But he will never come close to making great wine that endures. This is because there is no integrity, no aesthetic—there is no person who cares—behind the choices. It is technical precision with no soul.

如果凯茜·科里森尝试使用 Enologix 系统中的数据处理算法来玩弄她的酒，她或许可以优化某一年份的葡萄酒，从而获得更高的评分。但这将以更引人入胜、更令人印象深刻的轨迹为代价。“我喜欢葡萄酒的一点是，它讲述着时间和地点，并随着时间和地点的流逝而不断前进。这些葡萄酒至今仍在诉说着过去发生的事情，”科里森告诉我。“我感到自己有道义上的责任，要酿造出让泥土说话的葡萄酒。”

If Cathy Corison tried to game her bottles using a data-crunching algorithm in the Enologix system, she might optimize a single year for a better wine score. But it would be at the cost of a much more compelling—and impressive—trajectory. “One of the things I love about wine is that it speaks of time and place, and marches forward speaking of time and place. These wines are still talking about what was happening,” Corison told me. “I feel a moral obligation to make wines that let the dirt speak.”

科里森酿造葡萄酒已有三十年，她的年份多年来始终保持着惊人的一致性。她不添加酸、单宁、酶或任何橡木味。她渴望酿造的葡萄酒完全源于葡萄本身。当你品尝凯茜·科里森酿造的葡萄酒时，你​​会感受到她所关注的一切：一种算法永远无法捕捉到的深刻数据。机器学习永远无法理解她是如何在经历了短暂的流行和落伍之后依然屹立不倒的。即使输入所有可能的感知数据，也无法理解她坚持不懈的意义。计算机根本不在乎；它们永远不会理解，关心才是关键所在。

By making such wines for thirty years, Corison’s vintages have remained remarkably consistent over the years. She doesn’t add acid, tannins, enzymes, or any of the oak flavors. The wine that was dying to get out of her was based entirely on the grapes themselves. When you drink Cathy Corison’s wine, you are experiencing everything she cares about: a profundity of data that can never be captured in an algorithm. Machine learning can never understand how she prevailed despite falling in and then out of style. And entering all the sense data possible wouldn’t get at the meaning of her perseverance. Computers simply do not give a damn; they will never understand that caring is the whole point.

有意义的差异

Meaningful Differences

马丁·海德格尔、阿尔伯特·博格曼和休伯特·德雷福斯等伟大的哲学家认为，希恩、维斯塔格、沃斯和科里森所展现的精湛技艺，是一种寻找视角的导航技巧。这种导航的核心是一种他们称之为“有意义的差异”的现象。

Great philosophers like Martin Heidegger, Albert Borgmann, and Hubert Dreyfus argue that the kind of skill exhibited in the mastery displayed by Heen, Vestager, Voss, and Corison is the navigational skill of finding a perspective. At the heart of this navigation is a phenomenon they call meaningful differences.

为了帮助理解这个概念，首先试着想象一个没有有意义差异的世界。这就是我所描述的迷失方向的企业文化中的虚无主义世界。当我们体验到这个世界缺乏有意义的差异时，一切事物和每个人都只不过是需要优化的资源。资源的可替代性如此之强，以至于它们可以用于任何目的。凯茜·科里森的葡萄可以和玛格丽特·维斯塔格的意大利工厂生产的钢铁互换。这种理解的延伸是，人类本身就是资源，因此有了“人力资源”一词。

To help understand this concept, first try to imagine a world without meaningful differences. This is the world of nihilism I described in corporate cultures that have lost their way. When we experience the world as lacking in meaningful differences, everything and everyone is merely a resource to be optimized. Resources are so fungible, they can be used to any end. Cathy Corison’s grapes can be interchanged with steel from Margrethe Vestager’s Italian factory. The extension of this understanding is that humans themselves are resources, hence the term human resources.

马丁·海德格尔在 1954 年发表的或许是他最好的文章《关于技术的问题》中描述了这种现代意识形态，即我们的世界没有了有意义的差异。他将技术视为我们现代的“存在”方式，是我们观察世界的视角。但他使用的“技术”一词与设备或其他技术发明几乎没有关系。技术——或者用他的话说，技术性——是贯穿我们整个存在的逻辑。罗马人或前现代社会认为万物皆有上帝的作为；启蒙思想家认为我们人类是宇宙的主宰者，而海德格尔则认为，如今技术已成为我们存在的中心。它不仅取代了神，也取代了我们自己。

In perhaps his best essay, “The Question Concerning Technology,” from 1954, Martin Heidegger describes this modern ideology, our world without meaningful differences. He cites technology as our modern way of “Being,” our lens on the world. But his use of the word technology has very little to do with devices or other technical inventions. Technology—or technicity, as he calls it—is the logic that pervades our entire existence. Whereas Romans, or pre-modern societies, saw God’s work in everything; and the Enlightenment thinkers felt that we humans were rulers of the universe, Heidegger argues that technology, today, is now at the center of our being. Not only has it replaced the gods, it has also replaced us.

在海德格尔的世界里，技术的精神或逻辑是“优化”：不懈地追求从我们周围的物质——包括树木、水，甚至人——中榨取每一点价值。两百年前，木匠会看着一块木头，并根据这块木头的纹理和质感，对其进行加工，打造出尽可能精妙的作品——比如一个门把手。然而，今天，我们通过将所有木材制成木浆，再将其重新组装成标准化、非唯一且具有完美柔韧性的“木材”，来优化木材。在海德格尔看来，这正是当今世界秩序的无形结构：我们标准化、优化，并使事物变得可用且灵活。

In Heidegger’s world, the spirit or logic of technology is “optimization”: the relentless pursuit of squeezing every bit of value out of physical matter around us—including trees, water, and even people. Two hundred years ago, a carpenter would look at a piece of wood and work with it to make the finest creation possible—a door handle, say—given the grain and texture of that particular piece of wood. Today, however, we optimize wood by making all wood into wood pulp and reassembling it again as standardized, non-unique, and perfectly flexible “wood.” In Heidegger’s mind, this is the invisible structure that is ordering the reality of our world today: we standardize, optimize, and make things available and flexible.

在硅谷的心态下，我们日常生活的各个方面都体验着海德格尔所描述的那种不适。一切都唾手可得；一切都与其他一切等同：每一天、每一小时、每一秒都与其他的每一天、每一小时、每一秒都一样。我们和所有其他在硅谷四处运输的齿轮和小部件没什么不同。交通系统。我们的学校系统旨在培养灵活的会计师，这些会计师可以互换，随时可用并进行优化。公司和政府可以轻松地吸纳新人或解雇他们，因为每个人都在相同的机构接受相同的方法培训。技术使我们的存在如此灵活，但也使我们的存在如此易于操纵和处置。这就是进步。真的吗？

In a Silicon Valley state of mind, we experience the malaise that Heidegger characterizes across all aspects of our daily lives. Everything is available; everything is equivalent to everything else: every day, hour, and second are the same as every other day, hour, and second. We are no different from all the other cogs and widgets being shipped here and there in the transportation system. Our school system is built to create flexible accountants that are interchangeable and available for use and optimization. Companies and governments can take in new people or throw them out again with great ease because everyone is trained in the same methods by the same institutions. Technology is what makes our existence so flexible, but it is also what makes it so easy to manipulate and then to dispose of. This is progress. Or is it?

像希恩、维斯塔格、沃斯和科里森这样的大师在这个科技时代扮演着非常特殊的角色。他们运用实践智慧——运用必然依赖于具体情境的知识和经验融入自身世界——致力于驱散现代弊病。他们并非全球商品体系中可替代的资源。相反，他们响应着自身世界的召唤。

Masters like Heen, Vestager, Voss, and Corison have a very special role to play in this age of technology. Their acts of phronesis—engaging in their worlds with a knowledge and experience that is necessarily context-dependent—work to dispel the modern malaise. They are not fungible resources in the global system of goods. Instead, they respond to the call of their worlds.

加州大学伯克利分校哲学教授休伯特·德雷福斯（Hubert Dreyfus）进一步向我解释了这类大师的独特作用：“当我们最终理解了大师的精髓以及这个世界的召唤时，我们就会明白，生命意义的源泉并非像笛卡尔模型所暗示的那样，在我们自身——而是存在于这个世界之中。当人们在世间做着一件技艺精湛的事情时，他们便会迷失自我。大师与世界之间的界限消失了。了解大师们的所作所为，以及我们自身的所作所为，我们都能激发出自身最美好的一面。”

Hubert Dreyfus, professor of philosophy at the University of California, Berkeley, further explained the unique role of these kinds of masters to me: “When we finally understand mastery and this calling of the world, then we understand that the source of meaning in our lives isn’t in us, as the Cartesian model suggests—it is in being in the world. When people are doing a skillful thing in the world, they lose themselves. The distinction between the master and the world disappears. Seeing what masters can do, and what we can do, we can all bring out what is best in ourselves.”

这些大师们用他们的技艺，让我们得以一窥超越自我的意义。但这种旅程需要勇气。“在习得任何技能的过程中，冒险都至关重要，”德雷福斯告诉我，“因为你必须抛开规则，抛开惯常做法，去探索你对世界的体验。我们感兴趣的风险与纯粹的虚张声势之间的区别在于，承担这些风险是否是为了一个人所承诺的事情、一个人对自己的定义，以及是什么让他们的生活发生了有意义的变化。这种风险是成为任何领域大师的必要步骤。

With their craft, these masters give us a glimpse of what it is to transcend ourselves. But this type of journey takes courage. “Risk is absolutely important in acquiring any skills,” Dreyfus told me, “because you have to leave the rules behind and leave behind what one generally does and stretch out into your own experience of the world. What distinguishes between risks we’re interested in and mere bravado is whether the risks are taken in the interest of what one is committed to, what one has defined themselves in terms of, and what makes the meaningful differences in their life. That kind of a risk is a necessary step in becoming a master at anything.”

换句话说，除非你真的在意，否则你永远不会看到有意义的差异。你呢？

In other words, you will never see meaningful differences unless you actually give a damn. Do you?

第八章

Chapter Eight

人是为了什么？

What Are People For?

一切美好的事物......都来自恩典，恩典来自艺术，而艺术来之不易。

All good things… come by grace and grace comes by art and art does not come easy.

——诺曼·麦克莱恩，《大河恋》

—Norman Maclean, A River Runs Through It

我会试着列清单。列出大街上所有店铺和商家以及它们的主人，列出家族姓氏、墓地墓碑上的名字以及墓碑下的所有铭文……我们对这类任务的准确性抱有的希望是疯狂的，令人心碎的。而且没有一张清单能容纳我想要的一切，因为我想要的是每一件事，每一层言语和思想，每一道光线照射在树皮或墙壁上，每一种气味、每一种坑洼、每一种痛苦、每一种裂缝、每一种妄想，都静止不动，紧紧相连——光芒四射，永恒不灭。

I would try to make lists. A list of all the stores and businesses going up and down the main street and who owned them, a list of family names, names on the tombstones in the cemetery and any inscriptions underneath.… The hope of accuracy we bring to such tasks is crazy, heartbreaking. And no list could ever hold what I wanted, for what I wanted was every last thing, every layer of speech and thought, stroke of light on bark or walls, every smell, pothole, pain, crack, delusion, held still and held together—radiant, everlasting.

——爱丽丝·门罗，《女孩和女人的生活》

—Alice Munro, Lives of Girls and Women

护理的未来

The Future of Caring

一家全球领先的医疗设备和系统供应商试图了解老年人长期护理的未来，特别是考虑到以下国家人口老龄化：在日本、法国、加拿大和美国等国家，我们与他们合作开展了一项意义建构研究，对这四个国家33个不同机构的450多人进行了访谈和观察。研究涵盖了养老院、失智症护理机构、日托中心和辅助生活机构，旨在了解长期护理的发展方向以及患者和护理人员的体验如何变化。

A leading global provider of health care equipment and systems was trying to understand the future of long-term care for the elderly, especially given the aging populations in countries as varied as Japan, France, Canada, and the United States. We partnered with them for a sensemaking study that involved interviews and observations with more than 450 people across thirty-three different institutions in these four countries. The study included retirement homes, dementia homes, day care, and assisted living, and the goal was to form a perspective on where long-term care was headed and how the patient and caregiver experience was changing.

直到最近，长期护理模式仍在追随许多其他快速增长行业的轨迹。经济压力和日益加重的老年人负担过去和现在都在催生对效率的强烈需求。护理人员及其机构认为有必要更加关注那些易于衡量且投资回报率明显的护理环节，包括较高的住户与护理人员比例、较低的跌倒次数以及较低的压疮发生率。通过这种方式，护理人员和机构开始主要从住户的身体需求（洗澡、上厕所、上下床）来看待他们，并将护理标准化，以尽可能提高效率。正如研究中的一位护理人员所说：“我不想说我们是机器人，但我们确实有工作要做……根本没有时间去了解他们。你不了解他们的过去。”

Until recently, the model for long-term care was following the curve of so many other rapidly growing industries. Financial pressures and the increasing elderly burden were—and still are—creating a strong demand for efficiency. Caregivers and their institutions felt a need to put more focus on the parts of the care that were easily measured and that provided an obvious return on investment—including a high resident-to-caregiver ratio, a low number of falls, and low occurrence of pressure ulcers. In this way, caregivers and institutions started to view the residents primarily through their bodily needs—bathing, toileting, moving in and out of bed—and they standardized their care to be as efficient as possible. As one caregiver in the study put it, “I don’t want to say we are robots, but we do have a job to do… there simply isn’t time getting to know them. You don’t know their history.”

长期护理领域对效率的追求，与我们熟知的企业化农业体系及其对单一种植的依赖，或教育体系及其对指标、问责制和标准化考试的追求轨迹如出一辙。这正是现代管理科学的巅峰：一个高度优化的系统，通过量化账户来衡量患者。

This drive for efficiency in long-term care resembles the trajectory we know so well from the corporate farming system and its reliance on monoculture, or the education system and its drive for metrics, accountability, and standardized testing. This is the culmination of our modern era of management science: a highly optimized system that measures patients by quantitative accounts.

但研究中出现的一种模式为长期护理提供了新的视角。这一发展对我们理解以测量和投资回报形式呈现的抽象知识的态度大有裨益。最终，它让我们更清晰地理解了人的意义。

But a pattern emerged in the study that provides a new vision for long-term care. It is a development that has much to teach us about our attitudes toward abstracted knowledge in the form of measurements and returns on investment. Ultimately, it offers us a clearer understanding of what people are for.

兰德尔和下午3 点的解决方案

Randall and the 3PM Solution

加州一家养老院正在换班，87岁的老人“兰德尔”开始变得焦躁不安。对于患有痴呆症的兰德尔来说，这早已习以为常。每天下午3点换班，人来人往，新面孔涌现，人来人往，换班的节奏也随之而来。这触动了兰德尔内心深处的某种情绪，他经常会做出一些行为，与自己的幻觉进行愤怒的对话。

It is the changing of the shift at an assisted living facility in California, and “Randall,” an 87-year-old resident, is beginning to grow agitated. This is a regular pattern with Randall, who suffers from dementia. The shift change—which occurs at 3 PM every day—is filled with the commotion of moving bodies, new faces, the whirl of change. It triggers something from deep inside Randall and he often starts acting out, engaging in angry conversations with his own hallucinations.

他的一位护工“芭芭拉”把兰德尔领进餐厅，然后缓慢而有条不紊地把其他居民清空。兰德尔开始在房间里走来走去，桌子和椅子都摇来晃去。他抓住芭芭拉的胳膊，紧紧地攥了好几秒钟。芭芭拉漫不经心地把胳膊挪开，“亲爱的，我不会那样弯。”然后她试图分散他的注意力：“兰德尔，看看从窗户透进来的光线。看看外面多亮啊。”与此同时，她和其他居民一起跳起了微妙的舞蹈。她轻拍一些在餐桌旁睡着的人，叫醒他们，并在他们起身离开房间时扶着他们。她轻柔地绕过坐在轮椅和助行器上的居民，把他们一个个推到走廊里，这样兰德尔就可以……孤立。当房间里除了兰德尔之外空无一人时，她关上门，留下来观察他，透过玻璃观察，确保他的安全。

“Barbara,” one of his caregivers, ushers Randall into the dining room and slowly, methodically, clears the rest of the residents out of the space. Randall starts to wander through the room, tipping tables and moving chairs. He grabs Barbara’s arm and grips it with intensity for several seconds. She moves her arm away with a nonchalant comment, “I don’t bend that way, dear.” And then she tries to distract him: “Look at the light coming in the windows, Randall. Look at how bright it is out there.” All the while she performs a subtle dance with the other residents. She gives some of them a tap, waking them up if they have fallen asleep at the table, offering them support while they get out of chairs and get out of the room. She glides seamlessly around residents in wheelchairs and walkers, pushing them one by one into the hallway so Randall can be isolated. When the room is completely empty except for Randall, she shuts the doors and stays to observe him, making certain he is safe by watching through the glass.

“我们把他安排在餐厅里，这样他就能释放自己的能量，”她告诉研究人员。“这个空间对他来说更大，而且当他感到烦躁时，光线也更好。当其他居民看到兰德尔在那里时，他们就知道他们不想待在那里了。”

“We put him in the dining room so he can get his energy out,” she told researchers in the study. “This space has more room for him and better light when he is feeling agitated. When the other residents see Randall in there, they know they don’t want to be a part of it.”

这种痛苦对于患有痴呆症的居民来说是常见的，并且会改变长期护理领域的格局。经济合作与发展组织 (OECD) 预测，2015 年至 2035 年间，美国的痴呆症发病率将增加 55.6%。他们估计加拿大会增加 63%，日本会增加 74%。一些痴呆症患者特有的焦躁不安会耗费所有相关人员的时间，以至于整个高效护理模式正在被颠覆。机构需要关注如何防止焦躁情绪蔓延，以及如何最大限度地减少护理任务内外的摩擦。像压疮发生率这样容易量化的指标与像兰德尔这样的居民所需的护理无关。更重要的是他的护理人员每天实施的个性化策略——巧妙的技巧。

This type of distress is typical for residents with dementia, and it is a game changer in the world of long-term care. The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) projects that between 2015 and 2035, dementia in the United States will increase by 55.6 percent. In Canada, they estimate an increase of 63 percent, and in Japan an increase of 74 percent. The agitation that typifies some dementia patients is so time-consuming for everyone involved that the entire model of efficient care is being turned upside down. Facilities need to focus on how to keep the mood of agitation from spreading and on how to minimize friction, both inside and outside of care tasks. Easily quantified measurements like occurrence of pressure ulcers have no bearing on the care a resident like Randall needs. What matters much more are the personalized strategies—artful hacks—that his caregivers perform every day.

这种照护需要照护团队更好地了解兰德尔，包括他过去的生活以及他在机构的体验。例如，芭芭拉发现他曾担任数十年的教师。他对下午3点换班的反应并非偶然。他的肌肉记忆会根据学校的教学时间做出反应——下午3点的活力释放，走廊里孩子们的欢声笑语，以及学校里的活动。从教室回家。当机构换班时，兰德尔感到困惑和沮丧，因为他不认识周围的环境。他感觉到有什么事情正在发生，但不知道自己应该做什么。他的护理团队将他的行为与他在机构外的生活联系起来，将这些零散的信息拼凑在一起。芭芭拉叫兰德尔“约翰逊先生”（他的学生在课堂上叫他的名字）来让他平静下来。考虑到下午3点的混乱，她和其他工作人员开始用歌曲和故事分散兰德尔的注意力，同时新的护理人员签到。

This kind of care requires that the team of caregivers get to know Randall better, both his previous life and how he experiences being in the institution. For example, Barbara discovered that he was a schoolteacher for several decades. His reaction to the 3 PM shift change was not random. His muscle memory responded to the hours of the school day—the energy of the 3 PM release, with kids in the hallways and movement away from the classroom and toward home. When the shift change occurs at the facility, Randall feels confused and frustrated that he doesn’t recognize his surroundings. He senses that something is going on but doesn’t know what he is supposed to do. His caregiver team put these pieces together by placing his behavior in a context with his life outside the institution. Barbara calmed Randall down by addressing him as “Mr. Johnson,” the name his students used in class. In anticipation of the chaos of 3 PM, she and the rest of the staff began distracting him with songs and stories while the new caregivers signed in.

“我们已经把它归结为一种科学方法，”芭芭拉告诉研究人员。“有时候他只是需要换个环境，这样我们就知道什么时候该换人了。有时候，他对像耳语一样柔和的声音反应很好。但有时候，他需要你用和他一模一样的语气回应，就像他声音的回声一样。你得去感受他。”

“We’ve got it down to a kind of science,” Barbara told the researchers. “Sometimes he just needs a change so we know when to switch people. Sometimes he responds really well to a softer voice that is almost like a whisper. But sometimes he needs you to respond in exactly the same tone as his. Almost like an echo of his voice. You kind of have to feel him out.”

当所有巧妙的应对方法都无法让他平静下来时，兰德尔的团队制定了一套方案。他们温柔地把他带到餐厅，并短暂地将他隔离，让他“释放能量”。

And when none of the artful hacks manage to calm him, Randall’s team has devised a protocol. They guide him gently into the dining hall and isolate him briefly so he can “get his energy out.”

兰德尔的照护策略被写在白板上或打印的纸上，并在他的照护团队成员之间来回传递：“兰德尔是个木工。给他蒙特梭利积木。”以及“兰德尔是个辅导员。问问​​他的工作。”这类知识无法被整理成法典，因为它只与一个人的照护相关：兰德尔。如果他的机构试图将管理学应用于此——以“扩大”这些知识的规模——他们会发现很难应用。最好的照护是在特定的社会背景下了解每位患者，然后制定一系列最适合他们个人需求的策略。

Randall’s caregiving strategies are written up on whiteboards and on typed sheets of paper and passed back and forth among his caregiving team: “Randall was a woodworker. Offer him Montessori blocks,” and “Randall was a guidance counselor. Ask him about his work.” There is no way to codify this type of knowledge, because it is only relevant for the care of one person: Randall. If his institution attempted to apply management science to it—to “scale up” this knowledge—they would find it difficult to apply. The best care involves getting to know each patient within a social context and then devising a series of strategies that best suit their individual needs.

这种个性化护理看似复杂且成本高昂，但事实上，兰德尔所在的机构发现，这是应对兰德尔及其痴呆症最有效的方法。通过巧妙地结合各种技巧、提示和干扰，他们可以更快地为兰德尔洗澡、喂食并让他平静下来，这比他们匆忙地完成身体需求清单，而忽略兰德尔日益加剧的不适和特定诱因要快得多。而且，毋庸置疑，个性化护理更符合护理人员的愿景。当工作人员被鼓励去了解每位患者时，他们的倦怠和压力就会减少，目标感也会增强。

This personalized caregiving may seem like an elaborate and costly strategy, but, in fact, Randall’s facility has found that it is the most efficient way to deal with Randall and his dementia. With the right combination of hacks, cues, and distractions, they can get Randall bathed, fed, and calmed much faster than if they expediently checked off their list of bodily needs and ignored Randall’s growing discomfort and specific triggers. And, it goes without saying, personalized caregiving aligns more fully with the vision of the caregivers. There is less burnout and stress and a greater sense of purpose for the staff when they are encouraged to get to know each patient as a person.

看到这些例子，你可能会说，好吧，我们都想要好的护理，但维持这样的护理成本太高了。然而，我们发现，真正的开销来自于那些仅仅依靠管理科学和成文知识提供的护理。事实证明，对于痴呆症患者来说，高质量的个性化护理更经济实惠。成本效益直接源于其效率。根据我们所研究的每个国家的护理人员及其管理层的反馈，这种更加个性化的痴呆症患者护理可以节省时间。当机构内部的整体氛围更加平和、避免摩擦时，跌倒的患者和压疮患者都会减少。整个系统运行得更好。

You might look at these examples and say, well, sure, we all want good care, but it’s too expensive to maintain. What we are discovering, however, is that the real expense is care meted out only through management science and codified knowledge. As it turns out, good-quality personalized care is cheaper care when it comes to dementia. The cost-effectiveness is a direct result of its efficiency. According to caregivers and their management in every country we studied, this more personalized care of dementia patients saves time in the day. When the entire culture inside the facility is calmer and more peaceful—when friction is averted—fewer patients suffer from falls and there are fewer pressure ulcers. The entire system works better.

“重点正从任务转移到人身上，”一位参与研究的管理人员告诉我们。“如果你能与你照顾的人建立良好的关系，对他们来说会更好。他们可能会减少不良行为，生活质量更高，内心更平静。这让我们的工作更轻松、更快捷。”

“The focus is shifting more from the task to the person,” one administrator in the study told us. “If you can create relationships with the people you’re caring for, it’s going to be better for them. They’re probably going to have fewer behaviors, more quality of life and peace. This then makes our work easier and quicker.”

这种转变必然要求我们对时间和成本的假设进行根本性的改变。痴呆症护理中的这种“新效率”完全是本地化的、情境化的：它无法被抽象化和规模化。因为世界上没有另一个兰德尔，所以也没有标准化的解决方案能够解释兰德尔的行为。如今，护理人员依靠模拟的、“自制的”方式彼此分享​​针对住户的专业知识——技巧和窍门——来简化工作：例如在纸上或白板上做笔记，或者只是简单的对话。我们可以做更多的事情，让他们能够随时获得基于经验的、针对住户的专业知识，尤其是在住户容易感到恐惧或焦虑的护理环境中。新技术令人兴奋的潜力不在于它能加快标准化流程，而在于它能够帮助支持个性化护理。换句话说，护理人员需要支持，让他们确切地知道应该针对每位住户按下哪些“按钮”，并相应地调整护理方案——而不是支持他们越来越快地按下相同的按钮。

Such a shift necessitates a fundamental change in our assumptions about time and cost. This “new efficiency” in dementia care is entirely local and contextualized: it cannot be abstracted and scaled. Because there is no other Randall in the world, there is no standardized solution that can account for the behavior of Randall. Caregivers today rely on analog, “homemade” ways of sharing resident-specific knowledge—tips and tricks—with each other to make their work easier: notes on paper or whiteboards, or simply conversation. More can be done to make their experience-based, resident-specific knowledge readily available to them when it matters the most, often in care situations where residents easily become scared or agitated. The exciting potential of new technology is not that it makes standardized procedures quicker but that it can help support personalized care. In other words, caregivers need support knowing exactly which “buttons to push” with each resident and adapting the care accordingly—rather than support pushing the same buttons more and more quickly.

在很多情况下——当然不是全部，但很多情况下——人类智能仍然是应对情境挑战最有效的智能。这种效率并非基于可扩展的知识，而是基于对特定事物的深刻理解。

In many situations—certainly not all, but many—human intelligence is still the most efficient intelligence for addressing contextual challenges. It is an efficiency based not on scalable knowledge but on a profound understanding of the particular.

打破魔咒

Breaking the Spell

82岁的温德尔·贝里是美国的瑰宝。几十年来，他一直在肯塔基州亨利县的同一块土地上耕作，同时在母校肯塔基大学任教，并创作了四十多部小说、非小说和诗歌作品。20世纪80年代，他从自家门廊贝里在农场亲眼目睹了美国农业格局的变迁。1985年，他发表了一篇颇具预见性的文章，题为《人为何而生？》，为我们的“意义之旅”画上了完美的句号。

At age 82, Wendell Berry is an American treasure. He has been farming the same plot of land in Henry County, Kentucky, for several decades as well as teaching at his alma mater, the University of Kentucky, and has written over forty works of fiction, nonfiction, and poetry. In the 1980s, from his porch on his farm, Berry had a front-row seat to the transforming landscape of American agriculture. He wrote a prescient essay in 1985 entitled, “What Are People For?” that serves as a perfect coda to our sensemaking journey.

在文章中，贝里追溯了城市化进程以及美国乡村生活和社区空心化的发展。他呼吁关注经济学家对曾经在农田里劳作的大量人群的称呼：“永久失业者”。农业经济学家认为，这些人是效率最低的生产者：“如今，每天都有数百户农民失去农场，经济学家们仍在说，就像他们一直以来说的那样，这些人活该失败……而我们其他人却因为他们的失败而受益。”

In the essay, Berry tracks the development of increasing urbanization and the hollowing out of American rural life and community. He calls attention to the name economists give to the masses of people that used to work in the farmlands: the “permanently unemployable.” According to the agricultural economists, these were the least efficient producers: “[T]oday, with hundreds of farm families losing their farms every day, the economists are still saying, as they have said all along, that these people deserve to fail… and the rest of us are better off for their failure.”

这些人所掌握的知识和他们所做的劳动如今已被各种机械和化学品的组合所取代。有人称这种取代是农业科学的胜利，但贝里却不禁思考，这些如今被认为毫无用处的人将会面临怎样的命运。“淘汰人类难道现在是我们的社会目标吗？”他问道。

The knowledge these people held and the work that they did has now been eradicated by varying combinations of machinery and chemicals. Some called this displacement a triumph of agricultural science, but Berry wonders what is going to happen to all those people now deemed useless. “Is the obsolescence of human beings now our social goal?” he asks.

早在20世纪80年代，贝里的问题主要涉及农场的工作和知识。但35年后，我们或许会对几乎所有类型的人类劳动都提出同样的质疑。如今，白领工作——会计、放射科、法律、新闻和股票交易——面临的威胁与农业、驾驶和制造业等蓝领工作一样严重，甚至更甚。2013年，牛津大学的研究人员指出，未来20年内，机器可能会取代美国近一半的工作。

Back in the 1980s, Berry’s question referred primarily to the work and knowledge of the farm. But thirty-five years later we might say the same thing of almost every kind of human labor. Today it is white-collar jobs—accounting, radiology, law, journalism, and stock trading—that are endangered just as much as, if not more than, blue-collar jobs like farming, driving, and manufacturing. In 2013, Oxford University researchers argued that machines could perform almost half of U.S. jobs within the next twenty years.

这些以及其他类似的统计数据可能被夸大了，但毫无疑问，通用IT系统和机器人技术在我们今天和未来的生活中扮演着重要的角色。让我们的生活更美好、更有意义的进步总是值得庆祝的，但这些被取代的工作背后蕴含的智慧又将何去何从呢？

These and other such statistics might prove to be inflated, but there is no question that generalized IT systems and robotics play an important role in our lives today and in our futures. It is always worth celebrating developments that make our lives better and more meaningful, but what is to become of all the wisdom embedded in each and every one of these displaced jobs?

在我们日常生活中发生的细微而重要的举动中蕴藏着丰富的知识。而我们忽视这些知识，会对我们未来的福祉、生产力、安全以及人类自身精神的滋养造成巨大的风险。当我呼应温德尔·贝里提出的“人的意义是什么？”这个问题时，我并非建议我们摒弃算法和机器学习。这并非怀旧地呼吁我们回归过去，也并非试图躲藏在一个没有科技的孤岛上。当我问“人的意义是什么？”时，我并非在问一个非此即彼的问题。相反，我在提醒我们，被硬科学的魔力所冻结的文化根本算不上文化。当我们将技术及其解决方案置于一切之上时，我们就看不到人类智慧在最佳状态下所特有的敏捷性和细微之处。将技术置于我们之上，我们就停止了从其他来源整合数据。我们错失了源自整体思维而非优化的可持续效率。

There is a vast wealth of knowledge contained in the small but significant gestures that occur in our worlds every single day. And we dismiss that knowledge at great risk to our future well-being, productivity, safety, and the nourishment of our own human spirits. When I echo Wendell Berry in asking “What are people for?,” I am not suggesting that we do away with algorithms and machine learning. This is not a nostalgic call to return to the ways of the past, nor is it an attempt to hide away on a technology-free island. When I ask, “What are people for?,” I am not asking an either/or question. Instead, I am reminding us that a culture frozen under a spell of the hard sciences is not much of a culture at all. When we revere technology and its solutions above all else, we stop seeing the agility and nuance that characterize human intelligence at its best. By putting technology above us, we stop synthesizing data from other sources. We miss out on a sustainable efficiency that comes from holistic thinking, not from optimization.

对于意义建构而言，最重要的是，当我回应温德尔·贝里的问题时，我会问，为什么在西方世界——尤其是在美国——参与文化探究的想法已经变成了一种不必要的奢侈。为什么艺术、诗歌和音乐只是我们周末才会涉猎的爱好？为什么看戏剧或听音乐会是傲慢之人的特权，而读小说却浪费时间？艺术，我们假设，只适用于少数幸运儿。“这对底线有什么影响？”人们会问。写故事或唱歌的时间没有计费。严肃的诗歌和严谨的理论只有午餐时间的女士们才会讨论。依偎着读小说是我的时间，而不是高效的时间。

Most important for sensemaking, when I echo Wendell Berry’s question, I ask why, in the Western world—and in America in particular—the idea of engaging in cultural inquiry has become a notion of needless luxury. Why are art, poetry, and music something we only dabble in as a hobby on weekends? Why is watching a play or going to a concert a privilege for snotty people, and reading a novel a waste of time? Art, we assume, is only relevant for the lucky few. “What’s the impact to the bottom line?,” people ask. There are no billable hours from time spent on stories or songs. Serious poetry and rigorous theory are discussed only by ladies who lunch. Snuggling up with a novel is my time, not productive time.

然而，这个问题的答案却很明确：“人的意义是什么？”人是为了创造和诠释意义。人文学科领域正是这种努力的理想训​​练场。它为我们提供了两千多年的素材，作为我们的游乐场。是的——当然——人文学科的著作存在的意义是为了给我们带来愉悦和乐趣。但它们也是处理任何文化或组织中都存在的战略核心问题的实用工具：如何理解其他世界、习俗、意义和竞争市场。这些技能——意义建构的核心——正是永远无法外包的技能。机器学习永远无法获得对这些技能的洞察。这是因为它们需要视角，而算法根本没有视角。

And yet, the answer to the question is clear: “What are people for?” People are for making and interpreting meaning. And the realm of the humanities is an ideal training ground for such an endeavor. It offers us more than two thousand years of material as our playground. Yes—of course—works in the humanities exist to bring us delight and pleasure. But they are also helpful, practical tools for dealing with the core questions of strategy that exist in any culture or organization: how to understand other worlds, customs, meanings, and competitive markets. These skills—at the heart of sensemaking—are the very skills that can never be outsourced. Machine learning will never come close to achieving insights into them. This is because they require a perspective, and algorithms simply have no point of view.

当你聆听勃拉姆斯的音乐，或试图通过桑·豪斯简约却饱含深情的音乐理解20世纪30年代，或静静地聆听西尔维娅·普拉斯的诗歌时，你也在锻炼分析能力，这可以使你的初创企业、你的社会企业，甚至仅仅是你目前的处境变得更好。你可以让它变得更有趣，最重要的是，更真实。放下商学院肤浅的教条和自然科学对普遍原则的承诺。人文学科并非奢侈品；它们是你的竞争优势。

When you listen to Brahms, or try to understand the 1930s through the minimal but intensely soulful music of Son House, or sit down with the poetry of Sylvia Plath, you are also exercising analytical muscles that can make your start-up, your social enterprise, or simply your current position better. You can make it more fun and, above all else, more truthful. Let go of the shallow dogma of business schools and the promise of universal principles from the natural sciences. The humanities aren’t a luxury; they are your competitive advantage.

所以，在你嘲笑你的女儿想学习儒家哲学或瞧不起那些选择主修中世纪法国诗歌的人之前，请记住，你是很可能为这样的人工作。如果你们公司的董事长或总裁是历史专业出身，或者对斯拉夫语研究很感兴趣，又或者是一位古希腊语专家，那就不足为奇了。如果你的儿子真的热爱数学，一定要鼓励他进入STEM（科学、技术、工程和数学）的世界。但仅仅为了实用功能而强迫你自己或你的孩子放弃人文学科，转而学习自然科学，实际上并没有多大用处——无论对他们还是对我们社会的未来而言都是如此。我们当然需要大师级的化学工程师、数学家和软件开发人员，但我们也需要才华横溢的诗人、歌手、哲学家和人类学家。我们需要综合所有这些观点中的最佳思想，而不是试图优化我们作为个体或文化的整体。

So before you ridicule your daughter for wanting to study Confucian philosophy or look down on the people who choose to major in medieval French poetry, remember that you are quite likely working for such a person. It wouldn’t be surprising if the chairman of the board or the president who runs your company is a former history major or really into Slavic studies or an expert on ancient Greek. If your son is truly passionate about math, by all means encourage him to go into the world of STEM. But pushing yourself or your children away from the humanities and into natural science solely as a utility function isn’t actually very useful—either for them or for the future of our society. We certainly need masterful chemical engineers, mathematicians, and software developers, but we also need brilliant poets, singers, philosophers, and anthropologists. We need to synthesize the best ideas from all of these points of view, not attempt to optimize ourselves as individuals or as a culture.

因为当我们优化自己时，我们会忽视兰德尔——一个患有痴呆症的老人——和任何其他占据住宅空间的老人之间的重大差异。优化是关于计算资源以扩大其规模，而技术是规模大师。但它不必成为我们的主人。让我们将技术降级为同事，或者更好的是，训练有素的助手或跟班。当我们声称我们的空间是文化的唯一诠释者时，我们就可以解放自己，看清技术的本质：它只是武器库中的又一个工具。它可以帮助我们到达非凡的地方，但我们仍然需要弄清楚一旦到达那里该做什么。这个困境的答案只能通过我们受自身环境启发的掌控行为来解决。

For when we optimize ourselves, we lose sight of the meaningful differences between Randall—an old man with dementia—and any other old body taking up space in a residence. Optimization is about counting resources in an effort to scale them, and technology is the master of scale. But it need not be our master. Let us demote technology to a colleague or, better yet, a well-trained assistant or sidekick. When we claim our space as the sole interpreters of culture, we can emancipate ourselves and see technology for what it is: simply one more tool in the arsenal. It can help us to arrive at extraordinary places, but we still need to figure out what to do once we get there. The answers to that dilemma will only ever be solved by inspired acts of mastery that are drawn out of us by our context.

所以，今天当你开始新的一天时，我邀请你打破这个魔咒。环顾四周。聆听那些弥漫在文化中的情绪告诉你要惊叹的时刻。一款可以追踪你的数字足迹的新应用程序或一家医疗保健领域的初创公司可以为你提供实时症状诊断的魔力。这些都是巧妙的技巧，而且非常有用。但我们必须更加谨慎。史蒂夫·乔布斯曾经说过：“这将改变一切。”相反，试着用这句咒语打破魔咒：“这将改变一些事情。”毕竟，任何基础广泛的人文教育都会告诉我们，没有什么可以改变一切。无论是权力动态、家庭冲突、伟大帝国的兴衰、我们与神的关系，还是我们坠入爱河的经历，人文学科提供的思想、故事和艺术作品始终是相关的。我们人类对爱、知识、目标和卓越的渴望永远不会是新的，这正是它永远不会过时的原因。

So when you go about your day today, I invite you to break the spell. Look around you. Listen for the moments when the pervasive mood of the culture is telling you to marvel at the magic of a new app that can track your digital footprints or a start-up in the health care space that can give you a real-time diagnosis for your symptoms. These are neat tricks—and useful ones at that. But we must remain more circumspect. Steve Jobs used to say, “This will change everything.” Instead, try breaking the spell with this mantra: “This will change some things.” After all, any broad-based education in the humanities shows us that nothing changes everything. Whether it is power dynamics, family strife, the rise and fall of great empires, our relationship to the gods, or our experience of falling in love, the ideas and stories and artistic works on offer in the humanities are always relevant. Our own human yearning for love, for knowledge, for purpose, and for excellence is never new, which is precisely why it never gets old.

一旦魔咒破除，就用全新的眼光环顾世界。你可能会发现，每天在我们的街道、家中和学校里，都会发生一些非凡的事情。它就像哈勃太空望远镜或谷歌设计的围棋算法一样值得我们惊叹。今天，哪怕只是片刻，也请花点时间惊叹乔治·索罗斯如何能够将市场知识融入自己的身体。或者想想比亚克·英格尔斯，他让环境的特殊性——而不是惯例——来决定他建筑的形状。想想希拉·希恩，她能够在几秒钟内判断一个挤满几十个几乎陌生的人的房间如何才能最好地学习。欣赏玛格丽特·维斯塔格，以及她如何在庞大的官僚机构中为人类的接触点开辟空间。惊叹于克里斯·沃斯，以及他解读谈判信息中怀疑、机会、操纵和愤怒的能力。尽你所能去品味凯茜·科里森 (Cathy Corison) 的葡萄酒——当您品尝科里森赤霞珠时，您实际上品尝的是科里森所信仰的一切。您品尝的是一个人在一片土地上追求伟大的呼唤。

Once the spell is broken, look around the world with fresh eyes. You might discover something extraordinary happening on our streets, in our homes, and at our schools every day. It is just as deserving of our wonder as the Hubble spacecraft or a Google-designed Go-playing algorithm. Today, if just for a moment, take some time to marvel at the way George Soros can experience knowledge about the market in his body. Or think about Bjarke Ingels, who allows contextual specificities—not conventions—to determine the shape of his buildings. Consider Sheila Heen, who is able to assess in a matter of seconds how a room filled with dozens of near strangers will best learn. Appreciate Margrethe Vestager and the ways she carves out space for human touchpoints within the hulking beasts of bureaucracy. Wonder at Chris Voss and his ability to decode shades of doubt, opportunity, manipulation, and anger within a message of negotiation. And make your best effort to taste the wine of Cathy Corison—for when you taste a Corison Cabernet, you are really tasting everything that Corison believes in. You are tasting one person’s call to greatness within the context of a single plot of dirt.

赞美这些以及其他我们这个世界的大师们。然后更仔细地观察。你会发现，一种更谦逊的魔力就在我们身边。你或许会看到一位老师在操场上用一个手势就瞬间营造出凝聚力和秩序感。或许你会见证一位技艺精湛的经理人如何掌控团队的节奏。这一切或许就像拿起一本来自过去的伟大小说，全心全意地进入另一个世界，跨越时空与另一个人建立联系一样简单。

Celebrate these and other masters of our world. And then look even closer. You will see magic of a more humble sort is all around us. You might see a schoolteacher create immediate cohesion and structure on the playground in a single gesture. Maybe you will bear witness to the work of a skilled manager taking the temperature of the team. It might be as simple as picking up a great novel from the past and entering—with full heart and head—into another world, connecting with another human across time and space.

有太多的事情值得我们惊叹——从我们最伟大的运动员、歌手、政治家和商业领袖的非凡成就——一直到知道轻轻触摸病人手臂的护理人员的精湛技艺。

There is so much to marvel at—from the most extraordinary heights of our greatest athletes, singers, politicians, and business leaders—right down to the mastery of a caregiver who knows to touch her patient’s arm ever so gently.

“那个声音一定是您学生在走廊里的声音，约翰逊先生。”她在恰当的时机以恰当的方式说出了恰当的话，兰德尔终于能够在漫长的一天结束后平静下来，找到内心的平静。

“That noise must be the sound of your students in the hallway, Mr. Johnson.” She says just the right thing at just the right moment in just the right way, and Randall is able to calm down and find peace at the end of the long day.

人是用来做什么的？算法能做很多事，但它们永远不会真正关心别人。人是用来关爱别人的。

What are people for? Algorithms can do many things, but they will never actually give a damn. People are for caring.

Sources

引言：人的因素

Introduction: The Human Factor

关于人文学科资助减少的讨论得到了许多资料的支持，其中包括：美国艺术与科学学院 2013 年发布的一份两党联合报告《问题的核心：人文和社会科学如何造就一个充满活力、竞争力强且安全的国家》；哈佛大学 2013 年的一项研究《哈佛学院的艺术与人文学科教学：绘制未来》；以及《人文指标：美国艺术与科学学院的一个项目》，最新更新于 2016 年 10 月。

The discussion around the decline of funding for the humanities was supported by a number of sources including: “The Heart of the Matter: The Humanities and Social Sciences for a Vibrant, Competitive, and Secure Nation,” a 2013 bipartisan report put out by the American Academy of Arts and Sciences; “The Teaching of the Arts and Humanities at Harvard College: Mapping the Future,” a study by Harvard University from 2013; and “Humanities Indicators: A Project of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences,” last updated in October 2016.

我参考了2012 年 12 月《商业内幕》杂志的文章《30 位拥有‘软’大学专业却取得巨大成功的人》，整理出了拥有人文学科背景的金融、媒体或政策领域领袖名单。

I used the Business Insider article “30 People with ‘Soft’ College Majors Who Became Extremely Successful” from December 2012 to compile the list of leaders in finance, media, or policy with background in the humanities.

第一章：理解世界

Chapter One: Making Sense of the World

爱丽丝·门罗的名言——“就好像那些在我们心中根深蒂固、最私密、最独特的倾向，随着盛行的风而来，寻找任何可能的着陆点，任何地方都欢迎。”——这是她1990 年在《纽约客》上发表的小说《我青春的朋友》 。

The Alice Munro quote—“It’s as if tendencies that seem most deeply rooted in our minds, most private and singular, have come in as spores on the prevailing wind, looking for any likely place to land, any welcome.”—is from her story “Friend of My Youth,” published in the New Yorker in 1990.

第三章：文化而非个人

Chapter Three: Culture—Not Individuals

妮可·波伦蒂尔 (Nicole Pollentier) 的引言取自我们在 2015 年和 2016 年的几次谈话。经她许可，我们收录了她诗歌《在神经可塑性城市中建造道路》中的一节。

Nicole Pollentier’s quotes are taken from several of our conversations in 2015 and 2016. The stanza from her poem “building pathways in the neuroplastic city” is included with her permission.

第四章：厚数据——不仅仅是薄数据

Chapter Four: Thick Data—Not Just Thin Data

三位交易员的故事：这些故事源于我与罗伯特·约翰逊、克里斯·卡纳万以及其他几位曾在索罗斯基金与乔治·索罗斯共事的交易员的对话。我还引用了乔治·索罗斯1987年出版的《金融炼金术》一书中的引言和观点，以及《华尔街日报》和《纽约时报》的报道。塞巴斯蒂安·马拉比2010年出版的关于对冲基金的优秀著作《金钱胜过上帝》（More Money Than God）对“黑色星期三”和“黑色星期一”的一些市场细节提供了宝贵的资源。

The Story of the Three Traders: I pulled these narratives together from my conversations with Robert Johnson, Chris Canavan, and a handful of other traders who worked with George Soros at the Soros Fund. I also used quotes and ideas from George Soros’s 1987 book The Alchemy of Finance, as well as reporting from the Wall Street Journal and the New York Times. Sebastian Mallaby’s excellent 2010 book about hedge funds, More Money Than God, was an invaluable resource for some of the market details regarding “Black Wednesday” and “Black Monday.”

第五章：大草原——不是动物园

Chapter Five: The Savannah—Not the Zoo

胡塞尔、海德格尔与杏子鸡尾酒的故事：西蒙娜·德·波伏娃在她1962年的回忆录《人生的黄金时代》中描述了这个故事。莎拉·贝克韦尔2016年出版的引人入胜的著作《在存在主义咖啡馆：自由、存在与杏子鸡尾酒》中也描述了这次邂逅，以及胡塞尔的“现象学幼儿园”课程。

Husserl, Heidegger, and the Story of the Apricot Cocktail: Simone de Beauvoir describes this story in her 1962 memoir The Prime of Life. There is also a description of this encounter—as well as of Husserl’s “phenomenological kindergarten” classes—in Sarah Bakewell’s fascinating 2016 book At the Existentialist Café: Freedom, Being, and Apricot Cocktails.

第六章：创造力——而非制造

Chapter Six: Creativity—Not Manufacturing

我从史蒂文·沃茨 (Steven Watts) 的《人民大亨：亨利·福特与美国世纪》 (2005)中汲取灵感，在本章开头描述了亨利·福特作为发明家和工程师的早期经历。

I took inspiration from Steven Watts’s The People’s Tycoon: Henry Ford and the American Century (2005) for the descriptions of Henry Ford’s early days as an inventor and engineer at the opening of the chapter.

罗伯特·I·萨顿 (Robert I. Sutton) 的《行之有效的奇思妙想：如何打造一家创意公司》 (2001) 和克里斯·巴雷斯-布朗 (Chris Baréz-Brown) 的《如何拥有超棒的创意：撼动你的事业，撼动你的生活》(2008) 只是当今商业领域中此类“创意话语”无数例子中的两个。

Robert I. Sutton’s Weird Ideas That Work: How to Build a Creative Company (2001), and Chris Baréz-Brown’s How to Have Kick-Ass Ideas: Shake Up Your Business, Shake Up Your Life (2008), are just two of countless examples of this type of “creative discourse” in business today.

第七章：北极星——不是 GPS

Chapter Seven: The North Star—Not the GPS

2015 年和 2016 年，我与 Sheila Heen、Margrethe Vestager、Chris Voss 和 Cathy Corison 共度了一段时光，我利用我们的对话和对他们工作的报道，创作出了这些最精妙的意义建构简介。

I spent time with Sheila Heen, Margrethe Vestager, Chris Voss, and Cathy Corison in 2015 and 2016 and I used our conversations and reporting on their work to create these profiles of sensemaking at its most masterful.
